ench Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2010 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|QF]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2011 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2012 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2013 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2014 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2015 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| A\n| style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2017 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|QF]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2018 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2019 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| A\n|0 / 12\n|21\u201312\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=21|lost=12}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]\n|[[2006 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles Qualifying|Q1]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2007 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2010 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2011 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2012 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2014 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2015 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2016 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2017 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2018 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2019 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| A\n|0 / 13\n|25\u201313\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=25|lost=13}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]\n| A\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2007 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#D8BFD8;\"|[[2009 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|F]]\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"|[[2010 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|SF]]\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"|[[2011 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|SF]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2012 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2013 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#D8BFD8;\"|[[2014 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|F]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2015 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"|[[2016 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|SF]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2017 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2018 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2019 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| A\n|0 / 13\n|38\u201313\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=38|lost=13}}\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background:#efefef;\"\n|style=text-align:left|Win\u2013Loss\n|0\u20130\n|2\u20133\n|10\u20134\n|13\u20134\n|15\u20134\n|{{nowrap|15\u20134}}\n|6\u20134\n|7\u20134\n|11\u20134\n|6\u20134\n|5\u20133\n|10\u20134\n|12\u20133\n|6\u20134\n|2\u20131\n|{{nowrap|1 / 51}}\n|{{nowrap|120\u201350}}\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=120|lost=50}}\n|}\n\n===Doubles===\n{|class=wikitable style=text-align:center;\n|-\n!Tournament!![[2007 WTA Tour|2007]]!![[2008 WTA Tour|2008]]!![[2009 WTA Tour|2009]]!![[2010 WTA Tour|2010]]!!SR!!W\u2013L!!Win%\n|-\n|align=left| [[Australian Open]]\n| A\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2010 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n|0 / 3\n|1\u20133\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=1|lost=3|integer=yes}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[French Open]]\n| A\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 French Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 French Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2010 French Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n|0 / 3\n|1\u20133\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=1|lost=3|integer=yes}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]\n| A\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2010 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n|0 / 3\n|2\u20133\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=2|lost=3|integer=yes}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2007 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2010 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n|0 / 4\n|4\u20134\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=4|lost=4|integer=yes}}\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background:#efefef;\"\n|style=text-align:left|Win\u2013Loss\n|0\u20131\n|2\u20134\n|3\u20134\n|3\u20134\n|0 / 13\n|8\u201313\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=8|lost=13}}\n|}\n\n==Achievements==\n{{Main|List of career achievements by Caroline Wozniacki}}\n:{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Time span\n!Selected records\n!Players matched\n!{{Tooltip|Ref|References}}\n|-\n|29 January 2012 \u2013 29 January 2018\n|The longest time for a female player to return to [[List of WTA number 1 ranked tennis players|world No. 1]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|<ref name=\"WTA Tennis\"/>\n|-\n|2008\u20132011\n|4 [[Connecticut Open (tennis)|Connecticut Open]] titles\n|[[Steffi Graf]]<br/>[[Venus Williams]]\n|\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Denmark|Tennis}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.carolinewozniacki.com}}\n* {{WTA}}\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{Fed Cup player}}\n* {{IOC profile|caroline-wozniacki}}\n* {{SR/Olympics profile|wo/caroline-wozniacki-1}}\n* {{IMDb name|3226044}}\n\n{{Caroline Wozniacki}}\n{{Caroline Wozniacki start boxes}}\n{{Tennis World Number Ones (women)}}\n{{Australian Open women's singles champions}}\n{{Wimbledon girls' singles champions}}\n{{WTA Year-End Championships winners}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wozniacki, Caroline}}\n[[Category:Caroline Wozniacki| ]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian Open (tennis) champions]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriates in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Danish female tennis players]]\n[[Category:Danish people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in girls' singles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in women's singles]]\n[[Category:Hopman Cup competitors]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Order of the Dannebrog]]\n[[Category:Olympic tennis players of Denmark]]\n[[Category:People from Monte Carlo]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Odense]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon junior champions]]\n[[Category:World No. 1 tennis players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Danish tennis player}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                        = Caroline Wozniacki\n|image                       = Caroline Wozniacki (35449695422).jpg\n|caption                     = Wozniacki at the 2017 Eastbourne International\n|country                     = {{DEN}}\n|residence                   = [[Fisher Island]], United States<br/>[[Odense]], Denmark<br/>[[Monte Carlo]], Monaco<br/>[[New York City|New York]], United States\n|birth_date                  = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1990|7|11}}<ref name=\"WTAStats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/players/player/12631/title/caroline-wozniacki|title=Caroline Wozniacki Statistics|publisher=WTA Tour|accessdate=26 August 2013}}</ref>\n|birth_place                 = [[Odense]], Denmark\n|height                      = {{height|m=1.75|precision=0}}<ref name=\"WTAStats\"/>\n|turnedpro                   = 18 July 2005<ref name=WTAStats/>\n|retired                     = 24 January 2020\n|plays                       = Right-handed (two-handed backhand)<ref name=WTAStats/>\n|coach                       = Piotr Wo\u017aniacki (2004\u20132020)\n|careerprizemoney            = [[US$]] 34,233,415\n* [[WTA Tour records#WTA career prize money leaders|5th in all-time rankings]]\n|website                     = {{url|carolinewozniacki.com}}\n|singlesrecord               = {{tennis record|won=635|lost=264}}\n|singlestitles               = 30\n|highestsinglesranking       = [[List of WTA number 1 ranked tennis players|No. '''1''']] (11 October 2010)\n|AustralianOpenresult        = '''W''' ([[2018 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2018]])\n|FrenchOpenresult            = QF ([[2010 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2010]], [[2017 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2017]])\n|Wimbledonresult             = 4R ([[2009 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2009]], [[2010 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2010]], [[2011 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2011]], [[2014 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2014]], [[2015 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2015]], [[2017 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2017]])\n|USOpenresult                = F ([[2009 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2009]], [[2014 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2014]])\n|Othertournaments            = yes\n|WTAChampionshipsresult      = '''W''' ([[2017 WTA Finals|2017]])\n|Olympicsresult              = QF ([[Tennis at the 2012 Summer Olympics \u2013 Women's singles|2012]])\n|doublesrecord               = {{tennis record|won=36|lost=55}}\n|doublestitles               = 2\n|highestdoublesranking       = No. 52 (14 September 2009)\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult = 2R ([[2008 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2008]])\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult     = 2R ([[2010 French Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2010]])\n|WimbledonDoublesresult      = 2R ([[2009 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Doubles|2009]], [[2010 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Doubles|2010]])\n|USOpenDoublesresult         = 3R ([[2009 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2009]])\n}}\n\n'''Caroline Wozniacki''' [[Order of the Dannebrog|(R)]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.tv2.dk/tennis/2018-05-07-wozniacki-far-ridderkorset-af-dannebrogordenen|title=Wozniacki f\u00e5r ridderkorset af Dannebrogordenen|date=7 May 2018|publisher=}}</ref> ({{IPA-da|k\u02b0a\u0281o\u02c8li\u02d0n\u0259 v\u0252sni\u02c8a\u02d0k\u02b0i|lang}}; {{IPA-pl|v\u0254\u0291\u02c8\u0272atsk\u02b2i|lang}};{{efn|name=Polish pronunciation|''Karolina Wo\u017aniacka'' ({{IPA-pl|kar\u0254\u02c8l\u02b2ina v\u0254\u0291\u02c8\u0272atska|lang}}), the Polish form of her name, is often used by Polish-language sources.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rp.pl/artykul/481247.html?print=tak |title=Tata uczy\u0142 tenisa i Chopina |last=Rawa |first=Krzystof |date=17 May 2010 |accessdate=23 June 2014 |language=Polish |trans-title=Dad Taught Tennis and Chopin}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.se.pl/inne-sporty/tenis/karolina-wozniacka-w-nagiej-sesji-zobacz-ponetne-fotki-tenisistki-zdjecia-wideo_779219.html|title=Karolina Wo\u017aniacka w nagiej sesji! Zobacz pon\u0119tne fotki tenisistki [Zdj\u0119cia + Wideo]|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.tvn24.pl/tenis,115/karolina-wozniacka-nago-w-sesji-dla-sports-illustrated,619714.html|title=Na ciele Karoliny tylko farba. Wo\u017aniacka w odwa\u017cnej sesji|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportowefakty.wp.pl/tenis/caroline-wozniacki|title=Karolina Wo\u017aniacka \u2013 Tenis \u2013 WP SportoweFakty|first=Grupa Wirtualna|last=Polska|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazetawroclawska.pl/artykul/3747605,karolina-wozniacka-w-bikini-goraca-sesja-tenisistki-dla-sports-ilustrated-zobacz-zdjecia-i-film,id,t.html|title=Karolina Wo\u017aniacka w bikini. Gor\u0105ca sesja tenisistki dla Sports Illustrated (Zobacz Zdj\u0119cia i Film)|first=MH|last=TVN/X-news|publisher=|date=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://warszawa.naszemiasto.pl/artykul/karolina-wozniacka-ubrana-w-farbe-zobacz-zmyslowa-sesje,3652482,artgal,t,id,tm.html|title=Karolina Wo\u017aniacka ubrana w ... farb\u0119! Zobacz zmys\u0142ow\u0105 sesj\u0119 tenisistki [Zdj\u0119cia]|date=19 February 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fakt.pl/karolina-wozniacka|title=Karolina Wo\u017aniacka|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[https://forvo.com/word/karolina_wo%C5%BAniacka/#pl \"Karolina Wo\u017aniacka pronunciation: How to pronounce Karolina Wo\u017aniacka in Polish\"] Forvo. Retrieved 30 December 2016.</ref>}} born 11 July 1990) is a [[Denmark|Danish]] former professional [[tennis]] player<!-- Her Polish descent is mentioned later. [[Wikipedia:Manual of Style (biographies)#Opening paragraph]] is against saying it here. -->. She reached [[List of WTA number 1 ranked tennis players|world No. 1]] in singles,<ref>{{cite web|title=Notes & Netcords: January 16, 2012|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/page/NotesAndNetcords/0,,12781,00.html|publisher=WTA Tour|accessdate=16 January 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117193840/http://www.wtatennis.com/page/NotesAndNetcords/0%2C%2C12781%2C00.html|archivedate=17 January 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"Piers Newberry\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/tennis/42844093|title=Australian Open: Caroline Wozniacki beats Simona Halep to win first Grand Slam title|work=BBC Sport|author=Piers Newberry|date=27 January 2018}}</ref> the 20th in the [[Open Era]], and the first woman from a Scandinavian country to hold the top ranking position.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wtatennis.com/gallery/20101007/wozniackis-big-day-the-gallery_2256674_2178185?imageNo=8#picture |title=Wozniacki's Big Day \u2013 The Gallery |date=7 October 2010 |accessdate=11 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718202737/http://www.wtatennis.com/gallery/20101007/wozniackis-big-day-the-gallery_2256674_2178185?imageNo=8 |archivedate=18 July 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> She finished on top of the rankings in both 2010 and 2011.\n\nShe won 30 [[Caroline Wozniacki career statistics#Singles|WTA singles titles]], including six in 2010 and 2011, the most in a year by a WTA player from 2008\u20132011.<ref>{{cite web|title=Stats Corner: Best Of The Best|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/20101215/stats-corner-best-of-the-best_2256076_2245421|publisher=WTA Tour|date=15 December 2010|accessdate=11 April 2011}}</ref> She was runner-up at the [[2009 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2009 US Open]] and the [[2010 WTA Tour Championships]] to [[Kim Clijsters]], and at the [[2014 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2014 US Open]] to [[Serena Williams]]. She won the [[2006 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Singles|2006 Wimbledon girls' singles]] title and also holds two WTA titles in doubles. In 2008, Wozniacki won the title of WTA Newcomer of the Year. In 2017, she won the season-ending [[WTA Finals]] in Singapore for the first time in her career. Wozniacki won her maiden Grand Slam title at the [[2018 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2018 Australian Open]] and returned to the No. 1 ranking on 29 January 2018.\n\nOn 6 December 2019, Wozniacki announced that she would retire from professional tennis following the [[2020 Australian Open]], held in January.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/tennis/news/caroline-wozniacki-29-says-she-will-retire-following-2020-australian-open/|title=Caroline Wozniacki, 29, says she will retire following 2020 Australian Open|last=Bengel|first=Chris|date=6 December 2019|work=CBS Sports|access-date=6 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWozniacki was born in Odense, Denmark, the daughter of Polish<ref>{{cite news|title=\u20ac20m smiles: Rory McIlroy and tennis ace Caroline Wozniacki|url=http://www.independent.ie/lifestyle/euro20m-smiles-rory-mcilroy-and-tennis-ace-caroline-wozniacki-2926727.html |date=5 November 2011 |accessdate=16 December 2011|work=Irish Independent}}</ref> immigrants, Piotr Wo\u017aniacki and Anna.<ref name=\"aboutCaroline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.carolinewozniacki.dk/?page_id=2|title=About Caro|work=Caroline Wozniacki Official Web site|accessdate=31 March 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527234405/http://www.carolinewozniacki.dk/?page_id=2|archivedate=27 May 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Anna played on the [[Poland women's national volleyball team|Polish women's national volleyball team]],<ref name=\"WTAbio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/page/Player/Info/0,,12781~12631,00.html|title= Caroline Wozniacki| publisher=WTA Tour |accessdate=11 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110307112329/http://www.wtatennis.com/player/caroline-wozniacki_2257889_12631 |archivedate=7 March 2011 | url-status=dead}}</ref> and Piotr played professional football. The couple moved to Denmark when Piotr signed for the Danish football club [[Boldklubben 1909]].<ref name=\"aboutCaroline\"/><ref name=\"Wimbledon2009Women'sDarkHorse\">{{cite web|url=http://optimistworld.com/Dane-Caroline-Wozniacki-Wimbledon-2009-Women-Dark-Horse |title=Dane Caroline Wozniacki is the Wimbledon 2009 Women's Dark Horse |publisher=The Optimist |accessdate=1 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090701003444/http://optimistworld.com/Dane-Caroline-Wozniacki-Wimbledon-2009-Women-Dark-Horse/ |archivedate= 1 July 2009 |df= }}</ref> Her older brother, [[Patrik Wozniacki]], is a former professional footballer in Denmark.<ref name=\"WTAbio\"/>\n\n==Playing style, coaches and sponsors==\n[[File:Caroline Wozniacki 01.jpg|thumb|right|Wozniacki won her first WTA title at Nordic Light Open Stockholm 2008]]\nWozniacki's playing style centres on \"the defensive aspects of tennis with her anticipation, movement, agility, footwork and speed all first-rate and key parts of her game.\" She also anticipates serves with aggressive footwork.<ref>[http://www.footfault.net/2010/08/06/caroline-wozniacki-an-analysis/ Caroline Wozniacki: An Analysis] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131024071053/http://www.footfault.net/2010/08/06/caroline-wozniacki-an-analysis/ |date=24 October 2013 }}. 6 August 2010.</ref> Her two-handed backhand is one of her best weapons as she is capable of turning defence into offence, most notably the backhand down-the-line. Her defensive playing style had her contemporaries label her a counter-puncher;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ontennis.com/news/viewpoint-wozniacki-cant-just-be-counter-puncher |title=Viewpoint: Wozniacki can't just be counter-puncher |last=Martin|first=James |date=22 March 2010 |work=[[Tennis (magazine)|Tennis]] |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> sometimes, she was referred to as a [[Pusher (tennis)|pusher]] by critics. Following her retirement, [[The Guardian]] described Wozniacki as \"one of the most defensive players ever to reach No. 1\", noting her use of the moonball, and stated that her main strengths were her mental fortitude and competitive drive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2019/dec/07/defiant-caroline-wozniacki-will-end-turbulent-career-with-head-held-high|title=Wozniacki wants last hurrah after bravery loses out to brittleness|last=Carayol|first=Tumaini|date=7 December 2019|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> Despite Wozniacki's excellent footwork and anticipation, and a strong backhand, especially down the line, Wozniacki's forehand remained a weakness throughout her career, due to its lack of depth, power and speed. As noted in the Guardian, \"people questioned why her serve could scale 118mph and yet her forehand could not crack open an egg\".\n\nWozniacki's father, Piotr, was her primary coach since she was 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tennis/wozniacki-is-happy-to-keep-it-in-the-family-7768762.html |title=Wozniacki is happy to keep it in the family |date=20 May 2012 |work=The Independent |first=Paul |last=Newman |accessdate=8 September 2014 }}</ref> Throughout the years, she was coached by [[Sven Groeneveld]] through the Adidas Player Development Program.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/14/sports/tennis/caroline-wozniacki-a-former-no-1-is-seeking-stability.html?pagewanted=all |title=Former No. 1 Turns to Father for Help |newspaper=The New York Times |date=13 January 2013 |first=Christopher |last=Clarey |accessdate=8 September 2014 }}</ref> She was briefly coached by Ricardo Sanchez and [[Thomas Johansson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/tennis/french-open-caroline-wozniacki-confident-as-new-coach-joins-team-1-2331345 |title=French Open: Caroline Wozniacki confident as new coach joins team |work=The Scotsman |date=1 June 2012 |accessdate=8 September 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tennis.com/pro-game/2012/10/report-wozniacki-thomas-johansson-split/39968/#.VA1MdfldUrU |title=Report: Wozniacki, Thomas Johansson split |publisher=Tennis.com |date=31 October 2012 |first=Matt |last=Cronin |accessdate=8 September 2014 }}</ref> In October 2013, she hired [[Thomas H\u00f6gstedt]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/tennis/beyond-baseline/2013/10/31/caroline-wozniacki-hires-thomas-hogstedt-as-coach |title=Caroline Wozniacki hires Thomas Hogstedt as her coach |date=31 October 2013 |work=Sports Illustrated |first=Courtney |last=Nguyen |accessdate=8 September 2014 }}</ref> but parted ways in January 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/03/11/us-tennis-wozniacki-idUSBREA2A20J20140311 |title=Wozniacki postpones search for coach as dad rejoins team |date=11 March 2014 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=8 September 2014 }}</ref> In the same month, she hired [[Michael Mortensen]], but cut ties with him in March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/tennis/beyond-baseline/2014/03/13/caroline-wozniacki-splits-with-michael-mortensen |title=Report: Caroline Wozniacki splits with coach Michael Mortensen |work=Sports Illustrated |date=13 March 2014 |first=Courtney |last=Nguyen |accessdate=8 September 2014 }}</ref> Since then, Wozniacki decided to be coached again by her father Piotr for the rest of her career.{{citation needed|date=November 2018}}\n\nIn 2009, Wozniacki signed on to become an endorser for the line of tennis apparel designed by [[Stella McCartney]] for [[Adidas]]. She wore her first 'Adidas by Stella McCartney' tennis dress at the [[2009 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2009 US Open]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wmagazine.com/fashion/2009/07/caroline-wozniacki-keep-an-eye/|title=Keep your eye on this hot shot |date=28 July 2009|work=the daily W|publisher=[[W (magazine)|W]] |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref> She currently has partnership agreements with [[Babolat]], [[Rolex]], Adidas, [[USANA]], [[The Players' Tribune]] and Mundipharma.<ref>{{cite web|title=Caroline Wozniacki \u2013 Official Website|url=http://carolinewozniacki.com/partners/}}</ref> On 20 December 2010, she signed a three-year deal to endorse [[Turkish Airlines]]' business class service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/page/OffCourtNews/Read/0,,12781~2248577,00.html|title=WTA {{!}} Off-Court News {{!}} Off-Court News {{!}} Caro & Turkish Airlines|last=|first=|date=2011-04-08|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110408000904/http://www.wtatennis.com/page/OffCourtNews/Read/0,,12781~2248577,00.html|archive-date=2011-04-08|url-status=|access-date=2018-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntvmsnbc.com/id/25162507/|title=THY'yi Caroline u\u00e7uracak|language=tr|publisher=ntvmsnbc|accessdate=20 December 2010}}</ref> In 2012, Wozniacki became an endorser of Compeed BlisterPatch. At the end of 2013 she switched her racquet sponsorship from Yonex back to her long-time partner Babolat. In 2015, Wozniacki became an endorser of [[Godiva Chocolatier]].<ref>[http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/godiva-chocolatier-announces-partnership-with-tennis-star-caroline-wozniacki-300034065.html GODIVA Chocolatier Announces Partnership With Tennis Star Caroline Wozniacki] 11 February 2015, PRNewswire, retrieved 20 February 2015<!-- archived at web.archive.org --></ref> In 2018 she entered into a partnership with Lympo, a healthy lifestyle motivation app.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://lympo.com/news/tennis-superstar-wozniacki-becomes-lympo-app-ambassador|title=Lympo - Health is your biggest reward|website=Tennis superstar wozniacki becomes lympo app ambassador.|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180420074034/https://lympo.com/news/tennis-superstar-wozniacki-becomes-lympo-app-ambassador|archive-date=20 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the June 2011 edition of SportsPro, Wozniacki is the world's ninth-most marketable athlete.<ref>{{cite web|last=Love|first=Tom|title=The World's 50 Most Marketable Athletes|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/notes_and_insights/the_worlds_9th_most_marketable_athlete_-_caroline_wozniacki/|publisher=SportsPro|date=27 May 2011|accessdate=27 May 2011}}</ref> According to ''Forbes'' in 2011, Wozniacki was the second-highest-earning female athlete in the world.<ref>{{cite news|last=Badenhausen|first=Kurt|title=The Highest-Paid Female Athletes|url=https://blogs.forbes.com/kurtbadenhausen/2011/08/01/the-highest-paid-female-athletes/|work=Forbes|date=1 August 2011|accessdate=3 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Junior career==\nWozniacki had a career-high junior ranking of No. 2 in the world. She made her debut on the [[ITF Junior Circuit]],  the premier 18-and-under junior tour that is run by the [[International Tennis Federation]] (ITF), in October 2003 at 13 years and 3 months old. During her first month, she entered two Grade 5 events in Denmark, the lowest-level tournament on the tour. Wozniacki reached the final at both singles events, winning the second over compatriot [[Hanne Skak Jensen]]. With this success, she moved up to Grade 3 and Grade 4 tournaments, winning her first four singles events of 2004. Her win streak of five tournaments and 27 matches came to an end in April with a semifinal loss to [[Latisha Chan]] at the International Juniors Championships in Manila, her first event outside of Scandinavia as well as her first Grade 1 event. From this point on, Wozniacki only competed in Grade A and Grade 1 events, the two highest-level tournaments. She made her Grade A debut at [[2004 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] before turning 14, losing her first main draw match. Towards the end of the year, Wozniacki won her first Grade A title at the [[Osaka Mayor's Cup]].<ref name=\"itf-junior-singles-activity\">{{cite web |title=Caroline Wozniacki Juniors Singles Activity |url=https://www.itftennis.com/en/players/caroline-wozniacki/800254714/den/jt/s/activity |publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]] |accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"itf-junior-doubles-activity\">{{cite web |title=Caroline Wozniacki Juniors Singles Activity |url=https://www.itftennis.com/en/players/caroline-wozniacki/800254714/den/jt/d/activity |publisher=[[International Tennis Federation]] |accessdate=21 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki won several junior tournaments in 2005, including the [[Dunlop Orange Bowl|Orange Bowl tennis championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itftennis.com/juniors/news/newsarticle.asp?articleid=16044 |title=Roshardt and Wozniacki Claim Orange Bowl Title |author=Tim Curry |date=12 December 2005 |publisher=ITFtennis.com |accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref> She made her debut on the [[WTA Tour]] at Cincinnati's [[Cincinnati Women's Open|Western & Southern Financial Group Women's Open]] on 19 July 2005, losing to the top-seeded and eventual champion [[Patty Schnyder]] in the first round. In the [[Nordea Nordic Light Open]], her other WTA tournament of the year, she lost to [[Martina Such\u00e1]] in the first round.\n\n[[File:Carolinewozniacki.jpg|thumb|left|Wozniacki during the [[2006 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Singles|Wimbledon junior final]]]]\nIn 2006 she was the top seed at the [[2006 Australian Open|Australian Open]] ([[2006 Australian Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|junior girls' singles]]), but lost the final to eighth-seeded [[Anastasia Pavlyuchenkova]]. She was seeded second with partner [[Anna Tatishvili]] in the doubles tournament, but the pair was knocked out in the semifinals by the French-Italian pair of [[Aliz\u00e9 Cornet]] and [[Corinna Dentoni]], who were seeded 8th. In February at the [[2006 Regions Morgan Keegan Championships and the Cellular South Cup|Memphis]], she reached her first WTA Tour quarterfinal, beating [[Kristina Brandi]] and [[Ashley Harkleroad]] before losing to third-seeded [[Sofia Arvidsson]] of Sweden. Before [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]] Wozniacki won the [[Tradition-ICAP Liverpool International|Liverpool International Tennis Tournament]], an exhibition tournament, beating Ashley Harkleroad in the final.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liverpooltennis.co.uk//event-guide/tournament-history/liverpool-international-tennis-tournament-2006.phuse |title=Liverpool International Tennis Tournament 2006 |author=Ian Hargraves |work=Tournament website |accessdate=14 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724021715/http://www.liverpooltennis.co.uk//event-guide/tournament-history/liverpool-international-tennis-tournament-2006.phuse |archivedate=24 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Later that year she was given a wildcard to the qualifying draw at [[2006 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], where she was beaten in the first round by [[Miho Saeki]]. However, Wozniacki went on to win the [[2006 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Girls' Singles|Wimbledon girls' singles tournament]], beating [[Slovakia|Slovak]] [[Magdal\u00e9na Ryb\u00e1rikov\u00e1]] in the finals. In August, she reached another WTA Tour quarterfinal, this time at the [[Nordea Nordic Light Open]] in Stockholm. She defeated top-100 players [[Iveta Bene\u0161ov\u00e1]] and [[Eleni Daniilidou]], then lost to eventual champion and third-seeded [[Zheng Jie]].\n\nWozniacki was seeded second in the [[2006 US Open \u2013 Girls' Singles|US Open girls' singles]]. In the first round, she won the first set against Russian [[Alexandra Panova]], but was disqualified in the second set for verbally abusing an umpire. Wozniacki was said to have used an expletive in referring to a linesman who made a disputed call.<ref>Wozniacki was disqualified because she verbally abused an umpire. See [http://www.eurosport.com/tennis/us-open-young-blood_sto1259494/story.shtml US Open countdown: Young Blood]{{cbignore|bot=medic}}(Sardis, K.; 3 September 2006 on USOpen.org) and [http://www.carolinewozniacki.dk/blog/us-open-2/ US Open! at Caroline Wozniacki Official Website] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070603145248/http://www.carolinewozniacki.dk/blog/us-open-2/ |date=3 June 2007 }} (Wozniacki, C.; 4 September 2006 on carolinewozniacki.dk)</ref> However, on her blog, she claimed to have said \"take your sunglasses of [sic]\" and was mistaken for talking to the linesman, when she in fact was criticizing herself after the next point.<ref>{{cite news|title=Caroline Wozniacki U.S. Open Blog entry 2|first=Caroline|last=Wozniacki| date=4 September 2006|url =http://www.carolinewozniacki.dk/blog/us-open-2/|accessdate=1 January 2007|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070603145248/http://www.carolinewozniacki.dk/blog/us-open-2/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 3 June 2007}}</ref>\n\nIn her last junior tournament, the [[Osaka Mayor's Cup]], she won both the girls' singles and doubles.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itftennis.com/juniors/news/newsarticle.asp?articleid=17050 |title=Wozniacki and Sugita claim Grade A titles in Japan |author=Faye Andrews |date=19 October 2006 |publisher=ITFtennis.com |accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref> Her first title on the senior tour came in October when she won the $25,000 tournament in Istanbul by beating [[Tatjana Malek]] in the final. Wozniacki was set to face [[Venus Williams]] on 27 November in an exhibition match in Copenhagen,<ref name=\"gala06\">{{cite web|url=http://www.danskesportsjournalister.dk/?prm=22676 |title=Caroline Wozniacki f\u00f8r den store gallaaften: Jeg vil v\u00e6re lige s\u00e5 god som Venus Williams|publisher=Danske Sportsjournalister |language = Danish | date=29 October 2006 |accessdate=12 December 2010}}</ref> but five days before the event, Williams canceled because of an injury.<ref name=\"venuscancel\">{{cite news | last = [[Ritzau]] | title = Wozniackis kamp mod Venus aflyst | language = Danish | publisher=DR Forside| date = 22 November 2006 | url = http://www.dr.dk/Sporten/Oevrig_sport/Tennis/2006/11/22/163811.htm | accessdate =22 November 2006}}</ref> The two did, however, face each other in the [[2006 Regions Morgan Keegan Championships and the Cellular South Cup|Memphis]] [[WTA Tier III Events|WTA Tier III]] event on 20 February. Williams beat Wozniacki, ending a nine-match winning streak for Wozniacki. On 29 November Wozniacki was named ambassador for Danish Junior Tennis by the [[Culture Minister of Denmark]] at the time, [[Brian Mikkelsen]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Caroline Wozniacki bliver ambassad\u00f8r | language = Danish | newspaper=[[Politiken]]| date = 24 November 2006 | url = http://politiken.dk/sport/ECE204160/caroline-wozniacki-bliver-ambassadoer/ | accessdate =16 March 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 February 2007, she won a $75,000 singles title in [[Urtij\u00ebi|Ortisei]], beating Italian [[Alberta Brianti]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dr.dk/Sporten/Oevrig_sport/Tennis/2007/02/04/222552.htm?wbc_purpose=upda|title=Wozniacki vandt i Italien|date=4 February 2007|publisher=Danish Broadcasting Corporation|language=Danish|accessdate=21 June 2011}}</ref> On 4 March, she won the $75,000 tournament in Las Vegas, beating top-seed [[Akiko Morigami]] in the final. She obtained a wildcard for the [[2007 Pacific Life Open \u2013 Women's Singles|Pacific Life Open]] main draw and made her [[WTA Tier I tournaments|Tier I]] debut there. She was knocked out in the second round by [[Martina Hingis]]. She then made the semifinals of the [[2007 AIG Japan Open Tennis Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|AIG Open]] in Tokyo in October, her first career WTA Tour semifinal, and as a result became the first Danish woman to reach a WTA semifinal since [[Tine Scheuer-Larsen]] at [[WTA Austria|Bregenz]] in 1986. She was defeated by Venus Williams in straight sets.\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===2008: First WTA Tour title===\nAt the [[2008 Australian Open|Australian Open]], Wozniacki defeated [[Gisela Dulko]] and 21st seed [[Alona Bondarenko]] on her way to the round of 16, where she lost to the eventual finalist and fourth-seeded [[Ana Ivanovic]]. At the [[2008 French Open|French Open]], Wozniacki was seeded 30th, making this the first Grand Slam tournament in which she was seeded. She again lost in the third round to the eventual champion and world No. 2 Ana Ivanovic.<ref>{{cite news|author=Matthew Cronin|title=Ivanovic, Sharapova scratch through| url =http://www.rolandgarros.com/en_FR/news/articles/2008-05-30/200805301212149831875.html|date=2008-05-30| accessdate =2008-06-07 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080601211654/http://www.rolandgarros.com/en_FR/news/articles/2008-05-30/200805301212149831875.html  |archivedate = 2008-06-01}}</ref> At [[2008 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], she reached the third round, but lost to second-seeded [[Jelena Jankovi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://2008.wimbledon.org/en_GB/news/match_reports/2008-06-28/200806281214665988140.html |title=Jankovic hobbles to hard-fought win |first=Barry |last=Newcombe |date=28 June 2008 |publisher=All England Club |accessdate=31 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090915224515/http://2008.wimbledon.org/en_GB/news/match_reports/2008-06-28/200806281214665988140.html |archivedate=15 September 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wozniacki US Open 08.jpg|thumb|right|Wozniacki during the 2008 US Open]]\nWozniacki won her first WTA Tour title at the [[2008 Nordea Nordic Light Open|Nordic Light Open]] in Stockholm without dropping a set, defeating fifth seed [[Anabel Medina Garrigues]] in the quarterfinals, top seed and world No. 10 [[Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska]] in the semifinals, and [[Vera Dushevina]] in the final. At the [[Tennis at the 2008 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] in Beijing she beat world No. 12 [[Daniela Hantuchov\u00e1]] in the second round, then lost to the eventual gold-medalist [[Elena Dementieva]]. Wozniacki then won her second WTA Tour title at the [[2008 Pilot Pen Tennis|Pilot Pen Tennis]] in New Haven, defeating three seeded players, [[Dominika Cibulkov\u00e1]], [[Marion Bartoli]] and [[Aliz\u00e9 Cornet]], en route to the final, where she defeated world No. 11 [[Anna Chakvetadze]].\n\nWozniacki was the 21st seed at the [[2008 US Open (tennis)|US Open]]. She defeated world No. 14 [[Victoria Azarenka]] in the third round, but lost to second-seeded and eventual runner-up Jelena Jankovi\u0107 in the fourth round.<ref>{{cite news|author=Caroline Cheese|work=BBC Sport|title=Jankovic survives Wozniacki test| url =http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tennis/7479256.stm|date =2008-07-28| accessdate =2008-09-01}}</ref> At the [[2008 China Open (tennis)|China Open]], she lost her opening match to Anabel Medina Garrigues. However, she teamed up with Medina Garrigues to clinch the doubles title, defeating the Chinese duo of [[Han Xinyun]] and [[Xu Yifan]]. It was Wozniacki's first WTA doubles title. At the Tier III [[2008 AIG Japan Open Tennis Championships|AIG Japan Open Tennis Championships]], she was the top seed for the first time on the WTA Tour, and won her third career title, defeating [[Kaia Kanepi]] of Estonia in the final. Wozniacki then took part in the [[2008 Nordea Danish Open|Nordea Danish Open]], in her hometown of [[Odense]]. After a string of good performances, she won the tournament, beating world No. 64 [[Sofia Arvidsson]] in the final.\n\nWozniacki's final win\u2013loss record for the year (ITF matches included, exhibition matches not included) was 58\u201320 in singles and 8\u20139 in doubles. She ended the year ranked 12th in singles and 79th in doubles. She finished 13th in the race for the [[Sony Ericsson Championships]]. She won the [[WTA Awards|Newcomer of the Year]] award for 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cphpost.dk/sport/120-sport/45211-wozniacki-wins-tennis-award.html |title=Wozniacki wins tennis award |date=27 March 2009 |work=The Copenhagen Post |accessdate=11 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090331120201/http://www.cphpost.dk/sport/120-sport/45211-wozniacki-wins-tennis-award.html |archivedate=31 March 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===2009: First Grand Slam final and top-5 ranking===\nWozniacki started the season in [[2009 ASB Classic \u2013 Singles|Auckland]], where she lost to [[Elena Vesnina]] in the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tennis/7817160.stm |title=In-form Keothavong reaches semis |work=BBC Sport |date=8 January 2009 |accessdate=8 January 2009  |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090116144356/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/tennis/7817160.stm |archivedate=16 January 2009 |url-status=live |df=dmy }}</ref> She also reached the quarterfinals in [[2009 Medibank International Sydney \u2013 Women's Singles|Sydney]], this time losing to world No. 2 [[Serena Williams]] after having three match points. Seeded 11th at the [[2009 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|Australian Open]], Wozniacki lost in the third round to Australian [[Jelena Dokic]].\n\nIn [[2009 Pattaya Women's Open \u2013 Singles|Pattaya]], she lost to [[Magdal\u00e9na Ryb\u00e1rikov\u00e1]] in the quarterfinals. Seeded first at the [[2009 Cellular South Cup \u2013 Singles|Cellular South Cup]] in Memphis, Wozniacki advanced to the final, but lost to Victoria Azarenka, after they partnered in the doubles final to defeat [[Micha\u00eblla Krajicek]] and [[Yuliana Fedak]].\n\nWozniacki then took part in the first two [[WTA Premier tournaments|Premier Mandatory]] tournaments of the year. At [[2009 BNP Paribas Open \u2013 Women's Singles|Indian Wells]], she lost in the quarterfinals to eventual champion [[Vera Zvonareva]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/mar/23/sports/sp-dwyre-indian-wells23|title= Wind gets assist as Vera Zvonareva and Rafael Nadal win finals at Indian Wells |date=23 March 2009|work=The Los Angeles Times|accessdate=1 August 2017}}</ref> In [[2009 Sony Ericsson Open \u2013 Women's Singles|Miami]], she scored her first win over Elena Dementieva, then lost to [[Svetlana Kuznetsova]] in the quarterfinals.\n\n[[File:US Open 2009 4th round 156.jpg|thumb|left|Wozniacki reached her first Grand Slam final at the 2009 US Open]]\nWozniacki won her first title of the year at the [[2009 MPS Group Championships \u2013 Singles|MPS Group Championships]] on green clay in Ponte Vedra Beac, where she defeated Canadian [[Aleksandra Wozniak]]. In [[2009 Family Circle Cup \u2013 Singles|Charleston]], she defeated top seed Elena Dementieva in the semifinals, then lost the final to [[Sabine Lisicki]].\n\nWozniacki suffered early exits in her next two tournaments, losing to Marion Bartoli in the second round in [[2009 Porsche Tennis Grand Prix \u2013 Singles|Stuttgart]], and to Victoria Azarenka in the third round in [[2009 Internazionali BNL d'Italia \u2013 Women's Singles|Rome]]. She reached the final of the inaugural Premier Mandatory [[2009 Mutua Madrile\u00f1a Madrid Open \u2013 Women's Singles|Mutua Madrile\u00f1a Madrid Open]], where she lost to world No. 1 [[Dinara Safina]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2009/may/17/dinara-safina-madrid-open-caroline-wozniacki|title=Dinara Safina defeats Caroline Wozniacki to win Madrid Open|date=17 May 2009|work=The Guardian|accessdate=30 September 2009|location=London}}</ref> This was Wozniacki's only match against a reigning No. 1 before she became No. 1 in October 2010. Seeded 10th at the [[2009 French Open|French Open]], Wozniacki lost to Sorana C\u00eerstea in the third round. They partnered in doubles, but lost in the first round.\n\nWozniacki won her second 2009 title on the grass of [[2009 Aegon International \u2013 Women's Singles|Eastbourne]]. In the final, she defeated [[Virginie Razzano]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/8110893.stm|title=Wozniacki triumphs at Eastbourne |date=20 June 2009|work=BBC Sport  |accessdate=20 June 2009}}</ref> Wozniacki was seeded ninth at [[2009 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Wimbledon]], where she lost to Sabine Lisicki in the fourth round.\n\nOn her 19th birthday, she lost the final of the [[2009 Swedish Open|Swedish Open]] to [[Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 Mart\u00ednez S\u00e1nchez]]. On hard court at the [[2009 LA Women's Tennis Championships|LA Women's Tennis Championships]], she lost in the second round to Sorana C\u00eerstea. At the [[2009 Western & Southern Financial Group Masters and Women's Open|Cincinnati Masters]], she reached the quarterfinals, then lost to Elena Dementieva. In [[2009 Rogers Cup|Toronto]], she lost early in the second round to [[Zheng Jie]], but she then went on to defend her title at the [[2009 Pilot Pen Tennis|Pilot Pen Tennis]] in New Haven without losing a set. In the first round, she had her first [[double bagel]] win as a professional, 6\u20130, 6\u20130, over [[Edina Gallovits]] in 41 minutes. In the final, she beat Elena Vesnina for her third title of the season.\n\nWozniacki was the ninth seed at the [[2009 US Open (tennis)|US Open]]. She made her best result to date by becoming the first Danish woman to reach a Grand Slam final. Her route to the final included a hard-fought three-set win against reigning French Open champion Svetlana Kuznetsova in the fourth round, then scored straight sets wins against [[Melanie Oudin]] in the quarterfinals and [[Yanina Wickmayer]] in the semifinals.<ref>{{cite web |title=Player of the Day: Day 13 |work=usopen.org |url=http://www.usopen.org/en_US/news/playerday/20090912.html |date=12 September 2009 |accessdate=14 September 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090915234252/http://www.usopen.org/en_US/news/playerday/20090912.html |archivedate=15 September 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In the final, she was defeated by [[Kim Clijsters]].\n\nIn the second round of the [[2009 Toray Pan Pacific Open|Toray Pan Pacific Open]], she retired because of a viral illness down 0\u20135 against [[Aleksandra Wozniak]]. She then lost to [[Mar\u00eda Jos\u00e9 Mart\u00ednez S\u00e1nchez]] in the first round of the [[2009 China Open (tennis)|China Open]], and to [[Samantha Stosur]] in the semifinals in [[2009 HP Open|Osaka]]. The following week in [[2009 BGL Luxembourg Open|Luxembourg]], she retired with a hamstring injury in the first round while leading 7\u20135, 5\u20130 over [[Anne Kremer]]. This aroused controversy because of the scoreline.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tennis/wozniacki-denies-part-in-betting-scandal-1809774.html |title=Wozniacki denies part in betting scandal |date=26 October 2009 |work=The Independent |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki's stellar 2009 results qualified her for the year-end [[2009 WTA Tour Championships|Sony Ericsson Championships]] in Doha for the first time. She won two of three group matches and advanced to the semifinals. There she struggled with a stomach strain and a left thigh injury against world No. 1 Serena Williams, and retired while trailing 6\u20134, 0\u20131.<ref>{{cite news|author=Dave James (AFP) |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5h4FweZTbT9gCb8o6ZdoNdW9iqMpg|title=It's Venus against Serena in WTA Championships final |date=31 October 2009|agency=Agence France-Presse|accessdate=11 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131220135128/https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5h4FweZTbT9gCb8o6ZdoNdW9iqMpg?hl=en |archivedate=20 December 2013 | url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===2010: First WTA Premier Mandatory title and world No. 1===\n[[File:Caroline Wozniacki (4308352679).jpg|thumb|right|Wozniacki serving at the 2010 Australian Open]]\nIn her first WTA tournament of the year, Wozniacki suffered an opening-round loss to [[Li Na (tennis)|Li Na]] of China in the [[2010 Medibank International Sydney|Sydney]]. She was seeded fourth at the [[2010 Australian Open|Australian Open]], her first top-eight seed in a Grand Slam. She again fell to Li, this time in the fourth round, in straight sets. Despite her fourth-round exit, Wozniacki achieved a career-high ranking of No. 3.\n\nAs the second seed at [[2010 BNP Paribas Open|Indian Wells]], Wozniacki reached the final, then lost to former world No. 1 Jelena Jankovi\u0107. With this result, she achieved a new career-high ranking of world No. 2.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100324111013/http://www.bnpparibasopen.org/News/Tennis/2010/Tournament/WTA-Sunday2-Jankovic-Clinches-Title.aspx Jankovic Finishes With A Flourish] BNP Paribas Open, 21 March 2010. Retrieved 11 February 2015.</ref> At the [[2010 Sony Ericsson Open|Sony Ericsson Open]] in Miami, Wozniacki lost in the quarterfinals to the newly returned [[Justine Henin]].\n\nHer next tournament was in [[2010 MPS Group Championships|Ponte Vedra Beach]], where she defeated [[Olga Govortsova]] in the final. Wozniacki then competed at the [[2010 Family Circle Cup|Family Circle Cup]] in Charleston. She advanced to the semifinals, where she met Vera Zvonareva. Wozniacki was forced to retire down 2\u20135 when she rolled her ankle.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.familycirclecup.com/pages/articles/20100427110601.pdf |title=Post-Match Press Conference With: Caroline Wozniacki |date=17 April 2010 |work=Family Circle Cup website |accessdate=14 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710223830/http://www.familycirclecup.com/pages/articles/20100427110601.pdf |archivedate=10 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/20100417/vera-sam-into-final_2256076_2027943|title=Vera & Sam Into Final|date=17 April 2010|accessdate=17 April 2010|publisher=WTA Tour}}</ref><ref>\n{{cite web|title=2010 Caroline Wozniacki ankle injury; from google (Caroline Wozniacki ankle injury) result 4|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QsAysOpA97M&t=1m52s}}</ref>\n\nDespite her ongoing ankle injury, she continued to compete in tournaments through the clay-court season, suffering early losses in [[2010 Porsche Tennis Grand Prix|Stuttgart]], [[2010 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Rome]] and [[2010 Mutua Madrile\u00f1a Madrid Open|Madrid]]. She then reached the quarterfinals in [[2010 Polsat Warsaw Open|Warsaw]], but retired after losing the first set.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory?id=10699725 |title=Wozniacki Retires Hurt, Doubtful for French Open |date=20 May 2010 |work=ABC News |accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki was seeded third at the [[2010 French Open|French Open]]. She posted her best result at Roland Garros by advancing to the fourth round without dropping a set. After defeating [[Flavia Pennetta]] in the round of 16 in three sets, she lost to eventual champion [[Francesca Schiavone]] in the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/SEWTATour-Archive/posting/2010/903/MDS.pdf |title=WTA tournament structure, categories, and format \u2013 Sony Ericsson WTA Tour |publisher= |accessdate=12 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100601214424/http://www.sonyericssonwtatour.com/SEWTATour-Archive/posting/2010/903/MDS.pdf |archivedate= 1 June 2010 |df= }}</ref> Wozniacki partnered with Daniela Hantuchov\u00e1 in doubles, but they withdrew before their second round match against the Williams sisters because of a right shoulder injury to Hantuchov\u00e1.\n\nAs the defending champion, Wozniacki lost early at the [[2010 Aegon International|Aegon International]], her first grass-court tournament of the year, to [[Aravane Reza\u00ef]]. Wozniacki was seeded third at [[2010 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], where she defeated [[Tathiana Garbin]], [[Chang Kai-chen]], and [[Anastasia Pavlyuchenkova]] en route to the fourth round, where she was defeated by [[Petra Kvitov\u00e1]].\n\nWozniacki was the first seed at the inaugural [[2010 e-Boks Danish Open|e-Boks Danish Open]]. It was the first Danish WTA tournament, created largely out of Wozniacki's popularity in Denmark. She defeated [[Kl\u00e1ra Zakopalov\u00e1]] to win her second title of the year.\n\nIn [[2010 Western & Southern Financial Group Women's Open|Cincinnati]], she lost in the third round to Marion Bartoli. As the second seed in [[2010 Rogers Cup|Montreal]], Wozniacki was forced to wait two days to play her semifinal match with Svetlana Kuznetsova because of heavy rain. She defeated both Kuznetsova and Vera Zvonareva on the same day for her third singles title of the year. As the top seed in [[2010 Pilot Pen Tennis|New Haven]], Wozniacki defeated Nadia Petrova in the final for her third consecutive title there. By virtue of this, she also won the [[2010 US Open Series|US Open Series]].\n\nWozniacki was the top seed at the [[2010 US Open (tennis)|US Open]] due to the withdrawal of world No. 1 Serena Williams. She advanced to the semifinals, then lost to Vera Zvonareva. With her semifinal appearance, Wozniacki became one of only two women (the other being Venus Williams) to have reached at least the fourth round of all four Grand Slam events in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.onthebaseline.com/2010/10/07/caroline-wozniacki-dethrones-serena-williams-for-no-1-tennis-ranking/ |title=Caroline Wozniacki Dethrones Serena Williams for No. 1 Tennis Ranking |author=Aaress Lawless |date=7 October 2010 |work=On the Baseline Tennis News |accessdate=14 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nHer first tournament during the Asian hard-court season was the [[2010 Toray Pan Pacific Open|Toray Pan Pacific Open]] in Tokyo. She won back-to-back three-setters against Victoria Azarenka and Elena Dementieva, the latter of whom she beat in the final to win her fifth title of the year.\n\nShe then entered the [[2010 China Open \u2013 Women's Singles|China Open]] in Beijing. In the third round, Wozniacki faced Petra Kvitov\u00e1, who had routed her at Wimbledon. Wozniacki avenged that loss, which ensured that she would replace Serena Williams as the new world No. 1 after the tournament. She was the fifth player to reach the No. 1 position [[List of WTA number 1 ranked players#Players who were ranked world No. 1 without having won a Grand Slam tournament|without having won a Grand Slam tournament]]. She also became the first Danish player, man or woman, to reach the top ranking.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/tennis/story/wozniacki-ascends-to-no-1-in-world-rankings-100710 |title=Wozniacki ascends to No.1 |date=11 October 2010 |publisher=[[FOXSports.com]] |accessdate=21 January 2011}}</ref> Wozniacki ultimately won the tournament, defeating Zvonareva in the final to win her sixth title of the year and twelfth overall.\n\nAt the year-end [[2010 WTA Tour Championships|Sony Ericsson Championships]] in Doha, Wozniacki was drawn in a group with Francesca Schiavone, Samantha Stosur and Elena Dementieva.<ref name=\"onthebaseline\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.onthebaseline.com/2010/09/29/caroline-wozniacki-first-singles-player-to-qualify-for-season-ending-wta-championships/|title=Caroline Wozniacki First Singles Player to Qualify for Season-Ending WTA Championships|author=Aaress Lawless|date=29 September 2010|work=On the Baseline Tennis News|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101109145418/http://www.onthebaseline.com/2010/09/29/caroline-wozniacki-first-singles-player-to-qualify-for-season-ending-wta-championships/| archivedate= 9 November 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| url-status=live}}</ref> She defeated Dementieva in her first round-robin game, but lost to Stosur in the second. She won her last round-robin match in the group against Schiavone, securing the year-end world No. 1 rank and a place in the semifinals against the winner of the other group, Vera Zvonareva. Wozniacki defeated her, but then lost the final in three sets to Kim Clijsters. Wozniacki ended the season with six WTA singles titles, the most on the tour. Clijsters won five, and no other player won more than two.\n\n===2011: Year-end No. 1 for the second year in a row===\nDuring the off season, Wozniacki switched her racquet make from Babolat to Yonex.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ed McGrogan |date=3 January 2011 |url=http://www.tennis.com/shop/2011/01/frame-job-wozniacki-switches-to-yonex/26634 |title=Frame Job: Wozniacki Switches to Yonex |work=tennis.com |accessdate=11 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150212121356/http://www.tennis.com/shop/2011/01/frame-job-wozniacki-switches-to-yonex/26634/ |archivedate=12 February 2015 |df= }}</ref> She began her 2011 season with an exhibition match in Thailand against Kim Clijsters where she lost in a [[super tie-break]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bangkokpost.com/news/sports/214200/clijsters-beats-wozniacki-in-exhibition-match |title=Clijsters beats Wozniacki in exhibition match |author=Tor Chittinand |date=3 January 2011 |newspaper=[[Bangkok Post]] |accessdate=8 January 2011}}</ref> Wozniacki then played another exhibition, the team [[Hong Kong Tennis Classic]], where she represented and was captain of Team Europe. She won two matches against Team Asia Pacific, then was crushed by world No. 2 Vera Zvonareva in the final against Team Russia.<ref>[http://www.hongkongtennisclassic.com/eng/scoreboard.php?playDate=5 \"Hong Kong Tennis Classic 2011 Scoreboard\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110712215652/http://www.hongkongtennisclassic.com/eng/scoreboard.php?playDate=5 |date=12 July 2011 }}. Retrieved 8 January 2011.</ref> Her first WTA tournament was the [[2011 Medibank International Sydney|Medibank International Sydney]]. She received a bye to the second round, where she lost to Dominika Cibulkov\u00e1.\n\nThe [[2011 Australian Open|Australian Open]] was Wozniacki's first major as world No. 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/20110119/stats-corner-new-no1s-at-majors_2256076_2271116 |title=Stats Corner \u2013 New No. 1s at Majors |date=19 January 2011 |work=Women's Tennis Association |accessdate=11 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140325225756/http://www.wtatennis.com/news/20110119/stats-corner-new-no1s-at-majors_2256076_2271116 |archivedate=25 March 2014 }}</ref> She lost to Li Na in the semifinals, failing to convert a match point when trying to serve out the match at 5\u20134 in the second set.<ref>{{cite news |title=Li Beats Wozniacki in Australian Open Semifinals |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/27/sports/tennis/27openwomen.html?_r=0 |newspaper=The New York Times |date=27 January 2011 |accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki dropped to No. 2 behind Clijsters during the week of 14 February, but regained the top spot the following week. She received a bye to the second round in [[2011 Dubai Tennis Championships|Dubai]] where, in the quarterfinals, she beat [[Shahar Pe'er]] to ensure her No. 1 position in the next rankings update.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/20110218/wozniacki-beats-peer-secures-no1-return_2256076_2296495 |date=18 February 2011 |title=Wozniacki Beats Peer, Secures No.1 Return |work=Women's Tennis Association |accessdate=11 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130727220645/http://www.wtatennis.com/news/20110218/wozniacki-beats-peer-secures-no1-return_2256076_2296495 |archivedate=27 July 2013 }}</ref> She went on to defeat Svetlana Kuznetsova in the final to take her 13th career singles title and first of the year. In [[2011 Qatar Ladies Open|Doha]], she received a bye to the second round and reached the final, defeating Nadia Petrova, Flavia Pennetta and Marion Bartoli in straight sets. She lost to Vera Zvonareva in the final. In the first Premier Mandatory event of the year in [[2011 BNP Paribas Open|Indian Wells]], Wozniacki made it to the final, where she defeated Marion Bartoli for her 14th singles title. At the [[2011 Sony Ericsson Open|Sony Ericsson Open]] in Miami, Wozniacki lost in the fourth round to 21st seed [[Andrea Petkovic]]. She made an uncharacteristic 52 unforced errors and later said she had been playing a lot of matches when she was asked about fatigue.<ref>{{cite news |title=Petkovic Pulls the Plug on Wozniacki at the Sony Ericsson Open |url=http://miamitennisnews.com/2011/03/28/petkovic-pulls-the-plug-on-wozniacki-at-the-sony-ericsson-open/ |newspaper=Miami Tennis News |date=28 March 2011 |accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2011 Family Circle Cup|Family Circle Cup]], Wozniacki made it to the final, where she defeated unseeded Elena Vesnina to take her third title of the year, 15th of her career. In [[2011 Porsche Tennis Grand Prix|Stuttgart]], she made it to her fifth final of the year, where she lost to [[Julia G\u00f6rges]] in straight sets. In [[2011 Mutua Madrid Open|Madrid]], Wozniacki lost to G\u00f6rges again, this time in the third round. In [[Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Rome]], she lost to eventual champion Maria Sharapova in the semifinal round. At the [[2011 Brussels Open|Brussels Open]], Wozniacki reached the semifinals, where she defeated 3rd seed and reigning French Open champion, Francesca Schiavone.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/tennis/13476498.stm|title=Caroline Wozniacki to face Peng Shuai in Brussels final|date=20 May 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=27 June 2011}}</ref> In the final, Wozniacki's sixth of the year, she defeated eighth seed [[Peng Shuai]] to win her first red clay title, having won three titles on the faster green clay.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/othersports/2015116596_digs22.html|title=Top-ranked Caroline Wozniacki wins Brussels Open Tennis|date=21 May 2011|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=28 June 2011}}</ref> Wozniacki was the top seed at the [[2011 French Open|French Open]], but was upset in the third round by 28th seed Daniela Hantuchov\u00e1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/sports/tennis/french11/news/story?id=6598263|title=Caroline Wozniacki, Sam Stosur lose|date=27 May 2011|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=27 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Caroline WOZNIACKI.JPG|thumb|left|Wozniacki at the 2011 WTA Championships]]\nWozniacki's next tournament was the [[2011 e-Boks Sony Ericsson Open|e-Boks Sony Ericsson Open]] in her native Denmark. In the final, she defeated fourth seed [[Lucie \u0160af\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1]], taking her fifth title of the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2011/SPORT/tennis/06/12/tennis.wozniacki.murray.kohlschreiber/|title=Wozniacki retains Copenhagen crown|date=12 June 2011|publisher=CNN|accessdate=12 June 2011}}</ref> At [[2011 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], she had straight-set wins until the fourth round, but then lost to 24th seed Dominika Cibulkov\u00e1.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/wimbledon/8602085/Wimbledon-2011-Caroline-Wozniacki-loses-to-Dominika-Cibulkova-as-questions-raised-over-world-No-1-ranking.html|title=Wimbledon 2011: Caroline Wozniacki loses to Dominika Cibulkova as questions raised over world No 1 ranking|last=Chadband|first=Ian|date=27 May 2011|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=27 June 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n\nAt the Rogers Cup, Wozniacki made an early second-round exit. She was defeated by Roberta Vinci in straight sets despite holding a 5\u20131 lead in the second set. Wozniacki was the top seed at the [[2011 Western & Southern Open|Western & Southern Open]] in Cincinnati, but lost in the second round to world No. 76 [[Christina McHale]]. Next playing at the [[2011 New Haven Open at Yale|New Haven Open at Yale]], Wozniacki won the title for the fourth year in a row, defeating Francesca Schiavone in the semifinals and qualifier [[Petra Cetkovsk\u00e1]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2011-08-27/sports/hc-new-haven-open-final-0828-20110827_1_caroline-wozniacki-new-haven-open-anne-worcester|title=Wozniacki Makes It Four In A Row In New Haven|last=Doyle|first=Paul|date=27 August 2011|work=The Hartford Courant|accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2011 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], Wozniacki was the first seed. In the first round, she defeated [[Nuria Llagostera Vives]]. In the second round, Wozniacki defeated [[Arantxa Rus]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/othersports/tennis/woz-in-a-breeze-top-seed-advances-to-third-round-of-us-open/2011/09/01/gIQABR0JvJ_story.html|title=Woz in a breeze: Top seed advances to third round of US Open|date=1 September 2011|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=2 September 2011}} {{Dead link|date=April 2014|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> and in the third round, defeated [[Vania King]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.sacbee.com/2011/09/03/3882692/no-1-wozniacki-beats-king-in-us.html|title=No. 1 Wozniacki beats King in US Open's 3rd round |date=3 September 2011|work=The Sacramento Bee|accessdate=9 September 2011}}{{dead link|date=September 2014}}</ref> In the fourth round, Wozniacki fought back from a 7\u20136, 4\u20131 deficit, defeating Svetlana Kuznetsova.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-opinion/6934881/us-open-wozniacki-battles-back-beat-kuznetsova |title=Wozniacki battles back to beat Kuznetsova |last=Bernstein |first=Viv |date=5 September 2011 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=9 September 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102105146/http://espn.go.com/espnw/news-opinion/6934881/us-open-wozniacki-battles-back-beat-kuznetsova |archivedate= 2 November 2011 |df= }}</ref> Wozniacki then progressed to the semifinals by defeating Andrea Petkovic in the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://straightsets.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/09/08/wozniacki-defeats-petkovic/|title=Wozniacki Defeats Petkovic|last=Rothenberg|first=Ben|date=8 September 2011|work=The New York Times|accessdate=9 September 2011}}</ref> In the semifinals she lost to Serena Williams.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://straightsets.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/09/10/2011-u-s-open-live-analysis-williams-wozniacki-semifinals/|title=Williams Overpowers Wozniacki and Advances to Final|last=Martin|first=John|date=10 September 2011|work=The New York TImes|accessdate=11 September 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2011 Toray Pan Pacific Open|Tokyo]], Wozniacki lost to Kaia Kanepi in the third round. In [[2011 China Open (tennis)|Beijing]], she lost to Flavia Pennetta in the quarterfinals. This was Wozniacki's only loss in the 12 quarterfinals she reached in 2011.\n\nWozniacki was the top seed at the [[2011 WTA Tour Championships|WTA Championships]]. In the group stage, she beat Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska, then lost to Vera Zvonareva. She lost to Petra Kvitov\u00e1 in her final round-robin match and so failed to advance to semifinals for the first time in three appearances. She finished the year as world No. 1 for the second consecutive year. Despite narrowly edging Petra for the year-end No. 1 ranking in points, she lost on all Player of Year awards to Petra.\n\n===2012: Beginning of singles decline===\nWozniacki began her season by representing Denmark at the [[2012 Hopman Cup]] with [[Frederik Nielsen]] as her partner. Wozniacki won two of her three round robin matches in singles, defeating [[Bethanie Mattek-Sands]] and [[Tsvetana Pironkova]], then lost to world No. 2 Petra Kvitov\u00e1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hopmancup.com/content.php?idphc=216 |title=Wozniacki ready for 2012 after Hopman Cup debut |author=Holly Johnsen |publisher=hopmancup.com |accessdate=29 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108215709/http://hopmancup.com/content.php?idphc=216 |archivedate=8 January 2012 }}</ref> Her first WTA event was the [[2012 Apia International Sydney|Apia International Sydney]]. Wozniacki defeated Dominika Cibulkov\u00e1 when trailing 4\u20130 in the third set.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/tennis/dokic-falls-in-sydney-wozniacki-and-li-advance-20120110-1pste.html |title=Dokic falls in Sydney, Wozniacki and Li advance |date=10 January 2012 |work=[[The Age]] |accessdate=29 September 2012 |location=Melbourne}}</ref> She lost to Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska in three sets in the quarterfinals, after serving for the match at 5\u20134 up in the second set.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apiainternational.com.au/2012/01/radwanska-leaves-wozniacki-wondering |title=Radwanska leaves Wozniacki wondering |date=12 January 2012 |work=Apia International Sydney website|accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki competed at the [[2012 Australian Open|Australian Open]] as the top seed. She defeated [[Anastasia Rodionova]], [[Anna Tatishvili]], [[Monica Niculescu]] and Jelena Jankovi\u0107, all in straight sets, to reach the quarterfinals where she lost to the defending champion Kim Clijsters. As a result, Wozniacki lost her top ranking and was replaced by the 2012 champion Victoria Azarenka.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/tennis/article-2093529/Victoria-Azarenka-new-world-No-1.html |title=Shake up in the women's game as champion Azarenka replaces Wozniacki as world No 1 |author= Mike Dickson |date=30 January 2012 |work=[[Daily Mail]] |accessdate=29 September 2012 |location=London}}</ref> Next playing at [[2012 Qatar Open|Doha]], Wozniacki lost to Lucie \u0160af\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1 in the second round, having received a first-round bye. Wozniacki was the defending champion in [[2012 Dubai Tennis Championships|Dubai]] and [[2012 BNP Paribas Open|Indian Wells]], but failed to defend either title, losing to Julia G\u00f6rges and Ana Ivanovic, respectively.\n\nWozniacki reached the semifinals in [[2012 Sony Ericsson Open|Miami]], beating [[Barbora Z\u00e1hlavov\u00e1-Str\u00fdcov\u00e1]], Petra Cetkovsk\u00e1, [[Yanina Wickmayer]] and Serena Williams, all in straight sets. Wozniacki then lost to 2nd seed Maria Sharapova. Wozniacki did not defend her title in [[2012 Family Circle Cup|Charleston]] as she was not allowed to participate under WTA rules because two top-6 players had already entered the draw.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/tennis/blog/_/name/bodo_peter/id/7675974/tennis-star-security-backfiring-caroline-wozniacki-wta |title=Star security backfiring on WTA? |author=Peter Bodo |date=12 March 2012 |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref> Wozniacki then played her home tournament in [[2012 e-Boks Open|Copenhagen]]. She reached the final but lost to [[Angelique Kerber]], her first loss at the tournament since the start in 2010.\n\n[[File:Roland Garros 2012 - Caroline Wozniacki serve (8755331730).jpg|thumb|right|Wozniacki serving at the 2012 French Open]]\nShe then played the [[2012 French Open|French Open]], where she lost to Kaia Kanepi in three sets in the third round.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/tennis/18307177|title=French Open 2012: Caroline Wozniacki and Schiavone out|work=BBC Sport|date=2 June 2012|accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> At the [[2012 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], she lost to Austrian [[Tamira Paszek]] in the first round.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/tennis/wimbledon-2012/top-stories/Caroline-Wozniacki-dumped-out-by-Paszek/articleshow/14436441.cms|title= Caroline Wozniacki dumped out by Paszek|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|date=27 June 2012|accessdate=28 June 2012}}{{dead link|date=September 2014}}</ref> It was her first opening-round exit from any Grand Slam since making her professional debut at the [[2007 French Open]].<ref name=\"WTAStats\"/>\n\nWozniacki represented [[Denmark at the 2012 Summer Olympics|Denmark]] at the [[Tennis at the 2012 Summer Olympics|Olympics]] as the eighth seed in the women's singles event. In the first three rounds she defeated [[Anne Keothavong]], Yanina Wickmayer and Daniela Hantuchov\u00e1. She was then defeated by the eventual champion Serena Williams in the quarterfinals. She next participated in the [[2012 Rogers Cup|Rogers Cup]] where she lost to Petra Kvitov\u00e1 in the semifinals, and the [[2012 Western & Southern Open|Western & Southern Open]] where she was defeated in the third round by Anastasia Pavlyuchenkova. As the four-time defending champion at the [[2012 New Haven Open at Yale|New Haven Open at Yale]], Wozniacki retired against [[Maria Kirilenko]] in the semifinals due to a right knee injury, which she had suffered in her quarterfinal win over Dominika Cibulkov\u00e1.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/tennis/story/2012-08-24/new-haven-open-caroline-wozniacki-knee-injury/57289818/1 |title=Wozniacki retires with knee injury at New Haven |author=Pat Eaton-Robb |date=24 August 2012 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |accessdate=29 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki, still suffering with the injury, was seeded eighth at the [[2012 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], but did not advance past the first round. She lost in two sets to 96th-ranked Romanian [[Irina-Camelia Begu]]. As a result of the loss, Wozniacki dropped out of the top 10 for the first time in three years. Following her US Open disappointment, Wozniacki won her first tournament of the year in [[2012 Hansol Korea Open|Seoul]] by defeating [[Arantxa Rus]], [[Caroline Garcia]], Kl\u00e1ra Zakopalov\u00e1, [[Ekaterina Makarova]] and Kaia Kanepi in the final. It was her 19th career title.\n\nHer next tournament was the [[2012 Toray Pan Pacific Open|Toray Pan Pacific Open]] in Tokyo. She defeated [[Bojana Jovanovski]], Daniela Hantuchov\u00e1 and Li Na, then lost to Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska in the quarterfinals. At the [[2012 China Open (tennis)|China Open]] in Beijing, Wozniacki defeated [[Chanelle Scheepers]] and [[Hsieh Su-wei]] but lost to Angelique Kerber in the third round. Wozniacki's next tournament was the [[2012 Kremlin Cup|Kremlin Cup]]. As the third seed in the tournament, she defeated top seed Samantha Stosur in the final in three sets to take home her second title of the year, and 20th overall.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2012-10-20/stosur-sets-up-ivanovic-clash/4324352?section=sport |title=Stosur sets up Ivanovic clash - ABC Grandstand Sport - ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation)|accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref> At the year-end [[2012 Qatar Airways Tournament of Champions|Tournament of Champions]] in Sofia, Wozniacki won her three group matches and reached the final but lost to Nadia Petrova. She ended the year ranked 10th.\n\n{{quote box|quote=(Roddick) and (Djokovic) do it all the time and Caro does (it) and now it's racist.??|source=Serena Williams responding to the criticism of Wozniacki.<ref name=\"Serena response\"/>|width=21%|align=left}} In December 2012, during an exhibition match in Brazil, Wozniacki imitated friend and fellow tennis player Serena Williams by stuffing towels in her shirt and skirt in order to appear to be large-chested and have a large rear end. This act divided opinion on social network sites. It was noted that Wozniacki had done the impression before without controversy.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/tennis/9739960/Caroline-Wozniackis-latest-attempt-to-impersonate-friend-Serena-Williams-draws-criticism.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | title=Caroline Wozniacki's latest attempt to impersonate 'friend' Serena Williams draws criticism | date=12 December 2012}}</ref> Williams also defended Wozniacki in an email to ''[[USA Today]]'' and pointed out that they are friends and that the act was not racist. Williams added, however, that if people feel this way, then she should do something else next time.<ref name=\"Serena response\">{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2246293/Serena-Williams-dismisses-claims-fellow-tennis-player-Caroline-Wozniacki-did-racist-impression-says-mock-way-again.html|title=Serena Williams dismisses claims fellow tennis player Caroline Wozniacki did 'racist impression' of her but says she should not mock her in the same way again|date=23 December 2012|work=Daily Mail|location=London}}</ref>\n\n===2013: Continued struggles with form===\nWozniacki began the year in [[2013 Brisbane International|Brisbane]] where as the eighth seed, she lost in the first round to qualifier [[Ksenia Pervak]] in three sets. Wozniacki then competed at the [[2013 Apia International Sydney|Apia International Sydney]]. She defeated [[Urszula Radwa\u0144ska]] but lost to Kuznetsova in the second round. At the [[2013 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|Australian Open]], Wozniacki defeated Sabine Lisicki, Donna Veki\u0107 and [[Lesia Tsurenko]], but once again lost to Kuznetsova, this time in the fourth round.<ref>{{cite web|work=Australian Open|title=Kuznetsova holds firm to deny Dane|url=http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/match_reports/2013-01-21/201301211358739696722.html|date=2013-01-21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131112171235/http://www.australianopen.com/en_AU/news/match_reports/2013-01-21/201301211358739696722.html|archivedate=12 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki's next tournament was the [[2013 Qatar Total Open|Qatar Total Open]] where she reached the quarterfinals with wins over [[Mervana Jugi\u0107-Salki\u0107]], Sorana C\u00eerstea, [[Mona Barthel]], then lost to Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska. In [[2013 Dubai Tennis Championships|Dubai]], Wozniacki defeated Lucie \u0160af\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1, Zheng Jie and Marion Bartoli to reach the semifinals where she lost to the eventual champion, Petra Kvitov\u00e1. At the [[2013 Malaysian Open|Malaysian Open]], she lost in the first round to [[Wang Qiang (tennis)|Wang Qiang]]. She then played in an exhibition match at the [[BNP Paribas Showdown]] in Hong Kong. She was scheduled to play Li Na, but she had to withdraw due to injury. Instead Wozniacki played Li's replacement world No. 4 Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska and lost in straight sets.\n\n[[File:Caroline Wozniacki - Indian Wells 2013 - 002.jpg|thumb|left|Wozniacki reached her first final of the year at the [[2013 BNP Paribas Open]]]]\nAt the [[2013 BNP Paribas Open|BNP Paribas Open]], she defeated Aliz\u00e9 Cornet, Elena Vesnina and Nadia Petrova, then received a walkover when the defending champion Victoria Azarenka withdrew due to a foot injury. In the semifinals, Wozniacki defeated Angelique Kerber to reach her first final of the year but lost the title match to Maria Sharapova.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/tennis/story/_/id/9062961/maria-sharapova-wins-indian-wells-title-caroline-wozniacki|title=Maria Sharapova wins Indian Wells|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Martin Baccardax|date=17 March 2013|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> In her next tournament, the [[2013 Sony Open Tennis|Sony Open]] in Miami, Wozniacki made it to the third round where she lost to [[Garbi\u00f1e Muguruza]].\n\nWozniacki began the clay-court season by reaching the quarterfinals of the [[2013 Family Circle Cup|Family Circle Cup]] where she lost to [[Stefanie V\u00f6gele]]. Wozniacki lost in the first round to [[Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro]] in [[2013 Porsche Tennis Grand Prix|Stuttgart]], to [[Yaroslava Shvedova]] in [[2013 Mutua Madrid Open|Madrid]], to Bojana Jovanovski in [[2013 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Rome]], and to Zheng Jie in [[2013 Brussels Open|Brussels]]. At the [[2013 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|French Open]], Wozniacki defeated [[Laura Robson]] in the first round, then lost again to Jovanovski in the second.\n\nWozniacki began her grass-court season at the [[2013 Aegon International|Aegon International]] in Eastbourne. She reached the semifinals with victories over Tamira Paszek, Laura Robson and Ekaterina Makarova but then lost to qualifier [[Jamie Hampton]]. In the first round of [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Wimbledon]], Wozniacki beat [[Estrella Cabeza Candela]]. In the second round, she faced Petra Cetkovsk\u00e1. In just the fourth game of the first set, with the score at 2\u20131 and going with serve, Wozniacki slipped and fell, injuring her ankle. She received treatment but was visibly struggling and went on to lose the match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/1853562/report-wimbledon-injured-caroline-wozniacki-tumbles-out|title=Wimbledon: Injured Caroline Wozniacki tumbles out|work=DNAIndia|date=26 June 2013|accessdate=28 June 2013}}</ref> Wozniacki was one of several players to slip and injure themselves, including [[Jo-Wilfried Tsonga]], Victoria Azarenka and Maria Sharapova. After the match, Wozniacki questioned whether the preparation for the tournament was the same as in previous years, adding: \"I just know that it's just not really fun to be out there when you feel like you can't really push off on your foot.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/news/interviews/2013-06-26/201306261372279786109.html |title=Caroline Wozniaki Second Round |work=Wimbledon |date=26 June 2013 |accessdate=28 June 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201215232/http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/news/interviews/2013-06-26/201306261372279786109.html |archivedate= 1 February 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n\nWozniacki's woeful season continued at the [[2013 Rogers Cup|Rogers Cup]], where she fell in the second round to Sorana C\u00eerstea despite having double match point in the second set. She then reached the quarterfinals of the [[2013 Western & Southern Open|Western & Southern Open]], beating Peng Shuai, Monica Niculescu and Petra Kvitov\u00e1, but was defeated by Victoria Azarenka for the first time since 2009. Wozniacki then played at the [[2013 New Haven Open at Yale|New Haven Open at Yale]]. She reached the semifinals beating Peng via retirement, [[Karin Knapp]] and [[Sloane Stephens]], then lost to [[Simona Halep]] in straight sets. At the [[2013 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], Wozniacki defeated [[Duan Yingying]] and Chanelle Scheepers in straight sets, then lost to qualifier Camila Giorgi in the third round. This marked the first time since 2008 where Wozniacki had failed to reach the quarterfinals or better at one of the four Grand Slam tournaments.\n\nDuring the Asian swing, Wozniacki advanced to the semifinals of the [[2013 Toray Pan Pacific Open|Toray Pan Pacific Open]], defeating Flavia Pennetta, [[Magdal\u00e9na Ryb\u00e1rikov\u00e1]] and Lucie \u0160af\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1 en route, athen losing to Angelique Kerber. Her next tournament was in [[2013 China Open (tennis)|Beijing]] where she was seeded sixth and where she received a bye into the second round along with the other three Tokyo semifinalists. Wozniacki reached the quarterfinals with wins over Monica Niculescu and Sloane Stephens, but lost to the world No. 1 and eventual champion Serena Williams.\n\nWozniacki's final event for the year was the [[2013 BGL Luxembourg Open|BGL Luxembourg Open]], where she was top-seeded. She ended her two-match losing streak against Bojana Jovanovski by defeating the Serb in a three set quarterfinal. She then beat [[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Wimbledon]] finalist Sabine Lisicki to reach the final and defeated [[Annika Beck]] of Germany in straight sets to win her first and only title of the year.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news?search_api_views_fulltext=Caroline%20Wozniacki |title=Wozniacki Wins In Luxembourg |accessdate=28 June 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201215232/http://www.wtatennis.com/news?search_api_views_fulltext=Caroline%20Wozniacki |archivedate= 1 February 2014 |df= }}</ref> Despite the victory, Wozniacki failed to qualify for the year-ending [[2013 WTA Tour Championships|Tour Championships]] in Istanbul as Angelique Kerber secured the final spot with her win at the [[WTA International tournaments|WTA International]] tournament in Linz, Austria that same week. In winning Luxembourg, however, Wozniacki qualified for the [[2013 Garanti Koza WTA Tournament of Champions|Tournament of Champions]] in Sofia but ultimately chose not to participate.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/article/3506351/title/another-elite-eight-headed-to-sofia|title=Another Elite Eight Headed to Sofia |accessdate=28 June 2013 |df= }}</ref> She finished the year ranked world No. 10.\n\n===2014: Resurgence and second Grand Slam final===\nDuring the off season, Wozniacki switched her racquet make from Yonex to Babolat. She was scheduled to start the season in [[2014 Brisbane International|Brisbane]] but withdrew due to a right shoulder injury and instead began her season in [[2014 Apia International Sydney|Sydney]] where she defeated Julia G\u00f6rges in three sets, then lost to Lucie \u0160af\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1 in the second round. At the [[2014 Australian Open|Australian Open]], she lost to Garbi\u00f1e Muguruza in the third round in three sets.\n\nWozniacki competed at the [[2014 Qatar Total Open \u2013 Singles|Qatar Total Open]] where she was seeded eighth and where she lost to Yanina Wickmayer. The following week, she reached the semifinals in [[2014 Dubai Tennis Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Dubai]], defeating Sabine Lisicki, Annika Beck and Sorana C\u00eerstea before falling to the eventual champion Venus Williams.\n\nHer next tournament was the [[2014 BNP Paribas Open|BNP Paribas Open]] where she was defending runner-up points. She reached the fourth round following wins over Bojana Jovanovski and Yaroslava Shvedova, then lost to Jelena Jankovi\u0107, causing her to fall to world No. 18, her lowest ranking since 2010. She recovered by reaching the quarterfinals of the [[2014 Sony Open Tennis|Sony Open]], recording wins over [[Monica Puig]], Sloane Stephens and Varvara Lepchenko before losing to Li Na. Wozniacki made her debut at the [[2014 Monterrey Open|Monterry Open]], where she defeated [[CoCo Vandeweghe]], [[Kristina Mladenovic]] and [[Karol\u00edna Pl\u00ed\u0161kov\u00e1]] en route to the semifinals, then lost to the eventual champion Ana Ivanovic.\n\n[[File:Wozniacki WM14 (3) (14663423373).jpg|thumb|right|Wozniacki serving at the [[2014 Wimbledon Championships]]]]\nHer first tournament of the clay-court season was scheduled to be the [[2014 Porsche Tennis Grand Prix|Porsche Tennis Grand Prix]], but she was forced to withdraw due to a left wrist injury. Instead, her first event on clay was the [[2014 Mutua Madrid Open|Mutua Madrid Open]] where she reached the second round, beating Ekaterina Makarova and then losing to Roberta Vinci when sustaining a knee injury. This same injury caused her to withdraw from the following week's [[2014 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Internazionali BNL d'Italia]] in Rome.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tennisworldusa.org/Carolina-Wozniacki-pulls-out-of-Rome-articolo17914.html|accessdate=11 February 2014|title=Carolina Wozniacki pulls out of Rome|publisher=tennisworldusa.org}}</ref> At the [[2014 French Open|French Open]], Wozniacki was upset by Yanina Wickmayer in the first round in three sets.\n\nWozniacki enjoyed a stellar grass court season during which she made the semifinals of the [[2014 Aegon International|Aegon International]] with wins over Samantha Stosur, Sloane Stephens and Camila Giorgi, then lost to the eventual finalist Angelique Kerber. At the [[2014 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Wimbledon Championships]], Wozniacki reached the fourth round for the fourth time in her career with straight-sets wins over Shahar Pe'er, [[Naomi Broady]] and [[Ana Konjuh]], but ultimately lost to Barbora Z\u00e1hlavov\u00e1-Str\u00fdcov\u00e1.\n\nWozniacki won her first title of the year at the [[2014 \u0130stanbul Cup|\u0130stanbul Cup]]. She defeated [[Belinda Bencic]], Karin Knapp, Karol\u00edna Pl\u00ed\u0161kov\u00e1, Kristina Mladenovic, and Roberta Vinci to secure the title.\n\nWozniacki's first tournament of the [[2014 US Open Series]] was [[2014 Rogers Cup|Rogers Cup]]. She progressed to the quarterfinals with straight-set wins over Daniela Hantuchov\u00e1, Kl\u00e1ra Koukalov\u00e1 and [[Shelby Rogers]], then lost to top seed Serena Williams.<ref>{{cite web|work=ESPN|title=All-Williams semifinal at Rogers Cup|url=http://espn.go.com/tennis/story/_/id/11327854/serena-williams-outlasts-caroline-wozniacki-rogers-cup|date=9 August 2014}}</ref> At the [[2014 Western & Southern Open|Western & Southern Open]], she beat Magdal\u00e9na Ryb\u00e1rikov\u00e1 and [[Zhang Shuai (tennis)|Zhang Shuai]], Angelique Kerber, and Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska. In the semifinals, she fell in three sets to the eventual champion Williams.\n\nWozniacki's next tournament was the [[2014 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], where she was the tenth seed. She faced Magdal\u00e9na Ryb\u00e1rikov\u00e1 in her opening match, progressing when her opponent was forced to retire early in the third set. She then beat qualifier [[Aliaksandra Sasnovich]] in the second round in straight sets. In the third round she easily took care of 18th seed Andrea Petkovic in straight sets for her first win over a seeded player at a grand slam since 2012. In the fourth round, Wozniacki came up against former world No. 1 and former champion [[Maria Sharapova]], defeating her in three sets to progress to the quarterfinals of a grand slam for the first time since the [[2012 Australian Open]]. In the quarterfinals, she dropped just one game to breeze past Sara Errani. In the semifinals, Wozniacki came up against unseeded Peng Shuai. Wozniacki was up a set when her opponent was forced to retire due to a severe heat-related illness, allowing Wozniacki to advance to her second Grand Slam final, and her first since the [[2009 US Open (tennis)|2009 US Open]]. In the final, Wozniacki came up against two-time defending champion Serena Williams for the third time in four weeks, again falling to the world No. 1.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Robson|first1=Douglas|work=USA Today|title=Serena Williams beats Caroline Wozniacki for Open title|date=8 September 2014|accessdate=12 September 2014 |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/tennis/2014/09/07/serena-williams-beats-caroline-wozniacki-us-open/15255559/}}</ref> Due to her run to the final, Wozniacki returned to the top 10 for the first time since February.\n\nDuring the fall, Wozniacki competed at the [[2014 Toray Pan Pacific Open|Toray Pan Pacific Open]]. As the second seed, she received a bye into the second round where she faced Australian qualifier [[Jarmila Gajdo\u0161ov\u00e1]]. Wozniacki rallied from a set down to prevail. In the quarterfinals, she faced Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro, whom she easily defeated to progress to the semifinals. In a grueling match against unseeded Spaniard Garbi\u00f1e Muguruza whom she had never beaten, Wozniacki won in three sets to set up a clash with Ana Ivanovic. In her third final of the year, Wozniacki fell to the Serbian in straight sets. Wozniacki's next tournament was the [[2014 Wuhan Open|Wuhan Open]]. As the eighth seed, she received a bye into the second round, where she defeated Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro in three sets. Wozniacki then beat [[Casey Dellacqua]] and [[Timea Bacsinszky]] to reach the semifinals where she lost to [[Eugenie Bouchard]] in straight sets.<ref name=\"Yahoo\">{{cite news|url=https://ca.sports.yahoo.com/blogs/eh-game/eugenie-bouchard-rolls-over-caroline-wozniacki--reaches-final-in-china-130138767.html|title=Eugenie Bouchard rolls over Caroline Wozniacki, reaches final in China|work=Yahoo Sports|accessdate=26 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe following week, she competed at the [[2014 China Open (tennis)|China Open]] where she received a bye into the second round due to being a semifinalist in [[2014 Wuhan Open|Wuhan]]. She was eliminated by Samantha Stosur in her opening match of the tournament. It was then announced on 2 October that Wozniacki had qualified for the [[2014 WTA Finals|WTA Finals]].\n\nAt the WTA Finals, Wozniacki was drawn into the White Group alongside Sharapova, Kvitov\u00e1 and Radwa\u0144ska. In her first match she beat Maria Sharapova in three sets. She then went on to beat Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska in straight sets. With Sharapova winning in three sets against Radwa\u0144ska, Wozniacki qualified into the semifinals. She then beat Kvitov\u00e1 in straight sets going undefeated in her round robin matches. She would lose to Serena Williams in the semifinals in three sets despite serving for the match in the third set and leading 4\u20131 in the third set tiebreak. She finished the year ranked at No. 8.\n\nWozniacki then decided to run the New York City Marathon in November 2014. She recorded a time of 3 hours, 26 minutes and 33 seconds.<ref name=\"marathon\">{{cite web | url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/more-sports/caroline-wozniacki-happy-new-york-marathon-debut-article-1.1996587 | title=Caroline Wozniacki greeted by Serena Williams | accessdate=3 November 2014}}</ref> She claimed that the running training was positive for her and contributed to her good performances at the US Open and WTA Finals.\n\n===2015: Out of top 10 and an unsatisfied year-end ranking===\nWozniacki started her preparation for the Australian Open at the [[2015 ASB Classic|ASB Classic]] in Auckland seeded as No. 1 and advanced to the final, then lost to Venus Williams in three sets. Despite being seeded eighth at the [[2015 Australian Open|Australian Open]], Wozniacki was unfortunate to draw fellow former world number one and two-time champion Victoria Azarenka in the second round, and was defeated in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/article/4433986/title/azarenka-tops-wozniacki-down-under|title=Azarenka Tops Wozniacki Down Under|publisher=WTA official website|date=22 January 2015|accessdate=22 January 2015}}</ref> After the tournament, she climbed back up to No. 5.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/players/player/12631/title/caroline-wozniacki|title=Caroline Wozniacki Player Profile|publisher=WTA official website|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref> Wozniacki then competed at the [[2015 Dubai Tennis Championships|Dubai Tennis Championships]] where she made it all the way to the semifinals, then lost to eventual champion Simona Halep in three sets. Wozniacki's next tournament was the [[2015 Qatar Total Open|Qatar Total Open]] where she was seeded second. However, she lost once again to fellow former No. 1 Victoria Azarenka in the quarterfinals in straight sets, winning just four games. She rebounded at the [[2015 Malaysian Open|Malaysian Open]], winning the title by defeating [[Alexandra Dulgheru]] in the final in three sets.\n\n[[File:Caroline Wozniacki (19452566516).jpg|thumb|left|Wozniacki practicing at the 2015 Aegon International, Eastbourne]]\nWozniacki's next tournament was the [[2015 BNP Paribas Open|BNP Paribas Open]] where she was seeded fourth. In the second round, she beat [[Ons Jabeur]], then lost in the third round to Belinda Bencic in straight sets. She then competed at the [[2015 Miami Open|Miami Open]] beating [[Madison Brengle]] in the second round and Kaia Kanepi in the third round. She lost to Venus Williams in the fourth round in straight sets.\n\nWozniacki started her clay season in [[2015 Porsche Tennis Grand Prix|Stuttgart]] where she was seeded fourth.<ref>{{cite web|title=Seven Top 10s have signed up for the 2015 Porsche Tennis Grand Prix|url=http://www.porsche-tennis.com/prod/pag/tennis.nsf/web/english-pressreleases_T14_0557_en|publisher=Porsche Tennis Grand Prix|date=24 November 2014}}</ref> In the second round, she beat Lucie \u0160af\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1 in straight sets. In the quarterfinals, she dropped just three games against Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro to advance to the semifinals. In the semifinals, she beat Simona Halep in a three-set thriller to reach her first clay court final since 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/wozniacki-outlasts-halep-stuttgart|title=Wozniacki Outlasts Halep In Stuttgart|publisher=WTA official website|accessdate=4 March 2018}}</ref> She lost to Angelique Kerber in the final in three sets, despite serving for the match in the third set. Wozniacki's next tournament was the [[2015 Mutua Madrid Open|Mutua Madrid Open]] where she made it to the quarterfinals for the first time since 2009 beating [[Jarmila Gajdo\u0161ov\u00e1]], Christina McHale and Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska. She lost in the quarterfinals to Maria Sharapova in three sets. Wozniacki's next tournament was the [[2015 Internazionali BNL d'Italia|Internazionali BNL d'Italia]]. She lost in the second round to Victoria Azarenka for the third time in straight sets. Wozniacki then played at the [[2015 French Open|French Open]] as the fifth seed. She beat Karin Knapp in straight sets, then lost to Julia G\u00f6rges in the second round in straight sets.\n\nWozniacki started the grass-court season at the [[2015 Aegon International|Aegon International]]. She beat [[Jarmila Gajdo\u0161ov\u00e1]] in straight sets and Svetlana Kuznetsova in three sets to advance to the quarterfinals. She beat Andrea Petkovic in straight sets to advance to the semifinals where she faced Belinda Bencic. She retired from the match due to a back injury after losing the first three games. Wozniacki then played at [[2015 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] as the fifth seed. She beat [[Zheng Saisai]], [[Denisa Allertov\u00e1]], and Camila Giorgi to advance to the fourth round and then lost to eventual finalist [[Garbi\u00f1e Muguruza]] in straight sets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tennis/wimbledon-2015-caroline-wozniacki-goes-out-to-garbine-muguruza--and-takes-a-swipe-at-officialdom-10370418.html|title=Wimbledon 2015: Caroline Wozniacki goes out to Garbine Muguruza \u2013 and takes a swipe at officialdom|newspaper=independent.co.uk|access-date=7 July 2015}}</ref> Despite the loss, Wozniacki climbed back up to No. 4.\n\nWozniacki's summer hard-court season got off to a slow start due to an ankle injury. This injury caused her to lose early at [[2015 Bank of the West Classic|Stanford]], [[2015 Rogers Cup|Toronto]] and [[2015 Western & Southern Open|Cincinnati]] to [[Varvara Lepchenko]], [[Belinda Bencic]] and Victoria Azarenka, respectively.<ref>{{cite news|title=Varvara Lepchenko upsets top-seeded Caroline Wozniacki at Stanford|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/tennis/2015/08/06/lepchenko-upsets-top-seeded-wozniacki--stanford/31258433/|accessdate=2 September 2017|newspaper=USA TODAY|date=6 August 2015}}</ref> Wozniacki then played at the [[2015 Connecticut Open|Connecticut Open]]. She finally picked up her first win by crushing [[Alison Riske]] in the first round. She then beat Roberta Vinci in three sets, saving three match points in the third-set tiebreak, to advance to the quarterfinals. She breezed past Caroline Garcia, then lost in the semifinals to Petra Kvitov\u00e1 in straight sets. Wozniacki then played at the [[2015 US Open (tennis)|US Open]] as the fourth seed. She easily beat [[Jamie Loeb]] in her opening match to advance to the second round where she was upset by Petra Cetkovsk\u00e1 in a close three-set match despite having four match points.\n\nWozniacki began her Asian hard court swing at the [[2015 Toray Pan Pacific Open|Toray Pan Pacific Open]]. As the top seed, she received a bye in to the second round where she easily beat [[Ana Konjuh]]. She then defeated Angelique Kerber in three sets in the quarterfinals. In the semifinals, she lost to Belinda Bencic for the fourth straight time in straight sets. Wozniacki's next tournament was the [[2015 Wuhan Open|Wuhan Open]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.wuhanopen.org/index.php/index-show-tid-50.html|title=Wuhan Open Player List|publisher=Wuhan Open|access-date=17 September 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924160147/http://en.wuhanopen.org/index.php/index-show-tid-50.html|archive-date=24 September 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She lost to [[Anna Karol\u00edna Schmiedlov\u00e1]] in the second round in three sets, despite being up a set and a break. Wozniacki's next tournament was the [[2015 China Open (tennis)|China Open]]. She beat Bojana Jovanovski in the first round, and won ten games in a row to beat [[Wang Qiang (tennis)|Qiang Wang]] to advance to the third round. She lost to Angelique Kerber in straight sets. The loss ended Wozniacki's chances to qualify for the [[2015 WTA Finals|WTA Finals]].\n\nWozniacki's next tournament was the [[2015 Generali Ladies Linz|Generali Ladies Linz]]. She beat [[Mirjana Lu\u010di\u0107-Baroni]] in three sets, then lost to [[Kirsten Flipkens]] in the second round in straight sets. Wozniacki failed to qualify for the WTA Finals, but she did qualify for the [[2015 WTA Elite Trophy|Elite Trophy]] where she was drawn into Group D alongside Roberta Vinci and Svetlana Kuznetsova. After retiring in her first match against Svetlana Kuznetsova, Wozniacki withdrew from the tournament. She finished the year ranked at No. 17, her worst year-end ranking since 2007.\n\n===2016: Early injuries and revival===\nWozniacki began her 2016 season at the [[2016 ASB Classic|ASB Classic]] in Auckland, where she was defending finalist points. She beat [[Danka Kovini\u0107]], Christina McHale, and Alexandra Dulgheru to advance to the semifinals where she lost to eventual champion Sloane Stephens in straight sets. Wozniacki's next tournament was the [[2016 Australian Open|Australian Open]] where she lost to [[Yulia Putintseva]] in the first round in three sets, marking her worst performance at the tournament.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/article/5281895/title/putintseva-rallies-past-wozniacki|title=Putintseva Rallies Past Wozniacki|publisher=[[Women's Tennis Association]] (WTA)|website=www.wtatennis.com|date=18 January 2016|accessdate= 18 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki's next tournament was the [[2016 St. Petersburg Ladies' Trophy|St. Petersburg Ladies' Trophy]]. She lost to Dominika Cibulkov\u00e1 in the second round in straight sets. Wozniacki next played the Qatar Open for which she needed nine match points to beat Ana Konjuh in the first round. She was at one point up by a double break in the third set. In the second round, she faced [[Daria Gavrilova]] which she won in straight sets. Wozniacki then played Elena Vesnina in the third round, she fell in a grueling match. Wozniacki played in the [[2016 Monterrey Open|Monterrey Open]] instead of defending her title in Kuala Lumpur. She defeated [[Olga Govortsova]] in the first round and Mirjana Lucic-Baroni in the second round; however, she fell in the quarterfinals to the eventual winner Heather Watson.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/tennis/35741713 |title=Monterrey Open: Heather Watson beats Kirsten Flipkens in final |publisher=BBC |date=7 March 2016|accessdate=7 March 2016}}</ref> Caroline then played at the BNP Paribas Open and fell in the second round to Zhang Shuai. This match marked the longest match so far in 2016, at 3 hours and 24 minutes. Then in the [[2016 Miami Open|Miami Open]] Wozniacki made a promising start, defeating [[Vania King]]; however, she fell to 12th seed Elina Svitolina.\n\nWozniacki was scheduled to play many clay court tournaments, but she injured her ankle during a practice, which put her out for all of the clay-court season. This break saw Wozniacki fall through the rankings from 22 down to 34, the lowest since May 2008. She withdrew from the [[2016 French Open|French Open]] because her ankle was not 100%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/tennis/news/12110/10286053/belinda-bencic-and-caroline-wozniacki-withdraw-from-french-open|title=Caroline Wozniacki and Belinda Bencic withdraw from French Open with injuries|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|last=Charles|first=Andy|date=17 May 2016|accessdate=25 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki played in Nottingham, her first tournament since the Miami Open in March and her first tournament after hiring her new coach [[David Kotyza]]. Wozniacki won her first match in 10 weeks defeating [[\u00c7a\u011fla B\u00fcy\u00fckak\u00e7ay]], but falling in yet another three-set match to [[Anett Kontaveit]] in the second round. In her last tournament leading up to Wimbledon, Wozniacki played the [[2016 Aegon International Eastbourne|Aegon International Eastbourne]]. She showed signs of improvement from her loss of form and injury, dismissing Aliz\u00e9 Cornet and 7th seed Sam Stosur and dropping only seven games in the two matches, then lost in a three-set match to qualifier Monica Puig. In [[2016 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], she went unseeded in the tournament, the first time since 2008 Australian Open, and lost to Svetlana Kuznetsova in the first round, resulting in her falling out of the top 50 for the first time since February 2008.\n\n[[File:Wozniacki USOPEN2016.jpg|thumb|right|Wozniacki playing at the 2016 US Open]]\nWozniacki began her US hard-court season in Washington, playing the [[2016 Citi Open|Citi Open]] she went on to beat [[Hiroko Kuwata]] in the first round and retired in her second-round clash with Sam Stosur despite being up a set 7\u20135 a sharp pain in her left arm forced her to retire. This injury also took her out of The Rogers Cup. She then played the [[Summer Olympic Games]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Sports/wireStory/wozniacki-denmarks-flag-bearer-olympics-rio-36741572|title=Wozniacki to Be Denmark's Flag-Bearer at Olympics in Rio|work=[[ABC News]]|publisher=[[Associated Press]]|location=Copenhagen, Denmark|date=5 February 2016|accessdate=6 February 2016}}</ref> Dropping four games, she beat [[Lucie Hradecka]] but fell to Czech Petra Kvitov\u00e1 in the second round. She failed to win a match in the [[Connecticut Open (tennis)|Connecticut Open]] as she lost in the first round to young Latvian [[Jelena Ostapenko]]. However, Wozniacki's year turned around at the [[2016 US Open (tennis)|US Open]]. She slid past [[Taylor Townsend (tennis)|Taylor Townsend]] in three sets, then upset Svetlana Kuznetsova in round two. She then beat Monica Niculescu in two sets to reach the fourth round, in which she upended [[Madison Keys]] in two sets to reach the quarterfinals and then beat unseeded [[Anastasija Sevastova]] to enter the semifinals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/07/sports/tennis/07openwomen.html|title=Angelique Kerber and Caroline Wozniacki Advance to the Semifinals|first=Ben|last=Rothenberg|date=6 September 2016|publisher=|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> Wozniacki lost the semifinal to then-new No. 1 Angelique Kerber, in two sets, and resulting at the back of the top 30 for the first time since April of this year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/09/09/sports/tennis/angelique-kerber-defeats-caroline-wozniacki-make-us-open-final.html|title=Angelique Kerber Reaches the U.S. Open Final|first=Ben|last=Rothenberg|date=8 September 2016|publisher=|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki moved on to the [[2016 Toray Pan Pacific Open|Toray Pan Pacific Open]]. In the first round, Wozniacki defeated Belinda Bencic, who had defeated her the previous year, in three sets. In the second round, she defeated fourth seed Carla Suarez Navarro, then beat qualifier [[Magda Linette]] in straight sets. In the semifinals, Wozniacki defeated defending champion Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska, which sent her off to her first final since April of the previous year. In the final, she defeated Japanese player [[Naomi Osaka]] to win her 24th WTA title, and her first title since March 2015. This was also Wozniacki's first Premier-level title since 2012.\n\nWozniacki continued the Asian swing at the [[2016 Wuhan Open|Wuhan Open]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.wuhanopen.org/index.php/index-show-tid-55.html|title=Wuhan Open Player List|publisher=Wuhan Open|access-date=8 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910223415/http://en.wuhanopen.org/index.php/index-show-tid-55.html|archive-date=10 September 2016|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There, she had a good start, defeating Samantha Stosur in the first round. In the third round, Wozniacki faced Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska again, and this time, Radwa\u0144ska came out on top. Wozniacki then competed at the [[2016 China Open (tennis)|China Open]]. She cruised past her first two matches against Coco Vandeweghe and Roberta Vinci before going head to head with Radwa\u0144ska for the third time in three weeks. Radwa\u0144ska emerged victorious again, defeating Wozniacki in straight sets.\n\nWozniacki won her second title of the season and 25th title overall at the Hong Kong Open. She defeated Zheng Saisai, Heather Watson, Wang Qiang, Jelena Jankovic, add Kristina Mladenovic. This was the first time since 2012 that Wozniacki had won two WTA titles in a single season. With the win, Wozniacki returned to the top 20.\n\nWozniacki ended the season with a run at the [[2016 BGL Luxembourg Open|Luxembourg Open]]. The No. 2 seed had an easy first-round win against Madison Brengle, and survived a second-round encounter against Sabine Lisicki. She then was forced to retire in the quarterfinals due to sickness. Wozniacki did not play at the [[2016 WTA Elite Trophy|WTA Elite Trophy]] and ended her topsy-turvy season ranked No. 19 (having been as low as No. 74).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.tv2.dk/tennis/2016-10-24-surt-show-skadet-wozniacki-traekker-sig-fra-sidste-store-turnering|title=Injured Wozniacki retires from last major tournament|first=Henrik|last=Jensen|date=24 October 2016|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n===2017: WTA Finals crown and return to top 3===\nWozniacki began the year at the [[2017 ASB Classic|Auckland Open]] once again. This time, she was the No. 3 seed. She started out strong, breezing past [[Nicole Gibbs]] and Varvara Lepchenko, then lost in the quarterfinals to Julia G\u00f6rges in three sets, despite being up a set and a break. At the [[2017 Apia International Sydney|Apia International Sydney]], Wozniacki was seeded tenth. She played some solid tennis against Olympic gold medallist Monica Puig, winning in three sets. Wozniacki then defeated Yulia Putintseva in straight sets in a rematch of their 2016 Australian Open first-round clash. In the quarterfinals, she was defeated by Barbora Strycova in three close sets, despite twice being up a break in the final set.\n\nWozniacki was seeded 17th at the [[2017 Australian Open|Australian Open]]. She reached the third round, defeating [[Arina Rodionova]] and Donna Vekic, but lost to Johanna Konta in straight sets.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/konta-douses-japanese-threat-australian-open-015221316--ten.html|title=Konta sets up Australian Open blockbuster against Wozniacki|publisher=[[Yahoo!]]|date=19 January 2017|accessdate=20 January 2017|first=Martin|last=Parry}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki played at the [[2017 Qatar Total Open|Qatar Total Open]] sliding past [[Kiki Bertens]] and Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska in the first two rounds in straight sets. She then saved two set points in the first set to beat [[Lauren Davis]], before dispatching Monica Puig to reach the final. There she fell to the in-form Karol\u00edna Pl\u00ed\u0161kov\u00e1. From there she played at the [[2017 Dubai Tennis Championships|Dubai Championships]], also making the final there by beating [[Daria Kasatkina]], [[Viktorija Golubic]], [[Kateryna Bondarenko]], [[Catherine Bellis]] and Anastasija Sevastova respectively before losing to Elina Svitolina in straight sets in the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/article/6352898/title/svitolina-defeats-wozniacki-in-dubai-for-biggest-title-of-her-career-top-10-debut|title=Svitolina Defeats Wozniacki In Dubai For Biggest Title Of Her Career & Top 10 Debut|last=admin|date=25 February 2017|publisher=}}</ref> Despite runner-up finishes, Wozniacki rose back up to No. 14.\n\n[[File:Caroline Wozniacki 2017.jpg|thumb|left|Wozniacki during the 2017 BNP Paribas Open]]\nAt the [[2017 BNP Paribas Open|BNP Paribas Open]], Wozniacki beat Magda Linette, [[Kate\u0159ina Siniakov\u00e1]] and Madison Keys, not losing a set, to advance to the quarterfinals where she lost to Kristina Mladenovic. At the [[2017 Miami Open|Miami Open]], Wozniacki beat Varvara Lepchenko and Sorana C\u00eerstea in straight sets and then advanced to the quarterfinals with a retirement from Garbi\u00f1e Muguruza. In the quarterfinals, she beat Lucie \u0160af\u00e1\u0159ov\u00e1 in straight sets and in the semifinals, avenged her Doha loss to Karol\u00edna Pl\u00ed\u0161kov\u00e1 by beating her in three sets to advance to her first ever final in Miami and her first Mandatory final since 2013. She lost in straight sets to [[Johanna Konta]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/tennis/39468069|title=Johanna Konta beats Caroline Wozniacki to claim Miami Open title|date=1 April 2017|work=BBC Sport|access-date=2 April 2017|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki began her clay court season at the [[2017 Volvo Car Open|Volvo Car Open]]. She made it to the quarterfinals with straight-set wins over [[Annika Beck]] and [[Anastasia Rodionova]]. There she lost to Je\u013cena Ostapenko in straight sets. She next played at the [[2017 J&T Banka Prague Open|Prague Open]], beat [[Misaki Doi]] in the first round in straight sets, and lost to Ostapenko again in three sets despite having match point. Wozniacki next played at the [[2017 Mutua Madrid Open|Madrid Open]]. In the first round, she beat Monica Niculescu in three sets, then lost to Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro in three sets. In [[2017 Internationaux de Strasbourg|Strasbourg]], Wozniacki retired from her first match against [[Shelby Rogers]]. Wozniacki then played at the [[2017 French Open|French Open]] as the 11th seed. She beat [[Jaimee Fourlis]] in the first round in three sets, then beat [[Fran\u00e7oise Abanda]] without the loss of a game. In the third round, she beat [[CiCi Bellis]] in three sets and then went on to beat former champion Svetlana Kuznetsova in three sets to advance to the quarterfinals for the first time since 2010. She lost to eventual champion Je\u013cena Ostapenko for the third time in three sets.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |title=The Latest: Latvia's Ostapenko into French Open semifinals |work=abc news |agency=Associated Press |date=2017-06-06 |accessdate=2017-08-30 |url=http://abcnews.go.com/amp/Sports/wireStory/latest-french-open-womens-quarterfinals-started-47860794 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704213046/https://abcnews.go.com/amp/Sports/wireStory/latest-french-open-womens-quarterfinals-started-47860794 |archive-date=4 July 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWozniacki began her grass season at the [[2017 Aegon International Eastbourne|Aegon International]] with straight-set wins over Naomi Osaka and Elena Vesnina. In the quarterfinals, she came from a set and a double break down to beat Simona Halep and proceeded to beat Heather Watson in three sets to advance to her fourth final of the year where she lost to Karol\u00edna Pl\u00ed\u0161kov\u00e1 in straight sets. She then played at [[2017 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] as the fifth seed. She beat [[Timea Babos]] in three sets, recovering from a break down and grass court specialist [[Tsvetana Pironkova]] in straight sets. She then beat [[Anett Kontaveit]] in a come-from-behind three-set win which saw Kontaveit fail to serve for the match twice to advance to the fourth round for the sixth time. She lost to Coco Vandeweghe in straight sets.\n\nWozniacki competed in the [[2017 Swedish Open|Swedish Open]] and she made her fifth final of the year, beating [[Pauline Parmentier]], Viktorija Golubic, Kateryna Kozlova and [[Elise Mertens]] before falling to Katerina Siniakova in the final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/siniakova-seals-second-career-wta-title-bastad-ericsson-open-upsets-former-no1-wozniacki|title=A year after making her maiden WTA final in Bastad, Katerina Siniakova wins her second career title at the Ericsson Open, stunning former WTA World No.1 Caroline Wozniacki in straight sets.|first=WTA|last=staff|work=wtatennis.com|date=30 July 2017|access-date=30 July 2017}}</ref> Wozniacki began her hard-court season in [[2017 Rogers Cup|Rogers Cup]] in Toronto. Here she won her first ever match in Toronto defeating [[Ekaterina Alexandrova]] later in the quarterfinals she defeated the current world No. 1 for the first time, overcoming Karolina Pl\u00ed\u0161kov\u00e1 in three sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/caroline-wozniacki-scores-first-wta-no1-win-defeats-karolina-pliskova-toronto-epic-rogers-cup |title=Wozniacki scores first No.1 win, defeats Pliskova in Toronto epic|date=11 August 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>  Wozniacki eventually made her sixth final of 2017 yet again falling at this stage, this time to Elina Svitolina. This tipped Wozniacki back into the top 5. She then competed in the [[2017 Western & Southern Open|Cincinnati Open]] defeating Elena Vesnina and [[Ashleigh Barty]] before falling in the quarterfinals to world No. 1 Karolina Pl\u00ed\u0161kov\u00e1. At the [[2017 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], she defeated [[Mihaela Buz\u0103rnescu]], then lost to Ekaterina Makarova in the second round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/makarova-sends-wozniacki-tumbling-out-us-open |title=Makarova sends Wozniacki tumbling out US Open|date=31 August 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe then played at the [[2017 Toray Pan Pacific Open|Pan Pacific Open]], where she successfully defended her title by defeating Shelby Rogers, Dominika Cibulkova, Garbi\u00f1e Muguruza and Anastasia Pavlyuchenkova.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/wozniacki-waltzes-first-title-year-tokyo |title=Wozniacki waltzes to first title of the year in Tokyo|date=24 September 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> At the Wuhan Open she lost her opening match to [[Maria Sakkari]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/sakkari-shocks-tokyo-champion-wozniacki-wuhan |title=Sakkari shocks Tokyo champion Wozniacki in Wuhan|date=26 September 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> At the China Open, she lost in the third round to Petra Kvitova in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/kvitova-sees-wozniacki-complete-beijing-qf-lineup |title=Kvitova sees off Wozniacki to complete Beijing QF lineup|date=5 October 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> At the [[2017 Hong Kong Tennis Open|Hong Kong Open]], she won her first-round match against Eugenie Bouchard but withdrew from her next match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/defending-champ-wozniacki-zooms-past-bouchard-hong-kong |title=Defending champ Wozniacki zooms past Bouchard in Hong Kong|date=10 October 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2017 WTA Finals|WTA Finals]], Wozniacki beat Elina Svitolina for the first time after losing to her twice in finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/it-happened-wozniacki-waltzes-victory-over-svitolina |title=As it happened: Wozniacki waltzes to victory over Svitolina|date=23 October 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> She then defeated the world No. 1, Simona Halep, in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/it-happened-wozniacki-wows-against-halep |title=As it happened: Wozniacki wows against Halep|date=25 October 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> In her third and final match of round robin play, she was defeated by Caroline Garcia in three sets. Nonetheless, she still made the semifinals. In the semifinals, she beat Karolina Pliskova in straight sets to advance to the final for the first time since [[2010 WTA Tour Championships|2010]], where she finished runner-up.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/it-happened-wozniacki-sinks-pliskova-reach-final |title=As it happened: Wozniacki sinks Pliskova reach final|date=28 October 2017|accessdate=4 March 2017}}</ref> In the final, she beat Venus Williams for the first time to win the biggest title of her career. By virtue of her WTA Finals crown, she moved up to world No. 3 where she would finish the season, her highest year-end ranking since 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2017/oct/29/caroline-wozniacki-beats-venus-williams-wta-finals-singapore-tennis |title=Caroline Wozniacki beats Venus Williams to seal WTA Finals victory|date=29 October 2017|work=Guardian|accessdate=31 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2018: Australian Open champion and back to No. 1===\n{{main|2018 Caroline Wozniacki tennis season}}\nWozniacki began her season at the [[2018 ASB Classic|Auckland Open]] for the fourth straight year. She was the top seed and advanced into the final successfully, but she was defeated by the same opponent she lost to the previous year in the quarterfinals, Julia G\u00f6rges, in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/goerges-extends-streak-ousts-wozniacki-auckland-crown|title=Goerges extends streak, ousts Wozniacki for Auckland crown|publisher=WTA official|author=David Kane|date=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Caroline Wozniacki (Den) (24852316737) (2) (cropped2).jpg|thumb|Wozniacki practicing at the 2018 Australian Open]]\nAt the [[2018 Australian Open|Australian Open]], Wozniacki was seeded second, her highest seeding [[2012 Australian Open|since 2012]]. She defeated Mihaela Buz\u0103rnescu in straight sets and then beat [[Jana Fett]] in three sets after being down 1\u20135 in the third set and saving two match points.<ref>{{cite web| title=Wozniacki saves match points against Fett in Melbourne epic | url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/wozniacki-saves-match-points-against-fett-melbourne-epic | date = 17 January 2018 | accessdate = 27 January 2018}}</ref> She then beat Kiki Bertens and Magdal\u00e9na Ryb\u00e1rikov\u00e1 both in straight sets to reach the quarterfinals, where she beat Carla Su\u00e1rez Navarro in three sets to advance to her second Australian Open semifinal since [[2011 Australian Open|2011]]. In the semifinals, she beat Elise Mertens in straight sets to advance to her third Grand Slam final and her first since [[2014 US Open (tennis)|2014]]. She then defeated top seed and world No. 1 Simona Halep in three sets, to become [[List of Grand Slam related tennis records#Won a title after saving match points|the ninth woman to win the title after being match point down]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ausopen.com/articles/match-report/great-dane-wozniacki-wins-maiden-slam |title=Great Dane: Wozniacki wins maiden Slam |publisher=Tennis Australia |first=Linda |last=Pearce |date= |accessdate=27 January 2018}}</ref> By winning her first Grand Slam title, she regained the world No. 1 ranking on 29 January 2018 after a gap of exactly six years, which bested Serena Williams' previous record of five years 29 days.<ref name=\"Piers Newberry\"/><ref name=\"WTA Tennis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/caroline-wozniacki-becomes-new-wta-world-no1-after-australian-open-overtakes-simona-halep |title=Wozniacki overtakes Halep to return to WTA World No.1 |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=27 January 2018|accessdate=28 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nHer next tournament was the [[2018 St. Petersburg Ladies' Trophy|St. Petersburg Ladies' Trophy]], which she entered in the second round. She defeated [[Anastasia Potapova]], then lost to Daria Kasatkina in the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/kasatkina-knocks-no1-wozniacki-st-petersburg |title=Kasatkina knocks off No.1 Wozniacki in St. Petersburg |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=2 February 2018|accessdate=3 February 2018}}</ref> She then played the [[2018 Qatar Total Open|Qatar Open]] and reached the semifinals by defeating [[Carina Witth\u00f6ft]], Monica Niculescu and Angelique Kerber. However, she lost to the eventual champion Petra Kvitov\u00e1 in three sets despite having three match points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/kvitova-roars-past-wozniacki-gets-muguruza-doha-final |title=Petra Kvitova came back from a set down to out-hit World No.1 Caroline Wozniacki and take her place in the Qatar Total Open final, where Garbine Muguruza awaits. |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=17 February 2018|accessdate=18 February 2018}}</ref> With her Qatar performance, Caroline Wozniacki became only the fourth player in WTA history to surpass $30,000,000 in career prize earnings.<ref name=\"Prize Money\">{{cite news|url=http://wtafiles.wtatennis.com/pdf/rankings/All_YTD_Prize_Money.pdf |title=All_YTD_Prize_Money |work=wta.com |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=22 March 2018|accessdate=22 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki then played the [[2018 BNP Paribas Open|BNP Paribas Open]] at Indian Wells, where she received a bye in the first round. She defeated [[Lara Arruabarrena]] and [[Aliaksandra Sasnovich]] in straight sets and three sets respectively, then lost to eventual finalist Daria Kasatkina again in the fourth round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/kasatkina-grounds-wozniacki-again-reach-indian-wells-qf |title=Kasatkina grounds Wozniacki again to reach Indian Wells QF |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=14 March 2018|accessdate=16 March 2018}}</ref> A week later, she entered the [[2018 Miami Open|Miami Open]], where she also received a bye in the first round. However, she lost to the [[Tennis at the 2016 Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] champion Monica Puig in three sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/puig-bounces-back-bagel-stuns-wozniacki-miami |title=Puig bounces back from bagel, stuns Wozniacki in Miami |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=24 March 2018|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki began her clay court swing at the Istanbul Cup where she made the quarterfinals defeating [[Ekaterina Alexandrova]] and Sara Errani before retiring against [[Pauline Parmentier]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/parmentier-advances-past-injured-wozniacki-istanbul |title=Parmentier advances past injured Wozniacki in Istanbul |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=27 April 2018|accessdate=27 April 2018}}</ref> She then played in the [[2018 Mutua Madrid Open|Mutua Madrid Open]] where she easily beat [[Daria Gavrilova]] and escaping Ashleigh Barty, then lost to the eventual finalist Kiki Bertens in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/bertens-ends-wozniacki\u2019s-bid-world-no1-madrid |title=Bertens ends Wozniacki's bid for World No.1 in Madrid |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=9 May 2018|accessdate=11 May 2018}}</ref> Heading to Rome for the first time in three years, Wozniacki made the quarterfinals. There she received a first round bye then defeating [[Alison Van Uytvanck]] and Anastasija Sevastova but got defeated by an in form Anett Kontaveit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/kontaveit-upsets-wozniacki-secure-rome-semifinal-spot |title=Kontaveit upsets Wozniacki to secure Rome semifinal spot |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=18 May 2018|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref> In the [[2018 French Open|French Open]], she made it to the fourth round. However, she lost to Daria Kasatkina in straight sets after the match was interrupted for bad light.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/kasatkina-completes-wozniacki-stunner-roland-garros |title=Kasatkina completes Wozniacki stunner at Roland Garros |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=4 June 2018|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe played at [[2018 Eastbourne International|Eastbourne]], where she went one better than last year winning the title; she convincingly beat [[Camila Giorgi]] in round two.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/wozniacki-rolls-past-giorgi-first-match-grass |title=Wozniacki rolls past Giorgi in first match on grass |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=25 June 2018|accessdate=25 June 2018}}</ref> Next she got her first-ever win over Johanna Konta and then defeated Ashleigh Barty in the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/wozniacki-rallies-eastbourne-konta-clash |title=Wozniacki rallies in Eastbourne Konta clash |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=27 June 2018|accessdate=27 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/wozniacki-bests-barty-eastbourne-quarterfinals |title=Wozniacki bests Barty in Eastbourne quarterfinals |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=28 June 2018|accessdate=28 June 2018}}</ref> Wozniacki then went on to save a match point to outlast Angelique Kerber to make her 53rd WTA final.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/wozniacki-saves-match-point-kerber-win-eastbourne |title=Wozniacki saves match point in Kerber win at Eastbourne |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=29 June 2018|accessdate=29 June 2018}}</ref> In the final, she beat [[Aryna Sabalenka]] in two tight sets to win her 29th title of her career. The final marked her 600th career match-win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/wozniacki-dodges-sabalenka-claim-eastbourne-title |title=Wozniacki dodges Sabalenka to claim Eastbourne title |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=30 June 2018|accessdate=30 June 2018}}</ref> At [[2018 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]], Wozniacki lost in second round to Ekaterina Makarova, after saving five match points.<ref>{{cite web| title=Makarova upsets Wozniacki at Wimbledon; Halep remains No.1 | url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/makarova-upsets-wozniacki-wimbledon-halep-remains-no1 | date = 4 July 2018 | accessdate = 4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki was scheduled to start her [[2018 US Open Series]] in [[2018 Citi Open|Washington]], but withdrew due to a right leg injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/wozniacki-withdraws-washington |title=Wozniacki withdraws from Washington |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=16 August 2018|accessdate=16 August 2018}}</ref> Instead, she played in the [[2018 Rogers Cup|Canadian Open]], where she received a bye in the first round. However, she lost to Aryna Sabalenka in three sets despite having three match points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/surging-sabalenka-wraps-wozniacki-comeback-montreal |title=Surging Sabalenka wraps up Wozniacki comeback in Montreal |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=10 August 2018|accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref> One week later, in [[2018 Western & Southern Open|Cincinnati]], she retired against [[Kiki Bertens]] in her first match of the tournament because of a left knee injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/bertens-advances-over-injured-wozniacki-cincinnati |title=Bertens advances over injured Wozniacki in Cincinnati |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=1 August 2018|accessdate=31 July 2018}}</ref> In the [[2018 US Open (tennis)|US Open]], Wozniacki defeated 2011 champion Samantha Stosur in straight sets, then lost to [[Lesia Tsurenko]] in the second round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/tsurenko-serves-wozniacki-upset-us-open |title=Tsurenko serves up Wozniacki upset at US Open |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=31 August 2018|accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nComing into the East Asian season, Wozniacki participated in the [[2018 Toray Pan Pacific Open|Pan Pacific Open]] as the defending champion, but she lost to Camila Giorgi in three sets in the second round after receiving a bye.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/giorgi-shocks-defending-champ-wozniacki-tokyo |title=Giorgi shocks defending champ Wozniacki in Tokyo |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=20 September 2018|accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref> Then in [[2018 Wuhan Open|Wuhan]], Wozniacki was upset by Monica Puig for the second time this season in straight sets in the third round].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/puig-upsets-wozniacki-again-reach-wuhan-quarters |title=Puig upsets Wozniacki again to reach Wuhan quarters |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=26 September 2018|accessdate=26 September 2018}}</ref> A week later, in Beijing, Wozniacki won her second [[2018 China Open (tennis)|China Open]] title without losing a set.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/wozniacki-holds-sevastova-win-second-china-open |title=Wozniacki holds off Sevastova to win second China Open |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=7 October 2018|accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref> With her performance in China, she became the fifth player to secure [[2018 WTA Finals|Singapore]] spot.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/kvitova-wozniacki-book-spots-2018-wta-finals-singapore |title=Kvitova, Wozniacki book spots at 2018 WTA Finals Singapore |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=4 October 2018|accessdate=4 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nWozniacki entered the [[2018 WTA Finals|WTA Finals]] as second seed and defending champion, and was drawn in the White Group. She was upset in straight sets in her first round robin match by seventh seed Karol\u00edna Pl\u00ed\u0161kov\u00e1, then defeated fourth seed Petra Kvitov\u00e1 in three sets. She was then defeated in three sets by sixth seed Elina Svitolina, ending her title defense. Shortly after, she revealed she had been diagnosed with [[rheumatoid arthritis]] before the [[2018 US Open (tennis)|US Open]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/caroline-wozniacki-diagnosed-rheumatoid-arthritis-us-open|title=Caroline Wozniacki diagnosed with rheumatoid arthritis before US Open|publisher=WTA Tennis |date=25 October 2018|accessdate=26 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2019: Playing with injuries===\nWozniacki began her season at the [[2019 ASB Classic|Auckland Open]] for the fifth straight year, but she was upset in the second round by [[Bianca Andreescu]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wtatennis.com/news/andreescu-serves-wozniacki-stunner-auckland|title=Andreescu serves up Wozniacki stunner in Auckland|publisher=WTA official|date=3 January 2019}}</ref> In [[2019 Australian Open|Melbourne]], she made to the third round but lost to Maria Sharapova in three sets.<ref name=\"2019 AO\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wtatennis.com/news/steely-sharapova-dethrones-wozniacki-aussie-epic |title=Steely Sharapova dethrones Wozniacki in Aussie epic |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=18 January 2019 |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> Due to viral illness, she withdrew from [[2019 Qatar Total Open|Doha]] and [[2019 Dubai Tennis Championships|Dubai]], which dropped her out of the top ten.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wtatennis.com/news/wozniacki-withdraws-dubai-due-viral-illness |title=Wozniacki withdraws from Dubai due to viral illness |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=18 February 2019 |accessdate=19 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2019 BNP Paribas Open|Indian Wells]], she lost to [[Ekaterina Alexandrova]] in three tight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wtatennis.com/news/alexandrova-stuns-wozniacki-lengthy-indian-wells-upset |title=Alexandrova stuns Wozniacki in lengthy Indian Wells upset|publisher=WTA Tennis |date=10 March 2019 |accessdate=11 March 2019}}</ref> In [[2019 Miami Open|Miami]], she made it to the fourth round by beating [[Aliaksandra Sasnovich]] and [[Monica Niculescu]], but lost to [[Hsieh Su-wei]] in three sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wtatennis.com/news/hsieh-shimmies-past-wozniacki-miami-quarters |title=Hsieh shimmies past Wozniacki into Miami quarters |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=25 March 2019 |accessdate=7 April 2019}}</ref> In April, she began her clay court season by making the final at the [[Charleston Open]], but lost to [[Madison Keys]] in two tough sets.<ref>{{cite web |title=Keys conquers Wozniacki to claim Charleston championship |url=https://www.wtatennis.com/news/keys-conquers-wozniacki-claim-charleston-championship |website=WTA Tennis |accessdate=7 April 2019}}</ref>\nWozniacki ended her season without winning a title for the first time since 2007. In December, Wozniacki announced that she was going to retire from tennis after the [[2020 Australian Open]] where she won her first and only grand slam title.\n\n===2020: Australian series: Farewell tour===\nWozniacki reached the semifinals of the [[2020 ASB Classic|ASB Classic]] beating Hourigan, Davis, two-time defending champion [[Julia G\u00f6rges]], before losing to eventual finalist [[Jessica Pegula]]. She also reached the finals of the doubles tournament alongside Serena Williams.\n\nHer farewell tournament was the [[2020 Australian Open|Australian Open]]. She bowed out in the third round in a loss to Tunisian [[Ons Jabeur]].<ref>{{cite web| title='She really inspired me' - Wozniacki's career ends with Jabeur defeat | url=https://www.wtatennis.com/news/1587494/wozniacki-s-career-ends-with-jabeur-defeat-in-melbourne | work=WTA Tennis | date = 24 January 2020 | accessdate = 28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n===Outside tennis===\nWozniacki's best friend is her fellow Danish tennis player [[Malou Ejdesgaard]], who was her doubles partner in five tournaments.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carolinewozniacki.dk/?p=339 |title=Caroline's Blog: Hello from Ponte Vidra, Florida |author=Caroline Wozniacki |work=Caroline Wozniacki Official Web site |date=6 April 2010 |accessdate=11 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222060310/http://www.carolinewozniacki.dk/?p=339 |archivedate=22 December 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Wozniacki is also close friends with [[Serena Williams]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/early-lead/wp/2014/11/05/serena-williams-caroline-wozniacki-continue-their-bffs-tour-of-new-york-city/ |title=Serena Williams, Caroline Wozniacki continue their BFFs tour of New York City|date=May 11, 2014|work=The Washington Post}}</ref> [[Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska]] and [[Angelique Kerber]]. Wozniacki was one of the few tennis stars to attend Williams' wedding.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-5092153/Caroline-Wozniacki-dazzles-joins-NFL-player-fianc.html|title=Tennis pro Caroline Wozniacki dazzles as she joins NFL player fianc\u00e9|work=Daily Mail|date=17 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Relationships===\nWozniacki was in a relationship with Northern Irish professional golfer [[Rory McIlroy]] from 2011 until 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=McIlroy says arm fine, confirms dating Wozniacki|url=http://www.golf.com/golf/tours_news/article/0,28136,2090509,00.html?sct=hp_t2_a20&eref=sihp|archive-url=https://archive.today/20120731130645/http://www.golf.com/golf/tours_news/article/0,28136,2090509,00.html?sct=hp_t2_a20&eref=sihp|url-status=dead|archive-date=31 July 2012|work=Golf Magazine|date=25 August 2011|accessdate=26 August 2011}}</ref> She announced their engagement via Twitter on 1 January 2014.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=CaroWozniacki|author=Caroline Wozniacki|number=418141047152078848|date=31 December 2013|title=Happy New Year everyone! Rory and I started 2014 with a bang! ... I said YES!!!!}}</ref> On 21 May 2014, it was announced that McIlroy had ended the engagement: \"The problem is mine. The wedding invitations issued at the weekend made me realise that I wasn't ready for all that marriage entails. I wish Caroline all the happiness she deserves and thank her for the great times we've had.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.independent.ie/woman/celeb-news/its-over-rory-mcilroy-ends-engagement-to-caroline-wozniacki-30292782.html |title=McIlroy claims Wozniacki split was 'amicable and mutual' |newspaper=Irish Independent |first1=Caitlin |last1=McBride |first2=Cormac |last2=Byrne |date=21 May 2014}}</ref> Wozniacki later revealed that McIlroy had ended the relationship through a brief phone call, and had not contacted her since.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2014/sep/11/caroline-wozniacki-rory-mcilroy-split-phone-call |title=Caroline Wozniacki opens up over end of relationship with Rory McIlroy |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London |date=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/its-all-off-the-engagement-between-caroline-wozniacki-and-rory-mcilroy-has-ended/ |publisher=evoke.ie |title=Break point: The engagement between Caroline Wozniacki and Rory McIlroy is Off |date=21 May 2014 |access-date=4 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150204141455/http://www.evoke.ie/showbiz/its-all-off-the-engagement-between-caroline-wozniacki-and-rory-mcilroy-has-ended/ |archive-date=4 February 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 14 February 2017, Valentine's Day, Wozniacki revealed on her social media accounts that she was in a relationship with former NBA champion [[David Lee (basketball)|David Lee]], later being confirmed by her family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bt.dk/tennis/nu-bekraefter-familien-ja-caroline-har-faaet-ny-kaereste|title=Nu bekr\u00e6fter familien: Ja, Caroline har f\u00e5et ny k\u00e6reste|publisher=|date=14 February 2017}}</ref> The couple got engaged on 2 November 2017.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=CaroWozniacki|author=Caroline Wozniacki|number=926478812887449601|date=3 November 2017|title=Happiest day of my life yesterday saying yes to my soulmate\u2764\ufe0f\ud83d\udc8d @Dlee042}}</ref> Wozniacki married Lee on 16 June 2019 in [[Tuscany]]. [[Serena Williams]] was one of her bridesmaids while [[Angelique Kerber]], [[Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska]] and [[Urszula Radwa\u0144ska]] were all among the guests. Also in attendance at the ceremony were Williams\u2019 husband [[Alexis Ohanian]], basketball players [[Pau Gasol]] and [[Harrison Barnes]], and football player [[Jesse Palmer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wtatennis.com/news/caroline-wozniacki-marries-david-lee-tuscany|title=Caroline Wozniacki marries David Lee in Tuscany|last=publisher_wta2|date=2019-06-16|website=WTA Tennis|language=en|access-date=2019-06-16}}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nIn October 2018, Wozniacki announced that she was diagnosed with [[rheumatoid arthritis]], but would like to become a role model for people with the condition.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/tennis/45984375|title=Caroline Wozniacki: Former world number one reveals 'shock' over arthritis diagnosis|work=BBC News|date=25 October 2018}}</ref> She was diagnosed with the auto-immune disease before the [[2018 US Open (tennis)|2018 US Open]], but was able to play through it. Wozniacki did suffer a drop in results after her diagnosis, until bouncing back by winning the 2018 [[China Open (tennis)|China Open]] in Beijing without dropping a single set.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/champions-corner-caroline-wozniacki-has-one-more-dream-after-notching-30th-title |title=Champion's Corner: Caroline Wozniacki has one more dream after notching 30th title |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=7 October 2018|accessdate=7 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Rivalries==\n===Wozniacki vs. S. Williams===\nWozniacki and [[Serena Williams]] have met 11 times with Williams leading the head to head 10\u20131.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/head2head/player1/9044/player2/12631|title=Williams \u2013 Wozniacki Head 2 Head|author=WTA|accessdate=4 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210083919/http://www.wtatennis.com/head2head/player1/9044/player2/12631|archivedate=10 February 2015|df=dmy-all|author-link=Women's Tennis Association}}</ref> Williams leads 2\u20130 in Grand Slams, 8\u20131 on hard courts, and 1\u20130 on both clay and grass. Both held the No. 1 ranking from early November 2009 to late January 2012. They are currently the top 2 active players to hold the No. 1 ranking for the most weeks.\n\nThey first met at the [[2009 Medibank International Sydney]] with Williams winning in three tight sets saving match points. Wozniacki's only win over Williams came at the [[2012 Sony Ericsson Open]] where she won in straight sets. In 2014 the rivalry reached its peak with the pair meeting four times and Williams winning all of them. Three of their four meetings went to three sets with Williams coming from a set down in each to win. At the [[2014 Rogers Cup|Rogers Cup]] Wozniacki led by a set and a break before Williams came back to win it. They met a week later at the [[2014 Western & Southern Open|Western & Southern Open]] where Williams again came from a set down to win. They faced off against each other in the final at the [[2014 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|US Open]] where Williams won in straight sets to claim her 18th Grand Slam title. Their most recent meeting at the [[2014 WTA Finals|WTA Finals]] was an epic with Wozniacki winning the first set before Williams came back to win the second set. At 4\u20134 Wozniacki broke Williams to serve for the match and Williams broke back. At 6\u20135 Wozniacki saved match point with an incredible volley and held serve to take the set to a tiebreak. In the tiebreak, Wozniacki was up 4\u20131 before Williams came back and eventually prevailed.\n\nDespite being rivals, the two maintain a strong friendship off court.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vogue.com/12135713/serena-williams-april-cover-caroline-wozniacki|title=Why Serena Williams Is Best Friends with Her Fiercest Competitor|date=21 March 2015|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> Wozniacki visited Williams during her recovery from injury in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/tennis/2011-03-15-serena-williams-interview_N.htm|title=Serena Williams depressed but determined to return to top|date=17 March 2011|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> In 2014, it was announced that McIlroy had ended his engagement with Wozniacki just days prior to the [[2014 French Open|French Open]]. Wozniacki received a call from her best friend Williams then in time of need. After they both lost early at the French Open, they went on vacation in Miami. They attended a Mariah Carey concert the night before their semifinal match at the [[2014 WTA Finals|WTA Finals]]. Williams was present during Wozniacki's run at the 2014 New York City Marathon. They also went on a mini tour around New York City.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/early-lead/wp/2014/11/05/serena-williams-caroline-wozniacki-continue-their-bffs-tour-of-new-york-city|title=Serena Williams, Caroline Wozniacki continue their BFFs tour of New York City|date=5 November 2014|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref> Wozniacki attended Williams' wedding in 2017. Williams served as a bridesmaid at Wozniacki's wedding in 2019. In 2018, Williams posted an Instagram story during [[2018 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|US Open]] with the caption \"Auntie Caro\" as her daughter Olympia watches her match against Stosur.<ref>[https://www.instagram.com/p/BedMCDdnbCf/] instagram:olympiaohanian</ref> Wozniacki will play her last top level match in her career against Williams on May 18th, 2020 in Copenhagen.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B58hVohIavm/|title=&nbsp; |author=Caroline Wozniacki |date=2019-12-11 |website=Instagram |publisher= |access-date=2019-12-11 |quote=My final match, May 18th, 2020 in Royal Arena in Copenhagen! Playing against my dear friend @serenawilliams. |language= |trans-title=}}</ref>\n\n===Wozniacki vs. Radwa\u0144ska===\nWozniacki and [[Agnieszka Radwa\u0144ska]] have met 17 times with Wozniacki leading the head to head 11\u20136.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/head2head/player1/12631/player2/11530|title=Wozniacki \u2013 Radwanska Head 2 Head|author=WTA|accessdate=4 December 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210083923/http://www.wtatennis.com/head2head/player1/12631/player2/11530|archivedate=10 February 2015|df=dmy-all|author-link=Women's Tennis Association}}</ref> Wozniacki leads 9\u20136 on hard courts and 2\u20130 on clay.\n\nThey first met at the [[2007 Nordea Nordic Light Open]] with Radwa\u0144ska taking the victory in straight sets. After that win, Wozniacki won the next five matches before the streak snapped at the [[2012 Apia International Sydney]] where she lost in three sets. Radwa\u0144ska then won the next two matches before that streak was snapped at the [[2014 Western & Southern Open]] where she lost in straight sets. After this event, Wozniacki took another four consecutive wins, then she lost at the [[2016 Wuhan Open]] in straight sets. A week later, she lost again at the [[2016 China Open (tennis)|2016 China Open]] in straight sets. Their next two meetings were at the [[2017 Qatar Total Open]] and the [[2017 Rogers Cup]]. Wozniacki won both matches in straight sets.\n\n===Wozniacki vs. Sharapova===\nWozniacki and [[Maria Sharapova]] have met 11 times with Sharapova leading the head-to-head 7\u20134.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/head2head/player1/9376/player2/12631|title=Sharapova \u2013 Wozniacki Head 2 Head|author=WTA|accessdate=9 May 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210083925/http://www.wtatennis.com/head2head/player1/9376/player2/12631|archivedate=10 February 2015|df=dmy-all|author-link=Women's Tennis Association}}</ref> Wozniacki leads 2\u20131 in Grand Slams with two wins at the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] and one loss at the [[Australian Open]]. They are tied at 4\u20134 on hard courts, while Sharapova leads 3\u20130 on clay.\n\nThe pair first met at the [[2008 Qatar Total Open]] where Sharapova won in straight sets and then again at the [[2008 Rome Masters]]. Wozniacki then won the next two meetings to tie the head-to-head. Sharapova then won the next three meetings including their only meeting in a final at the [[2013 BNP Paribas Open]]. Wozniacki snapped the losing streak by beating Sharapova in three sets at the [[2014 US Open (tennis)|2014 US Open]] and would go on to the reach the final. They met again at the [[2014 WTA Finals]] where Wozniacki won in three sets in a marathon match that lasted over three hours. Their most recent meeting was at the [[2019 Australian Open]] where Sharapova won in three sets.<ref name=\"2019 AO\"/>\n\n===Wozniacki vs. Halep===\nWozniacki and [[Simona Halep]] have met seven times with Wozniacki leading the head to head 5\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/head2head/player1/313402/player2/314320|title=Wozniacki \u2013 Halep Head 2 Head|author=WTA|accessdate=3 February 2018|df=dmy-all|author-link=Women's Tennis Association}}{{dead link|date=March 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Wozniacki leads 3\u20132 on hard courts, 1\u20130 on both clay and grass courts and 1\u20130 in the Grand Slams.\n\nThey first met at the [[2012 Dubai Tennis Championships]] with Wozniacki winning in straight sets. Then, Halep won the next two matches, one at the [[2013 New Haven Open at Yale]] in straight sets and another one at the [[2015 Dubai Tennis Championships]] in three sets. Wozniacki then took a four-match winning streak over Halep, beginning at the [[2015 Stuttgart Open]] and including their most recent meeting at the [[2018 Australian Open]] in the final, where she defeated Halep in three sets to win her first [[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slam]] title and snatch the world No. 1 position from Halep.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2018/jan/27/caroline-wozniacki-wins-australian-open-title-after-epic-battle-with-halep|title= Caroline Wozniacki wins Australian Open title after epic battle with Halep|date=27 January 2018|work=Guardian|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Wozniacki vs. Karolina Pliskova===\nThe pair have met ten times in their career, with Wozniacki holding a 6\u20134 advantage over Pliskova, Wozniacki leads 6\u20133 on hard courts, Pliskova leading 1\u20130 on grass. They have never met at Grand Slam level.\n\nThe rivalry between Wozniacki and [[Karolina Pliskova]] didn't seem to brew very fast at the beginning of their meetings. The first three meetings occurred in 2013 and 2014 and all three meetings went the way of Wozniacki, all of which happening in three sets. Their rivalry really picked up in 2017 where the pair met six times, in this year their head to head record was 3\u20133 and each meeting would alternate the winner. The first meeting came in the final stage of [[2017 Qatar Total Open]], Pliskova winning is straight sets. A month later in the semifinals of [[2017 Miami Open]], Wozniacki took victory in three sets. Later, on the grass Pliskova took the [[2017 Aegon International Eastbourne]] title beating Wozniacki in straight sets. Their fourth meeting was arguably the match of the year, in the [[2017 Rogers Cup]] quarterfinals, where Wozniacki stormed back from 1\u20135 down in the first set and break down in the third set to take the victory. One week later, the pair met in the [[2017 Western & Southern Open]] quarterfinals where Pliskova dispatched a tired Wozniacki from making the final of Toronto the previous week. At the semifinal stage of the [[2017 WTA Finals]], Wozniacki won a marathon first set propelling her to a straight sets victory over Pliskova, and eventually lifting the title. The last meeting in 2018 occurred at the round robin of the [[2018 WTA Finals]] where Wozniacki was upset in straight sets.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtatennis.com/news/pliskova-serves-wozniacki-upset-white-group |title=Pliskova serves up Wozniacki upset in White Group |publisher=WTA Tennis |date=21 October 2018|accessdate=21 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{Main|Caroline Wozniacki career statistics}}\n\n===Grand Slam tournament finals===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n!Result\n!Year\n!width=160|Tournament\n!Surface\n!width=180|Opponent\n!width=140|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"| Loss || [[2009 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2009]] || [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] || Hard || {{flagicon|BEL}} [[Kim Clijsters]] || 5\u20137, 3\u20136\n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"| Loss || [[2014 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2014]] || US Open || Hard || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Serena Williams]] || 3\u20136, 3\u20136\n|- style=\"background:#ffc;\"\n|bgcolor=98fb98|Win|| [[2018 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2018]] || [[Australian Open]] || Hard || {{flagicon|ROU}} [[Simona Halep]] || [[2018 Australian Open \u2013 Women's singles final|7\u20136<sup>(7\u20132)</sup>, 3\u20136, 6\u20134]]\n|}\n\n===WTA Championships finals===\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Result\n!Year\n!width=160|Location\n!Surface\n!width=180|Opponent\n!width=140|Score\n|-bgcolor=ffffcc\n|bgcolor=FFA07A|Loss || [[2010 WTA Tour Championships \u2013 Singles|2010]] || [[WTA Finals|Qatar]] || Hard|| {{flagicon|BEL}} Kim Clijsters || 3\u20136, 7\u20135, 3\u20136\n|-bgcolor=ffffcc\n|bgcolor=98FB98|Win || [[2017 WTA Finals \u2013 Singles|2017]] || [[WTA Finals|Singapore]] || Hard (i) || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Venus Williams]] || 6\u20134, 6\u20134\n|}\n\n==Grand Slam performance timelines==\n{{Performance key|short=yes}}\n\n===Singles===\n{|class=wikitable style=text-align:center;\n|-\n!Tournament!![[2006 WTA Tour|2006]]!![[2007 WTA Tour|2007]]!![[2008 WTA Tour|2008]]!![[2009 WTA Tour|2009]]!![[2010 WTA Tour|2010]]!![[2011 WTA Tour|2011]]!![[2012 WTA Tour|2012]]!![[2013 WTA Tour|2013]]!![[2014 WTA Tour|2014]]!![[2015 WTA Tour|2015]]!![[2016 WTA Tour|2016]]!![[2017 WTA Tour|2017]]!![[2018 WTA Tour|2018]]!![[2019 WTA Tour|2019]]!![[2020 WTA Tour|2020]]!!SR!!W\u2013L!!Win%\n|-\n|align=left|{{nowrap| [[Australian Open]]}}\n|A\n|A\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2010 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"|[[2011 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|SF]]\n| style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2012 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|QF]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2013 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2014 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2015 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2016 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2017 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:lime;\"|[[2018 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|'''W''']]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2019 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2020 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n|1 / 13\n|36\u201312\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=36|lost=12}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[French Open]]\n| A\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2007 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2010 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|QF]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2011 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2012 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2013 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2014 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2015 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| A\n| style=\"background:#ffebcd;\"|[[2017 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|QF]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2018 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2019 French Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| A\n|0 / 12\n|21\u201312\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=21|lost=12}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]\n|[[2006 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles Qualifying|Q1]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2007 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2010 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2011 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2012 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2013 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2014 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2015 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2016 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2017 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2018 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2019 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| A\n|0 / 13\n|25\u201313\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=25|lost=13}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]\n| A\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2007 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|4R]]\n| style=\"background:#D8BFD8;\"|[[2009 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|F]]\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"|[[2010 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|SF]]\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"|[[2011 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|SF]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2012 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2013 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#D8BFD8;\"|[[2014 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|F]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2015 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:yellow;\"|[[2016 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|SF]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2017 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2018 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2019 US Open \u2013 Women's Singles|3R]]\n| A\n|0 / 13\n|38\u201313\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=38|lost=13}}\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background:#efefef;\"\n|style=text-align:left|Win\u2013Loss\n|0\u20130\n|2\u20133\n|10\u20134\n|13\u20134\n|15\u20134\n|{{nowrap|15\u20134}}\n|6\u20134\n|7\u20134\n|11\u20134\n|6\u20134\n|5\u20133\n|10\u20134\n|12\u20133\n|6\u20134\n|2\u20131\n|{{nowrap|1 / 51}}\n|{{nowrap|120\u201350}}\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=120|lost=50}}\n|}\n\n===Doubles===\n{|class=wikitable style=text-align:center;\n|-\n!Tournament!![[2007 WTA Tour|2007]]!![[2008 WTA Tour|2008]]!![[2009 WTA Tour|2009]]!![[2010 WTA Tour|2010]]!!SR!!W\u2013L!!Win%\n|-\n|align=left| [[Australian Open]]\n| A\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2010 Australian Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n|0 / 3\n|1\u20133\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=1|lost=3|integer=yes}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[French Open]]\n| A\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 French Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 French Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2010 French Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n|0 / 3\n|1\u20133\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=1|lost=3|integer=yes}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[The Championships, Wimbledon|Wimbledon]]\n| A\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2010 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n|0 / 3\n|2\u20133\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=2|lost=3|integer=yes}}\n|-\n|align=left| [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2007 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|1R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2008 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2009 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|3R]]\n| style=\"background:#afeeee;\"|[[2010 US Open \u2013 Women's Doubles|2R]]\n|0 / 4\n|4\u20134\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=4|lost=4|integer=yes}}\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background:#efefef;\"\n|style=text-align:left|Win\u2013Loss\n|0\u20131\n|2\u20134\n|3\u20134\n|3\u20134\n|0 / 13\n|8\u201313\n|{{tennis win percentage|won=8|lost=13}}\n|}\n\n==Achievements==\n{{Main|List of career achievements by Caroline Wozniacki}}\n:{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Time span\n!Selected records\n!Players matched\n!{{Tooltip|Ref|References}}\n|-\n|29 January 2012 \u2013 29 January 2018\n|The longest time for a female player to return to [[List of WTA number 1 ranked tennis players|world No. 1]]\n|'''Stands alone'''\n|<ref name=\"WTA Tennis\"/>\n|-\n|2008\u20132011\n|4 [[Connecticut Open (tennis)|Connecticut Open]] titles\n|[[Steffi Graf]]<br/>[[Venus Williams]]\n|\n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Denmark|Tennis}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.carolinewozniacki.com}}\n* {{WTA}}\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{Fed Cup player}}\n* {{IOC profile|caroline-wozniacki}}\n* {{SR/Olympics profile|wo/caroline-wozniacki-1}}\n* {{IMDb name|3226044}}\n\n{{Caroline Wozniacki}}\n{{Caroline Wozniacki start boxes}}\n{{Tennis World Number Ones (women)}}\n{{Australian Open women's singles champions}}\n{{Wimbledon girls' singles champions}}\n{{WTA Year-End Championships winners}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wozniacki, Caroline}}\n[[Category:Caroline Wozniacki| ]]\n[[Category:1990 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian Open (tennis) champions]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriates in Monaco]]\n[[Category:Danish expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Danish female tennis players]]\n[[Category:Danish people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in girls' singles]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in women's singles]]\n[[Category:Hopman Cup competitors]]\n[[Category:Knights of the Order of the Dannebrog]]\n[[Category:Olympic tennis players of Denmark]]\n[[Category:People from Monte Carlo]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Odense]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 2008 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 2016 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon junior champions]]\n[[Category:World No. 1 tennis players]]\n", "name_user": "Nardog", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:fixingDanish IPA", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caroline_Wozniacki"}
{"title_page": "Churchill College, Cambridge", "text_new": "{{short description|College of the University of Cambridge}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox residential college\n| university      = [[University of Cambridge]]\n| name            = Churchill College\n| abbreviation    = CHU<ref>{{cite journal |author=University of Cambridge |date=6 March 2019 |title=Notice by the Editor |url=https://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/reporter/2018-19/special/05/section1.shtml |journal=[[Cambridge University Reporter]] |volume=149 |issue=Special No 5 |pages=1 |access-date=20 March 2019 |author-link=University of Cambridge }}</ref>\n| shield          = Churchill College Crest - flat.png\n| shield_caption  = Arms of Churchill College\n| image           = cmglee_Cambridge_Churchill_College_entrance.jpg\n| scarf          = {{scarf|{{cells|3|#000}}{{cell|#F99}}{{cell|#630}}{{cell|#F99}}{{cells|3|#000}}{{cell|#F99}}{{cell|#630}}{{cell|#F99}}{{cells|3|#000}}}}\n| full_name      = \n| latin_motto    = \n| english_motto  = Forward\n| founder        = \n| named_for      = [[Winston Churchill]]\n| established    = 1958\n| old_names      = \n| location       = [[Storey's Way]] ([https://map.cam.ac.uk/Churchill+College map])\n| head_label     = Master\n| head           = [[Athene Donald|Dame Athene Donald]]\n| undergraduates = 450\n| graduates      = 280\n| sister_college = [[Trinity College, Oxford]]\n| homepage       = {{URL|http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/}}\n| jcr_label      = {{abbr|JCR|Junior Combination Room}}\n| jcr            = {{URL|http://jcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/}}\n| mcr_label      = {{abbr|MCR|Middle Combination Room}}\n| mcr            = {{URL|http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/}}\n| boat_club      = {{URL|http://www.churchillboatclub.org.uk/}}\n| endowment      = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]32.8m {{small|(as of 30 June 2017)}}<ref name=\"Churchill College Financial Statement 16/17\">{{cite web | url = http://www.clare.cam.ac.uk/data/uploads/about/strategicinformation/ClareCollegeFinancialStatements2016-17.pdf | title= Annual report and Financial Statements for the year ended 30 June 2017 | accessdate = 3 August 2018 | publisher = Churchill College, Cambridge}}</ref>\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.213|N|0.101|E|type:edu_region:GB|display=title}}\n| location_map = United Kingdom Cambridge\n}}\n[[File:cmglee_Cambridge_Churchill_College_archives_centre_hall.jpg|thumb|Churchill Archives Centre and dining hall in June 2019]]\n[[File:Churchill College - geograph.org.uk - 38551.jpg|thumb|right|Main entrance and Dhruva Mistry sculpture]]\n\n'''Churchill College''' is a [[Colleges of the University of Cambridge|constituent college]] of the [[University of Cambridge]], [[England]]. It has a primary focus on science, engineering and technology, but still retains a strong interest in the arts and humanities.\n\nIn 1958, a trust was established with [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]] as its chairman of trustees, to build and endow a college for 60 fellows and 540 students as a national and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] memorial to Winston Churchill; its Royal Charter and Statutes were approved by the [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen]], in August 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/about/foi/schemes/Churchill_College_introduction_part_1_v2.pdf|title=Churchill College, Cambridge - Publication Scheme|accessdate=5 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607170546/http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/about/foi/schemes/Churchill_College_introduction_part_1_v2.pdf|archivedate=7 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is situated on the outskirts of [[Cambridge]], away from the traditional centre of the city, but close to the University's main [[West Cambridge|new development zone]] (which now houses the [[Centre for Mathematical Sciences (Cambridge)|Centre for Mathematical Sciences]]), which some would argue is the new city centre. Its {{convert|16|ha}} of grounds make it physically the largest of all the colleges.\n\nChurchill was the first all-male college to decide to admit women, and was among three men's colleges to admit its first women students in 1972.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/dick-tizard-510308.html|title=Dick Tizard, Obituary|accessdate=5 February 2010|work=The Independent|location=London|date=10 October 2005}}</ref> Within 15 years all others had followed suit. The college has a reputation for relative informality compared with other Cambridge colleges, and traditionally admits a larger proportion of its undergraduates from state schools.\n\nThe college motto is \"Forward\". It was taken from the final phrase of Winston Churchill's first speech to the House of Commons as Prime Minister \u2013 his famous \"Blood, Toil, Tears and Sweat\" speech \u2013 in which he said \"Come, then, let us go forward together\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.churchillconferences.co.uk/college.htm|title=Churchill College Hospitality - About Churchill College|accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 1955, on holiday in [[Sicily]] soon after his resignation as prime minister, Winston Churchill discussed with [[Jock Colville|Sir John Colville]] and [[Frederick Lindemann, 1st Viscount Cherwell|Lord Cherwell]] the possibility of founding a new institution. Churchill had been impressed by [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] and wanted a British version, but the plans evolved into the more modest proposal of creating a science and technology-based college within the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Walsh, James Jackson|title=Postgraduate Technological Education in Britain: Events Leading to the Establishment of Churchill College, Cambridge, 1950-1958|doi=10.1023/A:1004396018945|year=1998|journal=Minerva|volume=36|issue=2|pages=147\u2013177}}</ref> Churchill wanted a mix of non-scientists to ensure a well-rounded education and environment for scholars and fellows. The college therefore admits students to read all subjects except [[land economy]] and theology & religious studies (though it is possible to switch to these subjects later).\n\nThe first postgraduate students arrived in October 1960, and the first undergraduates a year later. Full college status was received in 1966. Initially all students were male. Women were not accepted as undergraduates until 1972.\n\nThe bias to science and engineering remains as policy to the current day, with the statutes requiring approximately 70% science and technology students amongst its student intake each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/about/official/statutes_and_ordinances/statutes.pdf|title=Churchill College Statutes (PDF)|date=1 January 2010|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> The college statutes also stipulate that one third of the students of the college should be studying for postgraduate qualification.\n\n[[Cambridge University Radio]] (later [[Cam FM]]) broadcast from Churchill College from 1979 until 2011.\n\n== Buildings and grounds ==\nIn 1958, a 42-acre (170,000 m\u00b2) site was purchased to the west of the city centre, which had previously been farmland. After a competition, [[Richard Herbert Sheppard|Richard Sheppard]] was appointed to design the new college.  Building was completed by 1968 with nine main residential courts, separate graduate flats and a central building consisting of the dining hall, buttery, combination rooms and offices.\n\nThe dining hall is the largest in Cambridge.  It measures 22m square, 9m to the base of the vault beams, and 11.6m to the highest point. It can cater for up to 430 guests in a formal dining arrangement.\n\nThe main college buildings and courtyards are arranged around a large central space, in which the library was placed. Only a few years later, being opened in 1974, an extension to the library building was added to house the Churchill Archives Centre. Its original purpose was to provide a home to Sir Winston's papers, however since then it has been endowed with papers from other political figures including former Prime Ministers [[Margaret Thatcher]] and [[John Major]], as well as former Leader of the Opposition [[Neil Kinnock]], and those of eminent scientists and engineers including [[Reginald Victor Jones]], [[Rosalind Franklin]] and [[Frank Whittle|Sir Frank Whittle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/archives/|title=Churchill Archive Centre|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:8118899-exterior3-max.jpg|thumb|The M\u00f8ller Centre for Continuing Education]]\nIn 1992, the [[Moller Centre|M\u00f8ller Centre for Continuing Education]] was built on the Churchill site, designed by [[Henning Larsen]]. It is a dedicated residential executive training and conference centre, aiming to bring together education and commerce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mollercentre.co.uk|title=The M\u00f8ller Centre|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs well as the main College buildings, Sheppard designed a separate group of flats, known as the Sheppard flats, for the use of married graduate students. These are located to one side of the College grounds, a short distance from the main buildings.\n\n=== Chapel ===\nAt the farthest end of the college grounds is the Chapel. Sheppard's original design placed it within the main building complex near the college main entrance.<ref>Goldie, M.; ''Corbusier Comes to Cambridge'', Churchill (2007).</ref> The idea of having a religious building within a modern, scientifically-oriented academic institution deeply annoyed some of the original fellows, leading to the resignation of [[Nobel Prize]] winner [[Francis Crick]] in protest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profiles.nlm.nih.gov/SC/Views/Exhibit/narrative/biographical.html|title=The Francis Crick Papers: Biographical Information|accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref> Eventually a compromise was found: the chapel was sited just to the west of the Sheppard Flats,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/about/visitors/map_of_college.php|title=Churchill College: Information: Map of College|accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref> and funded and managed separately from the rest of the College itself, being tactfully referred to as \"the Chapel ''at'' Churchill College\". The chimney of the heating system at the front of the college substitutes visually for the missing chapel tower.\n\nCrick had agreed to become a fellow on the basis that no chapel be placed at Churchill. A donation was later made by [[Lord Beaumont of Whitley]] to Churchill College for the establishment of one, and the majority of fellows voted in favour of it. Sir Winston Churchill wrote to him saying that no-one need enter the chapel unless they wished to do so, and therefore it did not need to be a problem. Crick, in short order, replied with a letter dated 12 October 1961 accompanied by a [[cheque]] for 10 [[Guinea (British coin)|guineas]] saying that, if that were the case, the enclosed money should be used for the establishment of a [[brothel]]. This story was repeated by Crick in an interview with [[Matt Ridley]] (Crick's biographer<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/sep/17/scienceandnature.biography|title=Observer review: Francis Crick by Matt Ridley|accessdate=5 February 2010|work=The Guardian|location=London|first=Robin|last=McKie|date=17 September 2006}}</ref>), quotes from which are reported in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/3306329/Do-our-genes-reveal-the-hand-of-God.html|title=Do our genes reveal the hand of God?|accessdate=5 February 2010|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|first=Roger|last=Highfield|date=20 March 2003}}</ref>\n\n=== Artworks and sculptures ===\n[[File:Churchill College, Hepworth.jpg|thumb|right|[[Barbara Hepworth|Hepworth]]'s ''[[Four-Square (Walk Through)]]'' (1966) is large enough for many students to work and play on\u2014which they are allowed to do]]\n[[File:Lynn Chadwick Geograph-685492-by-Fractal-Angel.jpg|thumb|''Beast Alerted 1'', by British sculptor [[Lynn Chadwick]]]]\n\nThe college contains many examples of modern artwork including:\n* ''[[Four-Square (Walk Through)]]'' (1966) \u2013 [[Barbara Hepworth|Dame Barbara Hepworth]]\n* Prints of [[Marilyn Monroe]] \u2013 [[Andy Warhol]]\n* ''Gemini'' (1973) \u2013 [[Denis Mitchell (sculptor)|Denis Mitchell]]\n* ''Diagram of an Object (Second state)'' (1990)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sculpture.org.uk/image/618830211087/43/|title=Dhruva Mistry|accessdate=5 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205025343/http://www.sculpture.org.uk/image/618830211087/43/|archivedate=5 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \u2013 [[Dhruva Mistry]]\n* ''Spiral'' \u2013 Michael Gillespie (1993)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/685470|title=Geograph:: Spiral, Michael Gillespie, 1991 (C) Fractal Angel|publisher=Geograph.org|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>\n* ''Flight'' \u2013 [[Peter Lanyon]] (1981)\n* ''Black Bag'' \u2013 [[Graham Murdoch]] (1990)\n\nThere are also works by [[Eduardo Paolozzi|Sir Eduardo Paolozzi]], [[Bridget Riley]], [[Patrick Caulfield]], [[Peter Blake (artist)|Sir Peter Blake]],  and [[Daphne Hardy Henrion]].\n\nMistry's piece can be found at the front of college. [[Anthony Caro|Sir Anthony Caro]]'s ''Forum''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anthonycaro.org/Gallery-Pic.asp?WorkID=2350|title=Anthony Caro - Forum|accessdate=5 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719030802/http://www.anthonycaro.org/Gallery-Pic.asp?WorkID=2350|archive-date=19 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> used to stand near it but it was removed before the start of the 2004\u20132005 academic year.  In January 2007 its place was taken by ''Beast Alerted 1'', a sculpture by British sculptor [[Lynn Chadwick]].\n\n== Student life ==\nThe student population is divided into two [[Common Room (university)|common rooms]]: the Junior Common Room (JCR) and Middle Common Room (MCR). The former contains undergraduates and the latter postgraduates (known as ''advanced students''). Fourth year undergraduates studying towards their [[Master's degree in Europe#Undergraduate Master's Courses|Masters]] may choose to be in either.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/?page_id=25#Advanced_Student|title=Churchill MCR: What is an Advanced Student?|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> These student bodies organise various academic and social events as well as handling issues regarding welfare. The college funds sports clubs and societies which provide entertainment for students.\n\n[[File:Students on Hepworth, Churchill College.jpg|thumb|right|Students relaxing on 'The Hepworth' following a formal]]\n\n=== Social events ===\nEvery two weeks of the Michaelmas and Lent terms, and twice in Easter term, Churchill is host to Pav, a music event unusual for Cambridge events in that it is free and open to all university members. The name Pav originates from the pavilion buildings of the college where the event was originally held. Since 1992, Pav has been held in the Buttery, the main bar area.\n\nIn the early years of the college's foundation, the college held a ball in [[May Week]], in common with many older colleges. However, more recently Churchill has held a Spring Ball every February, close to [[Valentine's Day]]. The Ball has hosted a number of upcoming bands, such as [[The Wombats]] (2007) and [[The Noisettes]] (2008).\n\nDuring [[May Week]] the JCR organise a free [[garden party]]. The event hosts performances from local bands and musicians.\n\nStudents of the College run Churchill Casino,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.churchillcasino.co.uk|title=Churchill Casino|accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref> a Cambridge-based enterprise which provides professional casinos at various social events. Churchill Casino is frequently hired for [[May Ball|Cambridge May Balls]] as well as balls at the [[University of Oxford]] and corporate events throughout the country. Profits have been donated back towards the college and to local charities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Churchill Casino donates to Cam-mind at Churchill College event on 20th March 2012|url=http://www.cam-mind.org.uk/News/Story/Churchill-Casino-donates-to-Cam-mind-at-Churchill-College-event|work=Cam-mind News|accessdate=30 July 2012|date=22 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121224024033/http://www.cam-mind.org.uk/News/Story/Churchill-Casino-donates-to-Cam-mind-at-Churchill-College-event|archivedate=24 December 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe MCR has its own reserved area, the [[P. G. Ashmore|Sandy Ashmore]] Room, where students may socialise. This incorporates a student-run bar known as the Vicious Penguin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/?page_id=18|title=Churchill MCR: MCR Bar|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> The MCR organises a range of activities including an annual conference, the Conference on Everything, and hosts termly Guest Nights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/?page_id=21|title=Churchill MCR: Activities & Calendar|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> The Conference on Everything gives students an opportunity to present their own research as well as featuring talks from distinguished speakers including [[Salah Al-Shaikhly]], the [[Iraq]]i ambassador to the United Kingdom; [[Michael Green (physicist)|Michael Green]], [[Lucasian Professor of Mathematics|Lucasian Professor]] and pioneer of [[string theory]]; [[Julian Huppert]], scientist and [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for Cambridge; [[David Spiegelhalter]], [[Winton Professorship of the Public Understanding of Risk|Winton Professor]] of the Public Understanding of [[Risk]], and [[Nicholas Bingham]], Senior Investigator at [[Imperial College London]] and Visiting Professor of Mathematics at the [[London School of Economics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/?page_id=388|title=Churchill MCR: Conference on Everything|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Sport ===\n[[File:Churchill College Boat Club Fairairns M1.JPG|thumb|[[Churchill College Boat Club]] men's first VIII rowing past their boathouse on the [[River Cam]]. The club is noted for its pink boats.]]\nWith playing fields on site, unlike many other colleges, sport is an integral part of the college. As well as football pitches, a cricket pitch and others, the facilities include a gym, and tennis and squash courts.\n\nChurchill College Football Club (CCFC) were the first college team to retain the Cambridge University Amateur Football League Division 1 title, winning it in 2005\u201306 and 2006\u201307. In the 2006\u20132007 season they also reached the final of [[Cuppers]].{{citation needed|date=November 2009}}\n\nThe College also has a successful boat club ([[Churchill College Boat Club]]) which in 2013 won the [[Pegasus Cup]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miltonbrewery.co.uk/pegasus-cup/2013.html|title=Pegasus Cup 2013 \u2014 The Milton Brewery, Cambridge Ltd|publisher=The Milton Brewery, Cambridge Ltd|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> (This trophy is awarded annually to the most successful college boat club competing in the Cambridge May Bumping Races<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cucbc.org/handbook/pegasus_cup|title=Pegasus Cup - CUCBC|publisher=|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>). In 2015, Churchill College Boat Club made history by being the first boat club at the university to win both the Pegasus Cup and Marconi Cup (This award is present to the most successful college boat club in the Lent Bumps) in the same year.\n\n== Traditions ==\n[[File:Dining Hall, Churchill 2005.jpg|thumb|right|Churchill's Dining Hall is the largest in Cambridge.]]\nChurchill is a relatively young college, and prides itself on being modern and forward looking. It has relatively few traditions. Informal hall (cafeteria-style dining period) was introduced in 1971, as an alternative to formal hall (fixed time, waiter service, all diners wearing gowns), but students are no longer required to wear [[Academic dress of the University of Cambridge|gowns]] at formal halls,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/useful-stuff/faq/#Formals|title=Churchill College MCR Frequently Asked Questions|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> with exception of certain college feasts.\n\nIn special formal meals such as Matriculation Dinner or Scholars' Feast the Master usually raises a toast, first to [[Queen of the United Kingdom|The Queen]] and then to \"Sir Winston\". In other [[Formal Hall|formal halls]] this is usually made by a senior student once the [[fellow]]s have left. This latter tradition started in the early 2000s with the students customarily toasting in the reverse order: \"Sir Winston\", followed by \"The Queen\".\n\n== People associated with the college ==\n\n=== Masters ===\nThe Mastership of Churchill College is a [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Crown]] appointment. To date the College has had seven Masters:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Term of office\n!Notes\n|-\n| [[John Cockcroft|Sir John Cockcroft]]\n| 1959\u20131967\n| [[Nobel Prize|Nobel Laureate in Physics]], who split the atom.\n|-\n| [[William Hawthorne|Sir William Hawthorne]]\n| 1968\u20131983\n| Engineer who helped develop the [[jet engine]].\n|-\n| [[Hermann Bondi|Sir Hermann Bondi]]\n| 1983\u20131990\n| Cosmologist who helped develop the [[Steady State theory]] of the universe.\n|-\n| [[Alec Broers|Lord Alec Broers]]\n| 1990\u20131996\n| Nanotechnologist; later [[List of vice-chancellors of the University of Cambridge|Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge]] (1996-2003).\n|-\n| [[John Boyd (ambassador)|Sir John Boyd]] \n| 1996\u20132006\n| Formerly [[Heads of the United Kingdom Mission in Japan|British ambassador to Japan]] (1992\u20131996).\n|-\n| [[David Wallace (physicist)|Sir David Wallace]]\n| 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.number10.gov.uk/Page8002|title=Appointment of Master of Churchill College|accessdate=5 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616041413/http://www.number10.gov.uk/Page8002|archivedate=16 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\u20132014\n| Formerly Vice-chancellor of [[Loughborough University]] (1994\u20132005); Director of the [[Isaac Newton Institute|Newton Institute]] (2006\u20132011).\n|-\n| [[Athene Donald|Dame Athene Donald]]\n| 2014<ref>{{cite web|title=Appointment of Next Master of Churchill College|url=http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/about/news/315-appointment-of-next-master-of-churchill-college|work=Churchill College News|accessdate=2 October 2013}}</ref>\u2013present\n| Professor of experimental physics at the Cavendish Laboratory.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Donald|first1=A.|last2=Jacobsen|first2=S.D.|title=Dr. Athene Donald: Experimental Physicist, University of Cambridge|date=28 June 2013|journal=In-Sight|issue=2.A|pages=85\u201397|url=http://in-sightjournal.com/2013/06/28/dr-athene-donald-experimental-physicist-university-of-cambridge/}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Notable fellows ===\n''See also [[:Category:Fellows of Churchill College, Cambridge]]''\n* [[Michael Ashburner]] \u2013 Biologist, former head of the [[European Bioinformatics Institute]] and the [[European Molecular Biology Laboratory]]\n* [[Correlli Barnett]] \u2013 Military historian\n* [[Jacques Barzun]] \u2013 Historian and cultural critic; (Extraordinary Fellow at Churchill while also Provost, Dean of Graduate studies, and Dean of Faculties at Columbia.)\n* [[Piers Brendon]] \u2013 Writer and historian\n* [[Edward Bullard]] \u2013 Geophysicist, former head of the [[National Physical Laboratory (United Kingdom)|National Physical Laboratory]]\n* [[Edward Craig (philosopher)|Edward Craig]] \u2013 Philosopher\n* [[James Fox (art historian)|James Fox]] - Art historian and broadcaster\n* [[George Gamow]] \u2013 Cosmologist (overseas fellow)\n* [[Mark Goldie]] - Professor of Intellectual History\n*[[Priyamvada Gopal|Priya Gopal]] - Teaching fellow in colonial and postcolonial literature\n* [[Frank Hahn]] \u2013 Economist\n* [[Archie Howie]] \u2013 Physicist\n* [[Richard Keynes]] \u2013 Physiologist\n*[[Julia King, Baroness Brown of Cambridge]] - Engineer, former Vice-Chancellor of [[Aston University]]\n* [[John Kinsella (poet)|John Kinsella]] \u2013 Poet and novelist\n* [[Nigel Knight]] - Economist and political scientist\n* [[C. B. Macpherson]] \u2013 Political scientist\n* [[Peter Murray-Rust]] \u2013 Chemist\n* [[David Newbery]] \u2013 Economist \n* [[David Olive]] - Physicist\n*[[Nick Petford]] - Geologist and Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Northampton]]\n* [[Roy Porter]] \u2013 Historian and prolific author\n* [[Stephen Roskill]] \u2013 Naval historian\n* [[Andrew Sinclair]] \u2013 Historian, novelist and journalist\n* [[C. P. Snow]] \u2013 Physicist and novelist\n* [[George Steiner]] \u2013 Literary critic and linguistic theorist (Extraordinary Fellow at Churchill)\n* [[Colin St John Wilson|Sir Colin St John Wilson]] \u2013 Architect\n* [[David Spiegelhalter]] \u2013 Statistician\n* [[Dick Tizard]] \u2013 Engineer\n* [[Frank Gibbs Torto]] \u2013 Chemist\n* [[Melissa Hines]] \u2013 neuroscientist\n* [[Stuart Warren]] \u2013 organic chemist\n* [[Chandra Wickramasinghe]] \u2013 Physicist and Astrobiologist\n* [[Michael Young (politician)|Michael Young]] \u2013 Sociologist and politician\n* [[Ghil'ad Zuckermann]] \u2013 Linguist and revivalist\n* [[Sander van der Linden]] \u2013 Psychologist\n\n===Nobel laureates===\n[[File:Francis Crick crop.jpg|thumb|[[Francis Crick]]]]\n* [[Philip Warren Anderson]] \u2013 Physics, for the behaviour of electrons in magnetic solids, 1977\n* [[John Cockcroft]] \u2013 Physics, for using accelerated particles to study atomic nuclei, 1951\n* [[Francis Crick]] \u2013 co-discoverer of the structure of DNA, Medicine, 1962\n* [[Angus Deaton]] \u2013 Economics, 2015 (Overseas Fellow 1990\u20131): Analysis of consumption, poverty, and welfare\n* [[G\u00e9rard Debreu]] \u2013 Economics, 1983\n* [[Peter Diamond]] \u2013 Economics, 2010 (overseas fellow)\n* [[Robert G. Edwards]] \u2013 Physiology or Medicine, 2010\n* [[John Gurdon]] \u2013 Physiology or Medicine, 2012\n* [[Antony Hewish]] \u2013 co-discoverer of [[pulsar]]s, Physics, 1974\n* [[William Lipscomb]] \u2013 Chemistry, 1976 (overseas fellow)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wlipscomb.tripod.com/publications_biog_cv.html|title=CV - Biog - Publications - Lipscomb|publisher=|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Mario Vargas Llosa]] \u2013 Literature, 2010 (overseas fellow)\n* [[Eric Maskin]] \u2013 Economics, 2007 (overseas fellow)\n*[[Paul Nurse]] - Physiology or Medicine, 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/people/view/paul-nurse/|title=People \u2013 Churchill College|website=www.chu.cam.ac.uk|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref>\n* [[Wole Soyinka]] \u2013 Literature, 1986 (overseas fellow)\n* [[David Thouless]] \u2013 Physics, 2016 (Fellow 1961\u20135): Theoretical discoveries of topological phase transitions and topological phases of matter.\n* [[Roger Tsien]] \u2013 Chemistry, 2008\n\n=== Notable alumni ===\n''See also [[:Category:Alumni of Churchill College, Cambridge]]''\n[[File:Sal Brinton at Brighton 2013.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Liberal Democrat Peer [[Sarah Brinton, Baroness Brinton|Baroness Brinton]]]][[File:Helmer, Roger-9461.jpg|thumb|right|180px|UKIP MEP [[Roger Helmer]]]]\n* [[Kari Blackburn]] \u2013 [[BBC World Service]] executive\n* [[Sal Brinton|Baroness Brinton]] \u2013 [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] peer\n* [[Nick Brown (academic)|Nick Brown]] - Principal of [[Linacre College, Oxford]]\n* [[Michael Burrows]] \u2013 inventor of the first internet search machine, Alta Vista\n* [[Peter Fincham]] \u2013 former controller, [[BBC1]]\n* Sir [[Christopher Frayling]] \u2013 writer and educationalist\n* [[Mike Gascoyne]] \u2013 Chief technical officer of the [[Caterham F1]] Formula One team\n* Sir [[Peter Gershon]] \u2013 author of the [[Gershon Review]], chairman of [[Premier Farnell]] and [[Symbian Ltd.]]\n* [[John Warren Gladwin|John Gladwin]] \u2013 [[Bishop of Chelmsford]] and Chair of [[Citizens Advice]]\n* [[Michael Green (physicist)|Michael Green]] \u2013 [[Lucasian Chair]] of Mathematics\n* [[Charlie Hannaford (rugby union)|Charlie Hannaford]] \u2013 [[England national rugby union team|England]] rugby player\n* [[Roger Helmer]] \u2013 [[United Kingdom Independence Party|UK Independence Party]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]\n* [[Tianhui Michael Li|Michael Li]] \u2013 Founder, [[The Data Incubator]] and data scientist\n* [[Diarmaid MacCulloch]] \u2013 Historian\n* [[Christopher Walter Monckton, 3rd Viscount Monckton of Brenchley|Viscount Monckton]] \u2013 Writer and policy advisor to [[Margaret Thatcher]]\n* [[Simeon Nyachae]] \u2013 [[Kenya]]n minister and [[Elections in Kenya|2002 presidential candidate]]\n* [[Brendan O'Neill (businessman)|Brendan O'Neill]] \u2013 business executive\n* [[Andrew Parker (MI5 officer)|Andrew Parker]] - [[Director General of MI5|Director General]] of the [[Security Service (MI5)]]\n* [[David Pearson (computer scientist)|David Pearson]] - physicist and computer scientist\n* [[John-Luke Roberts|Luke Roberts]] \u2013 comedian\n*[[Philip Sales]] - [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]] Justice\n* [[Mark Smith (academic)|Mark Smith]] - Academic, Vice-Chancellor of [[Lancaster University]]\n* [[Ian Stewart (mathematician)|Ian Stewart]] \u2013 Mathematician\n* [[Gavin Strang]] \u2013 [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n* [[Bjarne Stroustrup]] \u2013 inventor of [[C++]]\n* [[John Stuttard|Sir John Stuttard]] \u2013 former [[Lord Mayor of London]]\n* [[Fabian Tassano]] \u2013 Economist and author\n* [[Geoffrey Thomas (academic)|Geoffrey Thomas]] \u2013 Former President of [[Kellogg College, Oxford]]\n* [[Geoff Travis]] \u2013 Founder of [[Rough Trade Records]] label and shops\n* [[Neil Turok]] \u2013 Mathematician\n* [[Stephen Tweedie]] \u2013 Software developer\n* [[Peter Wadhams]] - Oceanographer and glaciologist\n* [[Rick Warden]] \u2013 Actor ''[[Band of Brothers (TV miniseries)|Band Of Brothers]]'', ''[[Rome (TV series)|Rome]]''\n* [[Jeremy Warmsley]] \u2013 musician\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Churchill Scholarship]]s for fourteen graduates from the [[United States]].\n* [[Churchill College Boat Club]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/ College Website]\n* [http://jcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/ Churchill College JCR]\n* [http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/ Churchill College MCR]\n* [http://scr.chu.cam.ac.uk/ Churchill College SCR]\n* [http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/archives/ Archives Centre]\n\n{{University of Cambridge}}\n{{Winston Churchill|state=expanded}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Colleges of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Churchill College, Cambridge| ]]\n[[Category:Winston Churchill]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1958]]\n[[Category:1958 establishments in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|College of the University of Cambridge}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2012}}\n{{Infobox residential college\n| university      = [[University of Cambridge]]\n| name            = Churchill College\n| abbreviation    = CHU<ref>{{cite journal |author=University of Cambridge |date=6 March 2019 |title=Notice by the Editor |url=https://www.admin.cam.ac.uk/reporter/2018-19/special/05/section1.shtml |journal=[[Cambridge University Reporter]] |volume=149 |issue=Special No 5 |pages=1 |access-date=20 March 2019 |author-link=University of Cambridge }}</ref>\n| shield          = Churchill College Crest - flat.png\n| shield_caption  = Arms of Churchill College\n| image           = cmglee_Cambridge_Churchill_College_entrance.jpg\n| scarf          = {{scarf|{{cells|3|#000}}{{cell|#F99}}{{cell|#630}}{{cell|#F99}}{{cells|3|#000}}{{cell|#F99}}{{cell|#630}}{{cell|#F99}}{{cells|3|#000}}}}\n| full_name      = \n| latin_motto    = \n| english_motto  = Forward\n| founder        = \n| named_for      = [[Winston Churchill]]\n| established    = 1958\n| old_names      = \n| location       = [[Storey's Way]] ([https://map.cam.ac.uk/Churchill+College map])\n| head_label     = Master\n| head           = [[Athene Donald|Dame Athene Donald]]\n| undergraduates = 450\n| graduates      = 280\n| sister_college = [[Trinity College, Oxford]]\n| homepage       = {{URL|http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/}}\n| jcr_label      = {{abbr|JCR|Junior Combination Room}}\n| jcr            = {{URL|http://jcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/}}\n| mcr_label      = {{abbr|MCR|Middle Combination Room}}\n| mcr            = {{URL|http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/}}\n| boat_club      = {{URL|http://www.churchillboatclub.org.uk/}}\n| endowment      = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]32.8m {{small|(as of 30 June 2017)}}<ref name=\"Churchill College Financial Statement 16/17\">{{cite web | url = http://www.clare.cam.ac.uk/data/uploads/about/strategicinformation/ClareCollegeFinancialStatements2016-17.pdf | title= Annual report and Financial Statements for the year ended 30 June 2017 | accessdate = 3 August 2018 | publisher = Churchill College, Cambridge}}</ref>\n| coordinates = {{coord|52.213|N|0.101|E|type:edu_region:GB|display=title}}\n| location_map = United Kingdom Cambridge\n}}\n[[File:cmglee_Cambridge_Churchill_College_archives_centre_hall.jpg|thumb|Churchill Archives Centre and dining hall in June 2019]]\n[[File:Churchill College - geograph.org.uk - 38551.jpg|thumb|right|Main entrance and Dhruva Mistry sculpture]]\n\n'''Churchill College''' is a [[Colleges of the University of Cambridge|constituent college]] of the [[University of Cambridge]], [[England]]. It has a primary focus on science, engineering and technology, but still retains a strong interest in the arts and humanities.\n\nIn 1958, a trust was established with [[Winston Churchill|Sir Winston Churchill]] as its chairman of trustees, to build and endow a college for 60 fellows and 540 students as a national and [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] memorial to Winston Churchill; its Royal Charter and Statutes were approved by the [[Elizabeth II of the United Kingdom|Queen]], in August 1960.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/about/foi/schemes/Churchill_College_introduction_part_1_v2.pdf|title=Churchill College, Cambridge - Publication Scheme|accessdate=5 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607170546/http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/about/foi/schemes/Churchill_College_introduction_part_1_v2.pdf|archivedate=7 June 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is situated on the outskirts of [[Cambridge]], away from the traditional centre of the city, but close to the University's main [[West Cambridge|new development zone]] (which now houses the [[Centre for Mathematical Sciences (Cambridge)|Centre for Mathematical Sciences]]), which some would argue is the new city centre. Its {{convert|16|ha}} of grounds make it physically the largest of all the colleges.\n\nChurchill was the first all-male college to decide to admit women, and was among three men's colleges to admit its first women students in 1972.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/dick-tizard-510308.html|title=Dick Tizard, Obituary|accessdate=5 February 2010|work=The Independent|location=London|date=10 October 2005}}</ref> Within 15 years all others had followed suit. The college has a reputation for relative informality compared with other Cambridge colleges, and traditionally admits a larger proportion of its undergraduates from state schools.\n\nThe college motto is \"Forward\". It was taken from the final phrase of Winston Churchill's first speech to the House of Commons as Prime Minister \u2013 his famous \"Blood, Toil, Tears and Sweat\" speech \u2013 in which he said \"Come, then, let us go forward together\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.churchillconferences.co.uk/college.htm|title=Churchill College Hospitality - About Churchill College|accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 1955, on holiday in [[Sicily]] soon after his resignation as prime minister, Winston Churchill discussed with [[Jock Colville|Sir John Colville]] and [[Frederick Lindemann, 1st Viscount Cherwell|Lord Cherwell]] the possibility of founding a new institution. Churchill had been impressed by [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]] and wanted a British version, but the plans evolved into the more modest proposal of creating a science and technology-based college within the [[University of Cambridge]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Walsh, James Jackson|title=Postgraduate Technological Education in Britain: Events Leading to the Establishment of Churchill College, Cambridge, 1950-1958|doi=10.1023/A:1004396018945|year=1998|journal=Minerva|volume=36|issue=2|pages=147\u2013177}}</ref> Churchill wanted a mix of non-scientists to ensure a well-rounded education and environment for scholars and fellows. The college therefore admits students to read all subjects except [[land economy]] and theology & religious studies (though it is possible to switch to these subjects later).\n\nThe first postgraduate students arrived in October 1960, and the first undergraduates a year later. Full college status was received in 1966. Initially all students were male. Women were not accepted as undergraduates until 1972.\n\nThe bias to science and engineering remains as policy to the current day, with the statutes requiring approximately 70% science and technology students amongst its student intake each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/about/official/statutes_and_ordinances/statutes.pdf|title=Churchill College Statutes (PDF)|date=1 January 2010|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> The college statutes also stipulate that one third of the students of the college should be studying for postgraduate qualification.\n\n[[Cambridge University Radio]] (later [[Cam FM]]) broadcast from Churchill College from 1979 until 2011.\n\n== Buildings and grounds ==\nIn 1958, a 42-acre (170,000 m\u00b2) site was purchased to the west of the city centre, which had previously been farmland. After a competition, [[Richard Herbert Sheppard|Richard Sheppard]] was appointed to design the new college.  Building was completed by 1968 with nine main residential courts, separate graduate flats and a central building consisting of the dining hall, buttery, combination rooms and offices.\n\nThe dining hall is the largest in Cambridge.  It measures 22m square, 9m to the base of the vault beams, and 11.6m to the highest point. It can cater for up to 430 guests in a formal dining arrangement.\n\nThe main college buildings and courtyards are arranged around a large central space, in which the library was placed. Only a few years later, being opened in 1974, an extension to the library building was added to house the Churchill Archives Centre. Its original purpose was to provide a home to Sir Winston's papers, however since then it has been endowed with papers from other political figures including former Prime Ministers [[Margaret Thatcher]] and [[John Major]], as well as former Leader of the Opposition [[Neil Kinnock]], and those of eminent scientists and engineers including [[Reginald Victor Jones]], [[Rosalind Franklin]] and [[Frank Whittle|Sir Frank Whittle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/archives/|title=Churchill Archive Centre|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[File:8118899-exterior3-max.jpg|thumb|The M\u00f8ller Centre for Continuing Education]]\nIn 1992, the [[Moller Centre|M\u00f8ller Centre for Continuing Education]] was built on the Churchill site, designed by [[Henning Larsen]]. It is a dedicated residential executive training and conference centre, aiming to bring together education and commerce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mollercentre.co.uk|title=The M\u00f8ller Centre|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nAs well as the main College buildings, Sheppard designed a separate group of flats, known as the Sheppard flats, for the use of married graduate students. These are located to one side of the College grounds, a short distance from the main buildings.\n\n=== Chapel ===\nAt the farthest end of the college grounds is the Chapel. Sheppard's original design placed it within the main building complex near the college main entrance.<ref>Goldie, M.; ''Corbusier Comes to Cambridge'', Churchill (2007).</ref> The idea of having a religious building within a modern, scientifically-oriented academic institution deeply annoyed some of the original fellows, leading to the resignation of [[Nobel Prize]] winner [[Francis Crick]] in protest.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profiles.nlm.nih.gov/SC/Views/Exhibit/narrative/biographical.html|title=The Francis Crick Papers: Biographical Information|accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref> Eventually a compromise was found: the chapel was sited just to the west of the Sheppard Flats,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/about/visitors/map_of_college.php|title=Churchill College: Information: Map of College|accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref> and funded and managed separately from the rest of the College itself, being tactfully referred to as \"the Chapel ''at'' Churchill College\". The chimney of the heating system at the front of the college substitutes visually for the missing chapel tower.\n\nCrick had agreed to become a fellow on the basis that no chapel be placed at Churchill. A donation was later made by [[Lord Beaumont of Whitley]] to Churchill College for the establishment of one, and the majority of fellows voted in favour of it. Sir Winston Churchill wrote to him saying that no-one need enter the chapel unless they wished to do so, and therefore it did not need to be a problem. Crick, in short order, replied with a letter dated 12 October 1961 accompanied by a [[cheque]] for 10 [[Guinea (British coin)|guineas]] saying that, if that were the case, the enclosed money should be used for the establishment of a [[brothel]]. This story was repeated by Crick in an interview with [[Matt Ridley]] (Crick's biographer<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/sep/17/scienceandnature.biography|title=Observer review: Francis Crick by Matt Ridley|accessdate=5 February 2010|work=The Guardian|location=London|first=Robin|last=McKie|date=17 September 2006}}</ref>), quotes from which are reported in the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/science/science-news/3306329/Do-our-genes-reveal-the-hand-of-God.html|title=Do our genes reveal the hand of God?|accessdate=5 February 2010|work=The Daily Telegraph|location=London|first=Roger|last=Highfield|date=20 March 2003}}</ref>\n\n=== Artworks and sculptures ===\n[[File:Churchill College, Hepworth.jpg|thumb|right|[[Barbara Hepworth|Hepworth]]'s ''[[Four-Square (Walk Through)]]'' (1966) is large enough for many students to work and play on\u2014which they are allowed to do]]\n[[File:Lynn Chadwick Geograph-685492-by-Fractal-Angel.jpg|thumb|''Beast Alerted 1'', by British sculptor [[Lynn Chadwick]]]]\n\nThe college contains many examples of modern artwork including:\n* ''[[Four-Square (Walk Through)]]'' (1966) \u2013 [[Barbara Hepworth|Dame Barbara Hepworth]]\n* Prints of [[Marilyn Monroe]] \u2013 [[Andy Warhol]]\n* ''Gemini'' (1973) \u2013 [[Denis Mitchell (sculptor)|Denis Mitchell]]\n* ''Diagram of an Object (Second state)'' (1990)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sculpture.org.uk/image/618830211087/43/|title=Dhruva Mistry|accessdate=5 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081205025343/http://www.sculpture.org.uk/image/618830211087/43/|archivedate=5 December 2008|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \u2013 [[Dhruva Mistry]]\n* ''Spiral'' \u2013 Michael Gillespie (1993)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/685470|title=Geograph:: Spiral, Michael Gillespie, 1991 (C) Fractal Angel|publisher=Geograph.org|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>\n* ''Flight'' \u2013 [[Peter Lanyon]] (1981)\n* ''Black Bag'' \u2013 [[Graham Murdoch]] (1990)\n\nThere are also works by [[Eduardo Paolozzi|Sir Eduardo Paolozzi]], [[Bridget Riley]], [[Patrick Caulfield]], [[Peter Blake (artist)|Sir Peter Blake]],  and [[Daphne Hardy Henrion]].\n\nMistry's piece can be found at the front of college. [[Anthony Caro|Sir Anthony Caro]]'s ''Forum''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anthonycaro.org/Gallery-Pic.asp?WorkID=2350|title=Anthony Caro - Forum|accessdate=5 February 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719030802/http://www.anthonycaro.org/Gallery-Pic.asp?WorkID=2350|archive-date=19 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> used to stand near it but it was removed before the start of the 2004-2005 academic year.  In January 2007 its place was taken by ''Beast Alerted 1'', a sculpture by British sculptor [[Lynn Chadwick]].\n\n== Student life ==\nThe student population is divided into two [[Common Room (university)|common rooms]]: the Junior Common Room (JCR) and Middle Common Room (MCR). The former contains undergraduates and the latter postgraduates (known as ''advanced students''). Fourth year undergraduates studying towards their [[Master's degree in Europe#Undergraduate Master's Courses|Masters]] may choose to be in either.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/?page_id=25#Advanced_Student|title=Churchill MCR: What is an Advanced Student?|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> These student bodies organise various academic and social events as well as handling issues regarding welfare. The college funds sports clubs and societies which provide entertainment for students.\n\n[[File:Students on Hepworth, Churchill College.jpg|thumb|right|Students relaxing on 'The Hepworth' following a formal]]\n\n=== Social events ===\nEvery two weeks of the Michaelmas and Lent terms, and twice in Easter term, Churchill is host to Pav, a music event unusual for Cambridge events in that it is free and open to all university members. The name Pav originates from the pavilion buildings of the college where the event was originally held. Since 1992, Pav has been held in the Buttery, the main bar area.\n\nIn the early years of the college's foundation, the college held a ball in [[May Week]], in common with many older colleges. However, more recently Churchill has held a Spring Ball every February, close to [[Valentine's Day]]. The Ball has hosted a number of upcoming bands, such as [[The Wombats]] (2007) and [[The Noisettes]] (2008).\n\nDuring [[May Week]] the JCR organise a free [[garden party]]. The event hosts performances from local bands and musicians.\n\nStudents of the College run Churchill Casino,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.churchillcasino.co.uk|title=Churchill Casino|accessdate=5 February 2010}}</ref> a Cambridge-based enterprise which provides professional casinos at various social events. Churchill Casino is frequently hired for [[May Ball|Cambridge May Balls]] as well as balls at the [[University of Oxford]] and corporate events throughout the country. Profits have been donated back towards the college and to local charities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Churchill Casino donates to Cam-mind at Churchill College event on 20th March 2012|url=http://www.cam-mind.org.uk/News/Story/Churchill-Casino-donates-to-Cam-mind-at-Churchill-College-event|work=Cam-mind News|accessdate=30 July 2012|date=22 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121224024033/http://www.cam-mind.org.uk/News/Story/Churchill-Casino-donates-to-Cam-mind-at-Churchill-College-event|archivedate=24 December 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe MCR has its own reserved area, the [[P. G. Ashmore|Sandy Ashmore]] Room, where students may socialise. This incorporates a student-run bar known as the Vicious Penguin.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/?page_id=18|title=Churchill MCR: MCR Bar|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> The MCR organises a range of activities including an annual conference, the Conference on Everything, and hosts termly Guest Nights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/?page_id=21|title=Churchill MCR: Activities & Calendar|accessdate=25 June 2012}}</ref> The Conference on Everything gives students an opportunity to present their own research as well as featuring talks from distinguished speakers including [[Salah Al-Shaikhly]], the [[Iraq]]i ambassador to the United Kingdom; [[Michael Green (physicist)|Michael Green]], [[Lucasian Professor of Mathematics|Lucasian Professor]] and pioneer of [[string theory]]; [[Julian Huppert]], scientist and [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for Cambridge; [[David Spiegelhalter]], [[Winton Professorship of the Public Understanding of Risk|Winton Professor]] of the Public Understanding of [[Risk]], and [[Nicholas Bingham]], Senior Investigator at [[Imperial College London]] and Visiting Professor of Mathematics at the [[London School of Economics]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/?page_id=388|title=Churchill MCR: Conference on Everything|accessdate=30 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Sport ===\n[[File:Churchill College Boat Club Fairairns M1.JPG|thumb|[[Churchill College Boat Club]] men's first VIII rowing past their boathouse on the [[River Cam]]. The club is noted for its pink boats.]]\nWith playing fields on site, unlike many other colleges, sport is an integral part of the college. As well as football pitches, a cricket pitch and others, the facilities include a gym, and tennis and squash courts.\n\nChurchill College Football Club (CCFC) were the first college team to retain the Cambridge University Amateur Football League Division 1 title, winning it in 2005\u201306 and 2006\u201307. In the 2006\u20132007 season they also reached the final of [[Cuppers]].{{citation needed|date=November 2009}}\n\nThe College also has a successful boat club ([[Churchill College Boat Club]]) which in 2013 won the [[Pegasus Cup]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.miltonbrewery.co.uk/pegasus-cup/2013.html|title=Pegasus Cup 2013 \u2014 The Milton Brewery, Cambridge Ltd|publisher=The Milton Brewery, Cambridge Ltd|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref> (This trophy is awarded annually to the most successful college boat club competing in the Cambridge May Bumping Races<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cucbc.org/handbook/pegasus_cup|title=Pegasus Cup - CUCBC|publisher=|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>). In 2015, Churchill College Boat Club made history by being the first boat club at the university to win both the Pegasus Cup and Marconi Cup (This award is present to the most successful college boat club in the Lent Bumps) in the same year.\n\n== Traditions ==\n[[File:Dining Hall, Churchill 2005.jpg|thumb|right|Churchill's Dining Hall is the largest in Cambridge.]]\nChurchill is a relatively young college, and prides itself on being modern and forward looking. It has relatively few traditions. Informal hall (cafeteria-style dining period) was introduced in 1971, as an alternative to formal hall (fixed time, waiter service, all diners wearing gowns), but students are no longer required to wear [[Academic dress of the University of Cambridge|gowns]] at formal halls,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/useful-stuff/faq/#Formals|title=Churchill College MCR Frequently Asked Questions|accessdate=12 December 2014}}</ref> with exception of certain college feasts.\n\nIn special formal meals such as Matriculation Dinner or Scholars' Feast the Master usually raises a toast, first to [[Queen of the United Kingdom|The Queen]] and then to \"Sir Winston\". In other [[Formal Hall|formal halls]] this is usually made by a senior student once the [[fellow]]s have left. This latter tradition started in the early 2000s with the students customarily toasting in the reverse order: \"Sir Winston\", followed by \"The Queen\".\n\n== People associated with the college ==\n\n=== Masters ===\nThe Mastership of Churchill College is a [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Crown]] appointment. To date the College has had seven Masters:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Name\n!Term of office\n!Notes\n|-\n| [[John Cockcroft|Sir John Cockcroft]]\n| 1959\u20131967\n| [[Nobel Prize|Nobel Laureate in Physics]], who split the atom.\n|-\n| [[William Hawthorne|Sir William Hawthorne]]\n| 1968\u20131983\n| Engineer who helped develop the [[jet engine]].\n|-\n| [[Hermann Bondi|Sir Hermann Bondi]]\n| 1983\u20131990\n| Cosmologist who helped develop the [[Steady State theory]] of the universe.\n|-\n| [[Alec Broers|Lord Alec Broers]]\n| 1990\u20131996\n| Nanotechnologist; later [[List of vice-chancellors of the University of Cambridge|Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge]] (1996-2003).\n|-\n| [[John Boyd (ambassador)|Sir John Boyd]] \n| 1996\u20132006\n| Formerly [[Heads of the United Kingdom Mission in Japan|British ambassador to Japan]] (1992\u20131996).\n|-\n| [[David Wallace (physicist)|Sir David Wallace]]\n| 2006<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.number10.gov.uk/Page8002|title=Appointment of Master of Churchill College|accessdate=5 February 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616041413/http://www.number10.gov.uk/Page8002|archivedate=16 June 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\u20132014\n| Formerly Vice-chancellor of [[Loughborough University]] (1994\u20132005); Director of the [[Isaac Newton Institute|Newton Institute]] (2006\u20132011).\n|-\n| [[Athene Donald|Dame Athene Donald]]\n| 2014<ref>{{cite web|title=Appointment of Next Master of Churchill College|url=http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/about/news/315-appointment-of-next-master-of-churchill-college|work=Churchill College News|accessdate=2 October 2013}}</ref>\u2013present\n| Professor of experimental physics at the Cavendish Laboratory.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Donald|first1=A.|last2=Jacobsen|first2=S.D.|title=Dr. Athene Donald: Experimental Physicist, University of Cambridge|date=28 June 2013|journal=In-Sight|issue=2.A|pages=85\u201397|url=http://in-sightjournal.com/2013/06/28/dr-athene-donald-experimental-physicist-university-of-cambridge/}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n=== Notable fellows ===\n''See also [[:Category:Fellows of Churchill College, Cambridge]]''\n* [[Michael Ashburner]] \u2013 Biologist, former head of the [[European Bioinformatics Institute]] and the [[European Molecular Biology Laboratory]]\n* [[Correlli Barnett]] \u2013 Military historian\n* [[Jacques Barzun]] \u2013 Historian and cultural critic; (Extraordinary Fellow at Churchill while also Provost, Dean of Graduate studies, and Dean of Faculties at Columbia.)\n* [[Piers Brendon]] \u2013 Writer and historian\n* [[Edward Bullard]] \u2013 Geophysicist, former head of the [[National Physical Laboratory (United Kingdom)|National Physical Laboratory]]\n* [[Edward Craig (philosopher)|Edward Craig]] \u2013 Philosopher\n* [[James Fox (art historian)|James Fox]] - Art historian and broadcaster\n* [[George Gamow]] \u2013 Cosmologist (overseas fellow)\n* [[Mark Goldie]] - Professor of Intellectual History\n*[[Priyamvada Gopal|Priya Gopal]] - Teaching fellow in colonial and postcolonial literature\n* [[Frank Hahn]] \u2013 Economist\n* [[Archie Howie]] \u2013 Physicist\n* [[Richard Keynes]] \u2013 Physiologist\n*[[Julia King, Baroness Brown of Cambridge]] - Engineer, former Vice-Chancellor of [[Aston University]]\n* [[John Kinsella (poet)|John Kinsella]] \u2013 Poet and novelist\n* [[Nigel Knight]] - Economist and political scientist\n* [[C. B. Macpherson]] \u2013 Political scientist\n* [[Peter Murray-Rust]] \u2013 Chemist\n* [[David Newbery]] \u2013 Economist \n* [[David Olive]] - Physicist\n*[[Nick Petford]] - Geologist and Vice-Chancellor of the [[University of Northampton]]\n* [[Roy Porter]] \u2013 Historian and prolific author\n* [[Stephen Roskill]] \u2013 Naval historian\n* [[Andrew Sinclair]] \u2013 Historian, novelist and journalist\n* [[C. P. Snow]] \u2013 Physicist and novelist\n* [[George Steiner]] \u2013 Literary critic and linguistic theorist (Extraordinary Fellow at Churchill)\n* [[Colin St John Wilson|Sir Colin St John Wilson]] \u2013 Architect\n* [[David Spiegelhalter]] \u2013 Statistician\n* [[Dick Tizard]] \u2013 Engineer\n* [[Frank Gibbs Torto]] \u2013 Chemist\n* [[Melissa Hines]] \u2013 neuroscientist\n* [[Stuart Warren]] \u2013 organic chemist\n* [[Chandra Wickramasinghe]] \u2013 Physicist and Astrobiologist\n* [[Michael Young (politician)|Michael Young]] \u2013 Sociologist and politician\n* [[Ghil'ad Zuckermann]] \u2013 Linguist and revivalist\n* [[Sander van der Linden]] \u2013 Psychologist\n\n===Nobel laureates===\n[[File:Francis Crick crop.jpg|thumb|[[Francis Crick]]]]\n* [[Philip Warren Anderson]] \u2013 Physics, for the behaviour of electrons in magnetic solids, 1977\n* [[John Cockcroft]] \u2013 Physics, for using accelerated particles to study atomic nuclei, 1951\n* [[Francis Crick]] \u2013 co-discoverer of the structure of DNA, Medicine, 1962\n* [[Angus Deaton]] \u2013 Economics, 2015 (Overseas Fellow 1990\u20131): Analysis of consumption, poverty, and welfare\n* [[G\u00e9rard Debreu]] \u2013 Economics, 1983\n* [[Peter Diamond]] \u2013 Economics, 2010 (overseas fellow)\n* [[Robert G. Edwards]] \u2013 Physiology or Medicine, 2010\n* [[John Gurdon]] \u2013 Physiology or Medicine, 2012\n* [[Antony Hewish]] \u2013 co-discoverer of [[pulsar]]s, Physics, 1974\n* [[William Lipscomb]] \u2013 Chemistry, 1976 (overseas fellow)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wlipscomb.tripod.com/publications_biog_cv.html|title=CV - Biog - Publications - Lipscomb|publisher=|accessdate=13 September 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Mario Vargas Llosa]] \u2013 Literature, 2010 (overseas fellow)\n* [[Eric Maskin]] \u2013 Economics, 2007 (overseas fellow)\n*[[Paul Nurse]] - Physiology or Medicine, 2001<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/people/view/paul-nurse/|title=People \u2013 Churchill College|website=www.chu.cam.ac.uk|access-date=2019-01-13}}</ref>\n* [[Wole Soyinka]] \u2013 Literature, 1986 (overseas fellow)\n* [[David Thouless]] \u2013 Physics, 2016 (Fellow 1961\u20135): Theoretical discoveries of topological phase transitions and topological phases of matter.\n* [[Roger Tsien]] \u2013 Chemistry, 2008\n\n=== Notable alumni ===\n''See also [[:Category:Alumni of Churchill College, Cambridge]]''\n[[File:Sal Brinton at Brighton 2013.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Liberal Democrat Peer [[Sarah Brinton, Baroness Brinton|Baroness Brinton]]]][[File:Helmer, Roger-9461.jpg|thumb|right|180px|UKIP MEP [[Roger Helmer]]]]\n* [[Kari Blackburn]] \u2013 [[BBC World Service]] executive\n* [[Sal Brinton|Baroness Brinton]] \u2013 [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] peer\n* [[Nick Brown (academic)|Nick Brown]] - Principal of [[Linacre College, Oxford]]\n* [[Michael Burrows]] \u2013 inventor of the first internet search machine, Alta Vista\n* [[Peter Fincham]] \u2013 former controller, [[BBC1]]\n* Sir [[Christopher Frayling]] \u2013 writer and educationalist\n* [[Mike Gascoyne]] \u2013 Chief technical officer of the [[Caterham F1]] Formula One team\n* Sir [[Peter Gershon]] \u2013 author of the [[Gershon Review]], chairman of [[Premier Farnell]] and [[Symbian Ltd.]]\n* [[John Warren Gladwin|John Gladwin]] \u2013 [[Bishop of Chelmsford]] and Chair of [[Citizens Advice]]\n* [[Michael Green (physicist)|Michael Green]] \u2013 [[Lucasian Chair]] of Mathematics\n* [[Charlie Hannaford (rugby union)|Charlie Hannaford]] \u2013 [[England national rugby union team|England]] rugby player\n* [[Roger Helmer]] \u2013 [[United Kingdom Independence Party|UK Independence Party]] [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]\n* [[Tianhui Michael Li|Michael Li]] \u2013 Founder, [[The Data Incubator]] and data scientist\n* [[Diarmaid MacCulloch]] \u2013 Historian\n* [[Christopher Walter Monckton, 3rd Viscount Monckton of Brenchley|Viscount Monckton]] \u2013 Writer and policy advisor to [[Margaret Thatcher]]\n* [[Simeon Nyachae]] \u2013 [[Kenya]]n minister and [[Elections in Kenya|2002 presidential candidate]]\n* [[Brendan O'Neill (businessman)|Brendan O'Neill]] \u2013 business executive\n* [[Andrew Parker (MI5 officer)|Andrew Parker]] - [[Director General of MI5|Director General]] of the [[Security Service (MI5)]]\n* [[David Pearson (computer scientist)|David Pearson]] - physicist and computer scientist\n* [[John-Luke Roberts|Luke Roberts]] \u2013 comedian\n*[[Philip Sales]] - [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]] Justice\n* [[Mark Smith (academic)|Mark Smith]] - Academic, Vice-Chancellor of [[Lancaster University]]\n* [[Ian Stewart (mathematician)|Ian Stewart]] \u2013 Mathematician\n* [[Gavin Strang]] \u2013 [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]]\n* [[Bjarne Stroustrup]] \u2013 inventor of [[C++]]\n* [[John Stuttard|Sir John Stuttard]] \u2013 former [[Lord Mayor of London]]\n* [[Fabian Tassano]] \u2013 Economist and author\n* [[Geoffrey Thomas (academic)|Geoffrey Thomas]] \u2013 Former President of [[Kellogg College, Oxford]]\n* [[Geoff Travis]] \u2013 Founder of [[Rough Trade Records]] label and shops\n* [[Neil Turok]] \u2013 Mathematician\n* [[Stephen Tweedie]] \u2013 Software developer\n* [[Peter Wadhams]] - Oceanographer and glaciologist\n* [[Rick Warden]] \u2013 Actor ''[[Band of Brothers (TV miniseries)|Band Of Brothers]]'', ''[[Rome (TV series)|Rome]]''\n* [[Jeremy Warmsley]] \u2013 musician\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Churchill Scholarship]]s for fourteen graduates from the [[United States]].\n* [[Churchill College Boat Club]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/ College Website]\n* [http://jcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/ Churchill College JCR]\n* [http://mcr.chu.cam.ac.uk/ Churchill College MCR]\n* [http://scr.chu.cam.ac.uk/ Churchill College SCR]\n* [http://www.chu.cam.ac.uk/archives/ Archives Centre]\n\n{{University of Cambridge}}\n{{Winston Churchill|state=expanded}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Colleges of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Churchill College, Cambridge| ]]\n[[Category:Winston Churchill]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1958]]\n[[Category:1958 establishments in England]]\n", "name_