{"title_page": "JOEY", "text_new": "{{About|Joey Restaurant|Joey's Seafood Restaurants|Joey's Seafood Restaurants}}'''JOEY Restaurant Group''' is a Western Canadian [[Types of restaurants#Premium casual|premium casual]] restaurant chain based in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada. The concept for JOEY Restaurants was created by Jeff Fuller.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://joeyrestaurants.com/about-joey|title=JOEY Restaurants {{!}} About JOEY|website=JOEY Restaurants|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> JOEY restaurants is a part of a chain of family-owned restaurants, expanding all throughout North America. The restaurant focuses on Asian, American, [[Mediterranean cuisine|Mediterranean]] and other global dishes.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://joeyrestaurants.com/see-the-menu|title=JOEY Restaurants {{!}} See The Menu|website=JOEY Restaurants|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> The company operates 27 full-service restaurants in [[Canada]] and expanding in the [[United States]]. All JOEY restaurants feature a bar area and serve alcoholic beverages. {{Infobox company\n| name = Joey Tomato\u2019s (Canada) Inc.\n| logo = [[File:JOEY Restaurant Logo.png|250x250px|]]\n| type = Private<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vanmag.com/best-of-the-city/48-bus-fuller-stan-fuller-and-jeff-fuller/|title=48. Bus Fuller, Stan Fuller, and Jeff Fuller|date=17 November 2015|website=Vancouver Magazine|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n| industry = [[Restaurant]]\n| genre = [[Types_of_restaurants#Premium_casual|Premium Casual]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1992}} [[Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada]]\n| founder = Jeff Fuller\n| hq_location = 950-505 Burrard Street, [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]\n| num_locations = 27 (2020)\n| area_served = [[United States]], [[Canada]]\n| key_people = Jeff Fuller ([[Organizational founder|Founder]]), Chris Mills ([[Executive Chef]])\n| products = [[burgers]], [[steaks]], [[chicken]], [[sushi]], [[salads]], [[dessert]]\n| revenue = $270 million per year\n| net_income = n/a\n| num_employees = n/a\n| location_country = Canada\n| homepage = http://joeyrestaurants.com/\n}}\n\n==History==\n\n=== Founding and Early Years ===\nThe first JOEY Restaurant was opened in 1992 in [[Calgary]], [[Alberta]].  The chain now operates over twenty five restaurants.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/fuller-familys-restaurants-heading-east/article4297482/|title=Fuller family's restaurants heading east|publisher=|accessdate=12 February 2019|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://biv.com/article/2016/05/joey-restaurants-has-no-plans-buy-certified-human-|title=Joey Restaurants won't join sister company Earls and buy certified humane beef|website=Business in Vancouver|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe company's founding President and CEO is Jeff Fuller, son of restaurateur Leroy \"Bus\" Fuller (1928-2019)<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/british-columbia/leroy-full-earls-passing-1.5312602|title='A giant in our industry': Leroy Fuller, founder of Earls restaurant, dies at 90|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, who founded the [[Earls_(restaurant_chain)|Earls]] restaurant chain with Jeff's brother Stan Fuller.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bcbusiness.ca/bcs-invasion-of-toronto|title=BCBusiness|first=Kevin Hinton & Ryan|last=Mckenzie|website=BCBusiness.ca|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> Leroy Fuller was an experienced restaurateur who built the family restaurant empire stemming from one of the original [[A&W Restaurants|A&W Restaurant]] franchises in Canada, an American chain of fast-food restaurants known for draft root beers, floats and burgers.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/life/no-sass-no-sizzle-in-chain-dining/article730267/|title=No sass, no sizzle in chain dining|accessdate=12 February 2019|newspaper=[[The Globe and Mail]]}}</ref>  \n\nJOEY was originally conceived as a pasta house called \"Joey Tomato's\", which opened in [[Calgary]] in 1992 as a casual [[pasta]] and [[pizza]] joint. As more menu items were added eight years later, the name was changed to \"Joey Tomato's Mediterranean Grill,\" before being shortened in 2005 to simply \"JOEY.\"<ref name=\":3\" /> [[Executive chef|Executive Chef]], Chris Mills, began adding Asian cuisine into the menu as a way to rebrand the image.<ref name=\":3\" /> The company also owns the American restaurant Cucina, Cucina.\n\nIn 2016, Al Jessa was promoted to company President,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/al-jessa-named-president-of-joey-restaurant-group-2107649.htm |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-05-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328205414/http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/al-jessa-named-president-of-joey-restaurant-group-2107649.htm |archive-date=2016-03-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref> marking another link between the Earls chain and JOEY.  Al Jessa's twin brother Mo Jessa is the current president of Earls.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://biv.com/article/2013/07/mo-jessa-duke-of-earls|title=Mo Jessa: Duke of Earls|website=Business in Vancouver|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref> \n[[File:Earls restaurant at 191 Main Street in Winnipeg, Manitoba.JPG|thumb|Earls restaurant in Winnipeg, Manitoba]]\n\n== Locations ==\n\n=== Canada ===\nThere are 23 locations based in Canada: [[Calgary]], [[Edmonton]], [[Winnipeg]], [[Kelowna]], [[Ottawa]], [[Toronto]] and [[Vancouver]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== North America ===\nThe restaurant chain currently has locations in [[California]] and [[Washington (state)|Washington]] state. Locations in California include [[Woodland Hills, Los Angeles|Woodland Hills]] and [[Downtown Los Angeles]]. The locations in Washington state include [[Bellevue, Washington|Bellevue]], [[Tukwila, Washington|Tukwila]] and [[Seattle]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nOne location closed down in the Seattle [[South Lake Union, Seattle|South Lake Union]] Area in November 2013, opening a new location in Seattle's [[University Village, Seattle|University Village]] shortly after.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cornichon.org/2013/12/joey-overdelivers.html|title=Joey overdelivers Canadian fare to U Village - Cornichon.org|website=www.cornichon.org|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> The previous location fell victim to [[traffic]] and [[construction]] congestion in the area. \n\nThe newer Joey location based in [[Seattle]] is called JOEY Kitchen, the only one of its kind serving test kitchen items.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://joeyrestaurants.com/location/joey-university-village|title=JOEY Restaurants {{!}} JOEY University Village|website=JOEY Restaurants|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>Test kitchen items include dishes and drinks only offered through this specific restaurant, expanding to other locations throughout [[Canada]] and the [[United States]] if enjoyed by guests. The location was designed by Olson Kundig.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nOn July 31st, 2019, another location opened up in Downtown [[Los Angeles]] named, JOEY DTLA. The location joins in with other diverse businesses as part of The Bloc community. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/joey-restaurants-unveils-downtown-los-angeles-location-300882210.html|title=JOEY Restaurants Unveils Downtown Los Angeles Location|last=Group|first=JOEY Restaurant|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref>\n\n== Other Restaurants ==\n\n=== Local Eatery ===\nThe JOEY Restaurant Group is an [[umbrella company]] to [[Earls (restaurant chain)|Earls]] as well as Local. Local is a casual take with bar food and cheaper menu options.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.laconialocaleatery.com/menu|title=Local Eatery {{!}} Menu|website=localeatery|language=en|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\n=== Earls ===\nRestaurant founder, Leroy Earl \"Bus\" Fuller, died at the age of 90.<ref name=\":2\" /> [[Earls (restaurant chain)|Earls]] has since been operated by Jeff Fuller's brother, Stan Fuller, who also owns a large share of the Cactus Club chain, a competitor to the restaurant.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n=== Saltlik ===\nBrother of Jeff and Stan Fuller, Stewart Fuller, runs Saltlik, a casual fine [[steakhouse]] chain.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== Theme ==\nJOEY Restaurants has a casual fine dining theme. Each location is decorated with lighting fixtures, architecture, photos and decorations. The design of the restaurant is to cater to the locale and [[clientele]] of each restaurant location.<ref name=\":0\" /> Each restaurant is said to be custom-designed, catering again, to each location and its atmosphere.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n\n== Menu ==\n[[File:Short_Ribs_offered_at_JOEY_Kitchen.png|thumb|Balsamic Braised Short Rib offered at JOEY locations.]]\nThe restaurant is well known serving globally-inspired foods with a JOEY twist. The menu varies by location to cater to different clientele and locals.<ref name=\":1\" /> [[Hors d'oeuvre|Appetizers]] include Chicken Lettuce Wraps, Hibachi Wings, and Nachos. The restaurant offers a full bar with draft and bottled beers, wine, classic cocktails and non-alcoholic options. The lunch and dinner menu remain the same throughout the time the restaurant is open. The food menu has offerings such as smalls + sharings, sushi, salads, sandwiches + burgers, mains, steakhouse, and sweets.<ref name=\":1\" /> A signature [[side dish]] they offer is called Crispy Mashed Potatoes, a take on a [[spring roll]] combined with a loaded potato, topped with bacon, green onions, sour cream and cheese. \n\nJOEY is well known for their Super Drinks, a classic cocktail offering of [[Highball|highballs]] such as [[gin and tonic]], [[Vodka soda|vodka and soda]], or [[Jack and Coke|jack and coke]] with a lemon-lime slushy, called an Iceberg, on top.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Super Sonic Gin + Tonic is named after Seattle's [[Seattle SuperSonics|SuperSonics]] basketball team, which is now nonexistent. \n\nThe menu also offers [[Vegetarianism|vegetarian]] and gluten-wise options. The full [[Caloric concentration|caloric content]] and information is available online on the website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://joeyrestaurants.com/location/joey-university-village/menu#nutrition|title=JOEY Restaurants {{!}} JOEY University Village Menu|website=JOEY Restaurants|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref>\n\n== Dress Code ==\nBritt Innes, the [[Vice president|Vice President]] for JOEY Restaurant Group, is responsible for the [[dress code]] for the company. The dress code revolves around having a neat, polished and consistent appearance, focusing on an all-black outfit.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/marketplace/m_blog/company-statements-restaurant-dress-codes|title=Company statements: Restaurant dress codes|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Partnered with [[Aritzia]], female front of house staff wear black dresses or a mock-neck top with black pants. Male front of house staff wear black jeans and a black tee shirt.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\n== Awards ==\n[[File:JOEY_Oscars.jpg|thumb|JOEY Oscar Partner Party]]\nJoey has been consistently recognized as one of the Best Places to Work Best Workplace in [[Canada]] for a consecutive nine years from 2010\u20132018.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indeed.com/cmp/Joey-Restaurants/about|title=JOEY Restaurants Mission, Benefits, and Work Culture|website=Indeed.com|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> The company has also been awarded as one of the Top Employers for Young People. According to [[Forbes]], the restaurant dropped off the list in 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/joey-restaurant-group/|title=JOEY Restaurant Group|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Canadian restaurant chains]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in Canada]]\n[[Category:Restaurants established in 1992]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains]]\n[[Category:Canadian restaurateurs]]\n[[Category:Restaurant chains in the United States]]\n[[Category:Restaurant franchises]]\n[[Category:Theme restaurants]]\n[[Category:Restaurants]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|Joey Restaurant|Joey's Seafood Restaurants|Joey's Seafood Restaurants}}'''JOEY Restaurant Group''' is a Western Canadian [[Types of restaurants#Premium casual|premium casual]] restaurant chain based in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]], Canada. The concept for JOEY Restaurants was created by Jeff Fuller.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://joeyrestaurants.com/about-joey|title=JOEY Restaurants {{!}} About JOEY|website=JOEY Restaurants|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> JOEY restaurants is a part of a chain of family-owned restaurants, expanding all throughout North America. The restaurant focuses on Asian, American, Mediterranean and other global dishes.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://joeyrestaurants.com/see-the-menu|title=JOEY Restaurants {{!}} See The Menu|website=JOEY Restaurants|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref> The company operates 27 full-service restaurants in [[Canada]] and expanding in the [[United States]]. All JOEY restaurants feature a bar area and serve alcoholic beverages. {{Infobox company\n| name = Joey Tomato\u2019s (Canada) Inc.\n| logo = [[File:JOEY Restaurant Logo.png|250x250px|]]\n| type = Private<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vanmag.com/best-of-the-city/48-bus-fuller-stan-fuller-and-jeff-fuller/|title=48. Bus Fuller, Stan Fuller, and Jeff Fuller|date=17 November 2015|website=Vancouver Magazine|accessdate=12 February 2019}}</ref>\n| industry = [[Restaurant]]\n| genre = [[Types_of_restaurants#Premium_casual|Premium Casual]]\n| foundation = {{start date and age|1992}} [[Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada]]\n| founder = Jeff Fuller\n| hq_location 