{"title_page": "Saint Joan (1967 film)", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Saint Joan''''' is a 1967 American TV film adaptation of the 1923 [[George Bernard Shaw]] play ''[[Saint Joan (play)|Saint Joan]]'' for the ''[[Hallmark Hall of Fame]]''. It was directed by [[George Schaefer (director)|George Schaefer]].\n\nThe cast was announced August 1967.<ref>N.B.C. Fills Leading Roles For Hallmark's 'St. Joan'\n''New York Times'' August 2, 1967: p 75.</ref> [[Genevi\u00e8ve Bujold]] played the title role.<ref>TV's first St. Joan: Distinguished predecessors Her film credits By Louise Sweeney. ''The Christian Science Monitor'' December 1, 1967: p 10.</ref><ref name=\"joan\">Who's Playing Saint Joan? Genevieve Bujold?\nBy JUDY KLEMESRUD. ''New York Times'' October 22, 1967: p 147.</ref> Taping took place over four weeks.<ref>HALLMARK PLAY FINDS NEW STAR Humphrey, Hal. ''Los Angeles Times'' December 3, 1967: p c2.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Theodore Bikel]] as [[Robert de Baudricourt]]\n*[[David Birney]] as Ladvenu\n*[[Genevi\u00e8ve Bujold]] as [[Saint Joan of Arc]]\n*[[James Daly (actor)|James Daly]] as [[Jack Dunois]]\n*[[John Devlin (actor)|John Devlin]] as Poulengry\n*[[James Donald]] as Richard Warwick\n*[[Dana Elcar]] as La Hire\n*[[Maurice Evans (actor)|Maurice Evans]] as [[Pierre Cauchon|Bishop Cauchon]]\n*[[Chris Gampel]] as The Executioner\n*[[Leo Genn]] as [[Archbishop of Rheims]]\n*[[William Hickey (actor)|William Hickey]] as The Steward\n*[[William LeMassena]] as D'Estivet\n*Michael Lewis as La Teremouille\n*Ian Martin as English Soldier\n*[[Raymond Massey]] as The Inquisitor \n*[[Roddy McDowall]] as [[Charles, The Dauphin]]\n*[[George Rose (actor)|George Rose]] as [[Chaplain de Stogumber]]\n*[[Ted van Griethuysen]] as Bluebeard\n\n==Reception==\nThe production was well received, with one critic calling it \"wonderfully good\"<ref>Today's TV: NBC'S 'Saint Joan' Shows How Good TV Can Be: Canadian Actress Glows in Hallmark's 2d Special of Season\nGowran, Clay. Chicago Tribune (1963-Current file); Chicago, Ill. [Chicago, Ill]05 Dec 1967: b27.</ref> and another calling it \"absorbing and exciting\".<ref>TV REVIEW: Hall of Fame Version of 'St. Joan'\nSmith, Cecil. Los Angeles Times 6 Dec 1967: d28.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.org/details/GeorgeBernardShawSaintJoan Audio transcript of production] at [[Internet Archive]]\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1967 television films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by George Schaefer]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American historical films]]\n[[Category:1960s drama films]]\n[[Category:1960s historical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by George Bernard Shaw]]\n[[Category:Films about Joan of Arc]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n'''''Saint Joan''''' is a 1967 American TV film adaptation of the 1923 [[George Bernard Shaw]] play ''[[Saint Joan (play)|Saint Joan]]'' for the ''[[Hallmark Hall of Fame]]''. It was directed by [[George Schaefer (director)|George Schaefer]].\n\nThe cast was announced August 1967.<ref>N.B.C. Fills Leading Roles For Hallmark's 'St. Joan'\n''New York Times'' August 2, 1967: p 75.</ref> [[Genevi\u00e8ve Bujold]] played the title role.<ref>TV's first St. Joan: Distinguished predecessors Her film credits By Louise Sweeney. ''The Christian Science Monitor'' December 1, 1967: p 10.</ref><ref name=\"joan\">Who's Playing Saint Joan? Genevieve Bujold?\nBy JUDY KLEMESRUD. ''New York Times'' October 22, 1967: p 147.</ref> Taping took place over four weeks.<ref>HALLMARK PLAY FINDS NEW STAR Humphrey, Hal. ''Los Angeles Times'' December 3, 1967: p c2.</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Theodore Bikel]] as [[Robert de Baudricourt]]\n*[[David Birney]] as Ladvenu\n*[[Genevi\u00e8ve Bujold]] as [[Saint Joan of Arc]]\n*[[James Daly (actor)|James Daly]] as [[Jack Dunois]]\n*[[John Devlin (actor)|John Devlin]] as Poulengry\n*[[James Donald]] as Richard Warwick\n*[[Dana Elcar]] as La Hire\n*[[Maurice Evans (actor)|Maurice Evans]] as [[Pierre Cauchon|Bishop Cauchon]]\n*[[Chris Gampel]] as The Executioner\n*[[Leo Genn]] as [[Archbishop of Rheims]]\n*[[William Hickey (actor)|William Hickey]] as The Steward\n*[[William LeMassena]] as D'Estivet\n*Michael Lewis as La Teremouille\n*Ian Martin as English Soldier\n*[[Raymond Massey]] as The Inquisitor \n*[[Roddy McDowall]] as [[Charles, The Dauphin]]\n*[[George Rose (actor)|George Rose]] as [[Chaplain de Stogumber]]\n*[[Ted van Griethuysen]] as Bluebeard\n\n==Reception==\nThe production was well received, with one critic calling it \"wonderfully good\"<ref>Today's TV: NBC'S 'Saint Joan' Shows How Good TV Can Be: Canadian Actress Glows in Hallmark's 2d Special of Season\nGowran, Clay. Chicago Tribune (1963-Current file); Chicago, Ill. [Chicago, Ill]05 Dec 1967: b27.</ref> and another calling it \"absorbing and exciting\".<ref>TV REVIEW: Hall of Fame Version of 'St. Joan'\nSmith, Cecil. Los Angeles Times 6 Dec 1967: d28.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.org/details/GeorgeBernardShawSaintJoan Audio transcript of production] at [[Internet Archive]]\n\n[[Category:1967 television films]]\n[[Category:American television films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by George Schaefer]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American historical films]]\n[[Category:1960s drama films]]\n[[Category:1960s historical films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films based on works by George Bernard Shaw]]\n[[Category:Films about Joan of Arc]]\n\n\n{{US-tv-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Joan_(1967_film)"}
{"title_page": "Benjamin Burnley", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name          = Benjamin Burnley\n| image         = 2016 RiP Breaking Benjamin - Benjamin Burnley - by 2eight - 8SC8634.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Burnley performing in June 2016\n| birth_name    = Benjamin Jackson Burnley IV\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1978|3|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]], United States\n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active  = 1998\u2013present\n| known_for     = Frontman of [[Breaking Benjamin]]\n| spouse        = \n| children      = \n| module  = {{Infobox musical artist\n  | embed=yes\n  | background = solo_singer\n  | genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[alternative metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\n}}\n  | instrument = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n}}\n  | label      = [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]]\n  | associated_acts = [[Breaking Benjamin]]\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Benjamin Jackson Burnley IV''' (born March 10, 1978) is an American musician, singer, songwriter, and record producer, best known as the founder and frontman of the American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Breaking Benjamin]]. As the sole constant of the group, Burnley has served as its principal songwriter, lead vocalist, and guitarist since its inception in 1999. Since signing with [[Hollywood Records]] in 2002, Burnley has composed six studio albums under the name Breaking Benjamin, three of which have reached platinum and two of which have reached gold in the United States.<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web |url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?&artist=benjamin |title=RIAA - Gold & Platinum Searchable Database |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=[[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] |access-date=29 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904024728/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php |archive-date=September 4, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Outside of Breaking Benjamin, Burnley has also collaborated with acts such as [[Adam Gontier]]<ref name=\"kqrx\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rock951online.com/GET-THE-DIRT-W-LOU-BRUTUS/14586178?pid=290492 |title=Get The Dirt |first=Lou |last=Brutus |date=January 17, 2013 |website=[[KQRX|KQRX 95.1]] |publisher=Brazos Communications West, LLC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411003508/http://www.rock951online.com/GET-THE-DIRT-W-LOU-BRUTUS/14586178?pid=290492 |archive-date=April 11, 2015}}</ref> and [[Red (band)|Red]].<ref name=\"iheartradio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iheart.com/artist/Red-30400755/songs/Shadows-2510149/ |title=Red - Shadows |work=[[iHeart Radio]] |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |access-date=April 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBurnley's lyrical content frequently and most recently consists of cryptic, angst-ridden themes that \"waffle between being plaintive and aggressive.\" Burnley has the range of a [[tenor]] and occasionally utilizes [[death growl]]s in his singing. [[IGN]] described him as having a \"somewhat innocuous voice that is crystal clear... fluctuating between contemplative subjectivity and growling anger.\"<ref name=\"ign spence\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/11/breaking-benjamin-phobia |title=Breaking Benjamin - Phobia |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[j2 Global]] |author=Spence D. |date=September 11, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219175352/http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/11/breaking-benjamin-phobia |archive-date=February 19, 2014}}</ref> Burnley uses baritone guitars and drop tunings to match the range of his voice.<ref name=\"fret12 baritone\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5yfKDYNR7uY |title=Ben Burnley Talks About His Baritone Guitar And Low Tunings |website=[[YouTube]] |publisher=[[Mark Tremonti|FRET12]] |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |access-date=April 10, 2015}} (verified channel, [[WP:NOYT|primary source]]).</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Early life and career beginnings===\nBurnley was born in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]] and grew up in [[Ocean City, New Jersey]] before moving with his family at the age of 12 to the [[Snyder County, Pennsylvania|Snyder County]] town of [[Selinsgrove, Pennsylvania]].<ref>Roncace, Kelly. [https://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2015/08/breaking_benjamin_is_back_and_going_home.html 'Breaking Benjamin is back and going home with show at Trump Taj Mahal\"], NJ Advance Media for [[NJ.com]], August 8, 2015. Accessed August 9, 2018. \"'I was born in Atlantic City, at the hospital there, and raised in Ocean City until I was 12 years old.' Burnley explained his family moved to Pennsylvania when he was 12 due to an increase in taxes at the shore town.\"</ref> At 16, he became home schooled and quickly passed the GED requirement. At 21 he moved to [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]], where he became a roommate of former Breaking Benjamin bass player Jonathan Price. During his early teen years he taught himself to play guitar by listening to [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]'s ''[[Nevermind]]'' (he cites Nirvana as his biggest influence). Before Breaking Benjamin was formed, Ben Burnley earned money playing cover songs, mixed in with his own in various coffee houses and other all age venues mostly with local neighboring musicians.\n\n===Breaking Benjamin===\n{{Main|Breaking Benjamin}}\n\nIn 1998, Burnley and former lead guitarist Aaron Fink, got together (along with Nick Hoover and Chris Lightcap) and started the band \"Breaking Benjamin.\" Eventually, Ben wanted to try something different and went out to California to try some new material. The other three members went on to form the band [[Lifer (band)|Strangers With Candy]] (later known as [[Lifer (band)|Lifer]]). They recruited old friend Mark Klepaski to play bass and he joined in, and shortly after, Nick Hoover was asked to leave the band.\n\nIn 1999, Ben Burnley moved back to Pennsylvania, and started a band called \"Plan 9\" with drummer Jeremy Hummel. Originally, the band was a three-piece. The lineups consisted of Benjamin on vocals and electric guitar, Jeremy on drums, and Jason Davoli on bass. Plan 9 would occasionally open for Lifer at home shows. During one show, Ben said \"Thank you, we're Breaking Benjamin,\" thus reclaiming the name from 1998. Later on, Mark left Lifer and found himself playing bass for Breaking Benjamin. Lifer continued going through struggles, and months later, Aaron Fink sat in for a set with Benjamin. Finally, Aaron left Lifer, and was offered a spot in Ben Burnley's band, and they became a four-piece.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shallowbay.com/forum/faq.php?faq=section_2#faq_question_2_2 |title=Breaking Benjamin Underground |publisher=The Shallow Bay |date= |accessdate=2011-11-02}}</ref>\n\n===Collaborations===\nBurnley has lent his vocal and songwriting talents to other acts as well. He has performed numerous live duets with fellow alternative metal bands such as [[Three Days Grace]], [[Evans Blue]] and [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]]. He made a guest spot on a special remix of The Drama Club's single \"Brand New Day.\" He also co-wrote the [[Red (band)|Red]] hit song \"[[Innocence & Instinct|Shadows]]\" and [[Madam Adam]] song \"Forgotten\". Burnley has collaborated with former Three Days Grace singer [[Adam Gontier]] on a song titled \"The End of the Day\" (yet to be released).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harddriveradio.com/dirt/thursday-jan-17|work=Harddrive|accessdate=2013-04-21|title=DdirtRockforrecovery}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBurnley has several [[phobia]]s, a fact that inspired the title of their 2006 album ''[[Phobia (Breaking Benjamin album)|Phobia]]''. ''Phobia''{{'}}s cover, which depicts a winged man hovering above the ground, represents Burnley's [[fear of flying]], which has prevented Breaking Benjamin from touring outside the United States and Canada in the past.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://123/www.jodileib.com/TalkItOutSessions/BreakingBenjamin.html |title=Ben Burnley, Breaking Benjamin Interview on www.jodileib.com |publisher=Jodileib.com |date=November 22, 2004 |accessdate=2010-03-02 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However in May 2016, he and his band members travelled through ferry ship to Europe, and made their first musical tour outside of the US and Canada. Breaking Benjamin again toured Europe in 2017 successfully. Burnley also suffers from [[hypochondria]] and a [[fear of the dark]]. He says that he does not believe in a person's time to die and he wants to put off dying for as long as he possibly can, which is why he does not fly or even ride in a car unless it is necessary. He incorporates his phobias into his music on the album ''We Are Not Alone'' in the song \"Break My Fall,\" in which a pilot is heard over the music saying, \"Mayday, mayday. Request permission to land. I cannot control the plane. We are in danger of crashing.\"\n\nBurnley is an avid [[gamer|video gamer]], and conceived of the idea for Breaking Benjamin to write and record the song \"[[Blow Me Away]]\" for the soundtrack to ''[[Halo 2]]''. The song \"[[Polyamorous (Breaking Benjamin song)|Polyamorous]]\" is also featured on the games ''[[Run Like Hell (video game)|Run Like Hell]]'', ''[[WWE SmackDown! vs. Raw]]'' and ''[[WWE Day of Reckoning]]'' (along with their song \"Firefly\"). \"[[The Diary of Jane]]\" appears on ''[[NASCAR 07]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=12 maart 2008 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XVIMuoTt3N4 |title=Tour Gaming with Breaking Benjamin |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2010-03-02}}</ref>\n\nBurnley is a recovering alcoholic, admitting in an interview that he wanted to \"drink himself to death.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://listenin.org/interviews/archive/artists/Breaking+Benjamin/default.aspx |title=Breaking Benjamin|publisher=Listenin.org |accessdate=2011-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915062048/http://listenin.org/interviews/archive/artists/Breaking+Benjamin/default.aspx |archive-date=September 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He says that he regrets ever drinking a drop of alcohol and is victim to [[Wernicke\u2013Korsakoff syndrome]] due to his past excessive drinking. ''[[Dear Agony]]'' was reported to be the first ever Breaking Benjamin record to be written by Burnley without the use of alcohol.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kory Grow |url=http://www.revolvermag.com/uncategorized/breaking-benjamins-benjamin-burnley-on-wet-brain-and-motorcycle-accide.html |title=Breaking Benjamin's Benjamin Burnley on Wet Brain and Motorcycle Accidents \u2013 Revolver Magazine |publisher=Revolvermag.com |date=May 10, 2010 |accessdate=2011-11-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Benjamin Burnley}}\n{{Breaking Benjamin}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burnley, Benjamin}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Alternative metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock singers]]\n[[Category:American alternative rock musicians]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:American lyricists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American tenors]]\n[[Category:Breaking Benjamin members]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Atlantic City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Ocean City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Post-grunge musicians]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Selinsgrove, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Hypochondriacs]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=March 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name          = Benjamin Burnley\n| image         = 2016 RiP Breaking Benjamin - Benjamin Burnley - by 2eight - 8SC8634.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Burnley performing in June 2016\n| birth_name    = Benjamin Jackson Burnley IV\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1978|3|10}}\n| birth_place   = [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]], United States\n| nationality   = American\n| occupation    = {{flatlist|\n* Musician\n* singer\n* songwriter\n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active  = 1998\u2013present\n| known_for     = Frontman of [[Breaking Benjamin]]\n| spouse        = \n| children      = \n| module  = {{Infobox musical artist\n  | embed=yes\n  | background = solo_singer\n  | genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Alternative rock]]\n* [[alternative metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n* [[post-grunge]]\n}}\n  | instrument = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* guitar\n}}\n  | label      = [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]]\n  | associated_acts = [[Breaking Benjamin]]\n  }}\n}}\n\n'''Benjamin Jackson Burnley IV''' (born March 10, 1978) is an American musician, singer, songwriter, and record producer, best known as the founder and frontman of the American [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Breaking Benjamin]]. As the sole constant of the group, Burnley has served as its principal songwriter, lead vocalist, and guitarist since its inception in 1999. Since signing with [[Hollywood Records]] in 2002, Burnley has composed six studio albums under the name Breaking Benjamin, three of which have reached platinum and two of which have reached gold in the United States.<ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web |url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?&artist=benjamin |title=RIAA - Gold & Platinum Searchable Database |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |website=[[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] |access-date=29 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904024728/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php |archive-date=September 4, 2015 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Outside of Breaking Benjamin, Burnley has also collaborated with acts such as [[Adam Gontier]]<ref name=\"kqrx\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rock951online.com/GET-THE-DIRT-W-LOU-BRUTUS/14586178?pid=290492 |title=Get The Dirt |first=Lou |last=Brutus |date=January 17, 2013 |website=[[KQRX|KQRX 95.1]] |publisher=Brazos Communications West, LLC |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150411003508/http://www.rock951online.com/GET-THE-DIRT-W-LOU-BRUTUS/14586178?pid=290492 |archive-date=April 11, 2015}}</ref> and [[Red (band)|Red]].<ref name=\"iheartradio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iheart.com/artist/Red-30400755/songs/Shadows-2510149/ |title=Red - Shadows |work=[[iHeart Radio]] |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |access-date=April 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBurnley's lyrical content frequently and most recently consists of cryptic, angst-ridden themes that \"waffle between being plaintive and aggressive.\" Burnley has the range of a [[tenor]] and occasionally utilizes [[death growl]]s in his singing. [[IGN]] described him as having a \"somewhat innocuous voice that is crystal clear... fluctuating between contemplative subjectivity and growling anger.\"<ref name=\"ign spence\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/11/breaking-benjamin-phobia |title=Breaking Benjamin - Phobia |website=[[IGN]] |publisher=[[j2 Global]] |author=Spence D. |date=September 11, 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219175352/http://www.ign.com/articles/2006/09/11/breaking-benjamin-phobia |archive-date=February 19, 2014}}</ref> Burnley uses baritone guitars and drop tunings to match the range of his voice.<ref name=\"fret12 baritone\">{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5yfKDYNR7uY |title=Ben Burnley Talks About His Baritone Guitar And Low Tunings |website=[[YouTube]] |publisher=[[Mark Tremonti|FRET12]] |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |access-date=April 10, 2015}} (verified channel, [[WP:NOYT|primary source]]).</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\n\n===Early life and career beginnings===\nBurnley was born in [[Atlantic City, New Jersey]] and grew up in [[Ocean City, New Jersey]] before moving with his family at the age of 12 to the [[Snyder County, Pennsylvania|Snyder County]] town of [[Selinsgrove, Pennsylvania]].<ref>Roncace, Kelly. [https://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2015/08/breaking_benjamin_is_back_and_going_home.html 'Breaking Benjamin is back and going home with show at Trump Taj Mahal\"], NJ Advance Media for [[NJ.com]], August 8, 2015. Accessed August 9, 2018. \"'I was born in Atlantic City, at the hospital there, and raised in Ocean City until I was 12 years old.' Burnley explained his family moved to Pennsylvania when he was 12 due to an increase in taxes at the shore town.\"</ref> At 16, he became home schooled and quickly passed the GED requirement. At 21 he moved to [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]], where he became a roommate of former Breaking Benjamin bass player Jonathan Price. During his early teen years he taught himself to play guitar by listening to [[Nirvana (band)|Nirvana]]'s ''[[Nevermind]]'' (he cites Nirvana as his biggest influence). Before Breaking Benjamin was formed, Ben Burnley earned money playing cover songs, mixed in with his own in various coffee houses and other all age venues mostly with local neighboring musicians.\n\n===Breaking Benjamin===\n{{Main|Breaking Benjamin}}\n\nIn 1998, Burnley and former lead guitarist Aaron Fink, got together (along with Nick Hoover and Chris Lightcap) and started the band \"Breaking Benjamin.\" Eventually, Ben wanted to try something different and went out to California to try some new material. The other three members went on to form the band [[Lifer (band)|Strangers With Candy]] (later known as [[Lifer (band)|Lifer]]). They recruited old friend Mark Klepaski to play bass and he joined in, and shortly after, Nick Hoover was asked to leave the band.\n\nIn 1999, Ben Burnley moved back to Pennsylvania, and started a band called \"Plan 9\" with drummer Jeremy Hummel. Originally, the band was a three-piece. The lineups consisted of Benjamin on vocals and electric guitar, Jeremy on drums, and Jason Davoli on bass. Plan 9 would occasionally open for Lifer at home shows. During one show, Ben said \"Thank you, we're Breaking Benjamin,\" thus reclaiming the name from 1998. Later on, Mark left Lifer and found himself playing bass for Breaking Benjamin. Lifer continued going through struggles, and months later, Aaron Fink sat in for a set with Benjamin. Finally, Aaron left Lifer, and was offered a spot in Ben Burnley's band, and they became a four-piece.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shallowbay.com/forum/faq.php?faq=section_2#faq_question_2_2 |title=Breaking Benjamin Underground |publisher=The Shallow Bay |date= |accessdate=2011-11-02}}</ref>\n\n===Collaborations===\nBurnley has lent his vocal and songwriting talents to other acts as well. He has performed numerous live duets with fellow alternative metal bands such as [[Three Days Grace]], [[Evans Blue]] and [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]]. He made a guest spot on a special remix of The Drama Club's single \"Brand New Day.\" He also co-wrote the [[Red (band)|Red]] hit song \"[[Innocence & Instinct|Shadows]]\" and [[Madam Adam]] song \"Forgotten\". Burnley has collaborated with former Three Days Grace singer [[Adam Gontier]] on a song titled \"The End of the Day\" (yet to be released).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harddriveradio.com/dirt/thursday-jan-17|work=Harddrive|accessdate=2013-04-21|title=DdirtRockforrecovery}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBurnley has several [[phobia]]s, a fact that inspired the title of their 2006 album ''[[Phobia (Breaking Benjamin album)|Phobia]]''. ''Phobia''{{'}}s cover, which depicts a winged man hovering above the ground, represents Burnley's [[fear of flying]], which has prevented Breaking Benjamin from touring outside the United States and Canada in the past.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://123/www.jodileib.com/TalkItOutSessions/BreakingBenjamin.html |title=Ben Burnley, Breaking Benjamin Interview on www.jodileib.com |publisher=Jodileib.com |date=November 22, 2004 |accessdate=2010-03-02 }}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However in May 2016, he and his band members travelled through ferry ship to Europe, and made their first musical tour outside of the US and Canada. Breaking Benjamin again toured Europe in 2017 successfully. Burnley also suffers from [[hypochondria]] and a [[fear of the dark]]. He says that he doesn't believe in a person's time to die and he wants to put off dying for as long as he possibly can, which is why he doesn't fly or even ride in a car unless it's necessary. He incorporates his phobias into his music on the album ''We Are Not Alone'' in the song \"Break My Fall,\" in which a pilot is heard over the music saying, \"Mayday, mayday. Request permission to land. I cannot control the plane. We are in danger of crashing.\"\n\nBurnley is an avid [[gamer|video gamer]], and conceived of the idea for Breaking Benjamin to write and record the song \"[[Blow Me Away]]\" for the soundtrack to ''[[Halo 2]]''. The song \"[[Polyamorous (Breaking Benjamin song)|Polyamorous]]\" is also featured on the games ''[[Run Like Hell (video game)|Run Like Hell]]'', ''[[WWE SmackDown! vs. Raw]]'' and ''[[WWE Day of Reckoning]]'' (along with their song \"Firefly\"). \"[[The Diary of Jane]]\" appears on ''[[NASCAR 07]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=12 maart 2008 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XVIMuoTt3N4 |title=Tour Gaming with Breaking Benjamin |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2010-03-02}}</ref>\n\nBurnley is a recovering alcoholic, admitting in an interview that he wanted to \"drink himself to death.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://listenin.org/interviews/archive/artists/Breaking+Benjamin/default.aspx |title=Breaking Benjamin|publisher=Listenin.org |accessdate=2011-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915062048/http://listenin.org/interviews/archive/artists/Breaking+Benjamin/default.aspx |archive-date=September 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> He says that he regrets ever drinking a drop of alcohol and is victim to [[Wernicke\u2013Korsakoff syndrome]] due to his past excessive drinking. ''[[Dear Agony]]'' was reported to be the first ever Breaking Benjamin record to be written by Burnley without the use of alcohol.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kory Grow |url=http://www.revolvermag.com/uncategorized/breaking-benjamins-benjamin-burnley-on-wet-brain-and-motorcycle-accide.html |title=Breaking Benjamin's Benjamin Burnley on Wet Brain and Motorcycle Accidents \u2013 Revolver Magazine |publisher=Revolvermag.com |date=May 10, 2010 |accessdate=2011-11-02}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Commons category|Benjamin Burnley}}\n{{Breaking Benjamin}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Burnley, Benjamin}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Alternative metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Alternative rock singers]]\n[[Category:American alternative rock musicians]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal guitarists]]\n[[Category:American heavy metal singers]]\n[[Category:American lyricists]]\n[[Category:American male guitarists]]\n[[Category:American male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American rock songwriters]]\n[[Category:American male songwriters]]\n[[Category:American tenors]]\n[[Category:Breaking Benjamin members]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Atlantic City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Ocean City, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:People from Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Post-grunge musicians]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n[[Category:Singers from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Songwriters from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Selinsgrove, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Hypochondriacs]]\n[[Category:Guitarists from Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "L.T.G", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benjamin_Burnley"}
